 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - John Beckwith, chairman of Premier Club to buy up social  security offices </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>John Beckwith, chairman of Premier Club to buy up social security offices </b><br><br><br><b><h2>24  July 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Major's tycoon covets welfare offices</h2><h3>Billion dollar man in takeover bid   </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Hencke</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>John Beckwith, chairman of the Premier Club, where wealthy business people pay up to &#163;100,000  to dine with John Major, has secured backing worth $1bn from a United States insurance company to buy  up Britain's social security offices.  <p>  <p>Confidential minutes of a meeting held with management advisers to the Social Security Secretary,  Peter Lilley, reveal that Mr Beckwith wants to buy all the social security property in England and  Wales on top of purchasing 58,000 Ministry of Defence homes in deals worth around &#163;2.5bn.  According to the minutes, the 49-year-old property tycoon - whose role in the Premier Club was  disclosed by the Observer this week - says that it is a "good time to be planning a transaction of  this nature and size, because of the large amount of capital available globally for major deals." The  sale of the social security offices, including the headquarters at Quarry House, Leeds, and management  centres in Newcastle upon Tyne, will offer huge opportunities for property developers.  <p>  <p>Some of the more lucrative high street locations could be resold and converted into up-market shops  on condition the developer provides alternative accommodation on council estates, where more people  are on benefit.  <p>  <p>Ministers have denied that any bid for the social security offices had been made, and have defended  the short-listing of a consortium headed by Beckwith Capital Partners for the MoD estate in May.  <p>  <p>Yesterday, after being challenged in the House of Commons over the Observer story by the Labour MP  Peter Hain, John Major said: "No one can buy access to ministers, no one is promised favours."  <p>  <p>The minutes of the meeting between Mr Beckwith and two fellow directors and three directors of  Deloitte and Touche, management consultants, reveal that Mr Beckwith is running two consortiums to buy  large swathes of the Whitehall estate. Deloitte and Touche confirmed the meeting had taken place. The  planned bid for the social security offices, which will be put up for sale next year to raise at least  &#163;750m for the Government, is under Beckwith Property Fund Management with chartered surveyors  Richard Ellis and the United States insurance company AIG. The minutes say: "AIG is one of the largest  insurance companies in the world with gross assets over one billion dollars."  <p>  <p>They show that Mr Beckwith has already told the Department of Social Security that are "more  interested in the DSS opportunity. The option of doing a deal in a single one-off transaction is more attractive than phasing it over  time or splitting it into packages. A partnership arrangement, probably including an FM (facilities  management) company, is favoured."  <p>  <p>The minutes also disclose that Mr Beckwith was highly critical of Defence Secretary Michael  Portillo's handling of its approach to buy the MoD estate with another consortium involving Hodge plc  and Lehman Brothers (BHL), an American investment bank.  <p>  <p>The MoD was said to be running the sale badly, with several bidding consortiums breaking apart and  a poorly thought out shortlisting process.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
