 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Ian Botham loses his libel case against Imran  Khan</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ian Botham loses his libel case against Imran Khan</b><br><br><br><b><h2>1 August  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Botham libel case "an exercise in futility"</h2><h3>Imran says losing would have left  him bankrupt  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Vivek Chaudhary</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Imran Khan yesterday described the libel case brought against him by Ian Botham and Allan Lamb as a  "complete exercise in futility", adding that the whole thing had been a nightmare.  <p>  <p>Imran, speaking on CNN television a few minutes after his High Court victory, said: "It's a  complete exercise in futility, it's a ridiculous situation to be involved in a case like this when I  have something more important in Pakistan."  <p>  <p>He also said he would have been bankrupt had he lost the case. "I had no money left, it's so  expensive this libel, because most of the money I made from cricket I gave to the cancer hospital. The  rest would have gone today." The former Pakistan captain said the end of the case would allow him to  concentrate on his Justice Movement, the political group he founded in Pakistan.  <p>  <p>Imran again reiterated his claim that he never called anyone a cheat and that he was trying to  defend the Pakistan cricket team.  "I found there was no one defending the team so I jumped into the fray, trying to defend my team,  saying ball tampering is a huge issue and no one understands it and the Pakistanis are not cheating.  <p>  <p>"Don't ask me how I have ended up in this, but it's been a nightmare." Imran said he wrote to both  Botham and Lamb saying there was a misunderstanding when the India Today article appeared in which he  was quoted as calling them racist and lower class. "What I could not do was apologise for something I  had not done."  <p>  <p>Imran's solicitor, Howard Cohen, said his client would only have to pay a small proportion of the  costs.  <p>  <p>With Imran being whisked away by friends and family for a private celebration, Ian Botham was left  counting the cost of the two-week trial, insisting he had no regrets.  <p>  <p>The former England all-rounder said: "How can one regret it? I fought for my dignity and honesty  and one thing no one can ever accuse me of is being a racist. To call me a cheat. I find it amazing."  Botham said he was confused and astonished at the verdict. His former England colleague, Allan  Lamb, said: "The jury has got to make their decision and you have got to accept that."  <p>  <p>The dispute which resulted in the costly High Court action can be traced back to the summer of  1992, when the Pakistan cricket team arrived in England and allegations of cheating were being made  against them. The trial also saw the darker side of cricket being publicly exposed, with successive  players, including England captain Mike Atherton, admitting that ball tampering was part and parcel of  the game.  <p>  <p>The 1992 series, which Pakistan won 2-1, was described in court as savage and ugly, with  accusations of cheating being made by the tabloid press against Pakistan's two fast bowlers - the  current captain Wasim Akram and Waqar Younis.  <p>  <p>There were headlines like 'Paki cheats' and claims that the two, and previous Pakistan bowlers, had  regularly been tampering with the ball, by either picking the seam or scratching it on one side, to  make it swing more than it should. Some even suggested that this contributed to their world cup win  against England months earlier.  <p>  <p>The controversy resurfaced in 1994 when Imran admitted in a biography that he had scratched a ball  with a bottle top while playing for Sussex in a county match.  <p>  <p>Imran claimed in court that he was merely trying to highlight the unacceptable face of ball  tampering which he claimed had gone on in English cricket for years. Picking the seam with your  fingers or applying a bit of grease to one side of the ball was "tacitly accepted" but using outside  agents like bottle tops was over-stepping the limit.  "That's what I would call cheating," Imran confessed while giving evidence during the trial.  <p>  <p>Lamb and Botham responded swiftly to the Imran biography.  In May 1994, Lamb contributed an article to the Sun newspaper in which Imran was accused of  cheating and teaching Younis and Akram how to tamper with the ball.  This was followed by an article in the Daily Mirror in which Botham called for a full investigation  into Imran's ball tampering, and demanded his resignation from the International Cricket Conference.  <p>  <p>Less than a week later, Imran, who by now had retired from Test cricket and was concentrating on  building a cancer hospital in his native Lahore, responded by giving an interview to the Sun.  <p>  <p>Headlined 'World's greatest bowlers have all doctored the ball' he once again claimed that ball  tampering was an accepted part of English cricket. With England-Pakistan cricket relations at an  all-time low, matters deteriorated when extracts from an interview given by Imran to India Today  magazine appeared in the British press.  <p>  <p>He was quoted as calling Botham and Lamb racists, claiming that their approach to the whole issue  of ball tampering was "irrational" because they were lower class and uneducated.  It was this interview that led Botham and Lamb to bring their libel action against Imran while  Botham alone was suing him for the Sun article, claiming that Imran had called him a cheat.  <p>  <p>At times the trial became bogged down with technical details of what happens to a cricket ball when  it is scratched, has its seam picked or lipsalve is applied. The issue of what constitutes cheating in  cricket became crucial. At the end of the day it was a tussle between two cricket giants with egos to  match who refused to back down once heated words were exchanged over what is cheating in their sport.  <p>  <p>Perhaps the most poignant comment of the costly trial came from Allan Lamb's wife Lindsay.  Giving evidence midway through the trial and referring to an earlier libel action her husband was  involved in, she said: "I had four days of that and this is another seven days I have been listening  to balls."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Botham libel case: the leading players</b>  <p>  <p>Imran Khan, aged 43, made his Test debut for Pakistan against England in 1971 but returned to  Worcester Royal Grammar school after the tour. He went up to Oxford in 1973 and captained the side the  following year. He had an outstanding career as an all-rounder, first for Worcestershire and then  Sussex, as well as leading Pakistan to Test and World Cup success, the last in 1992 when they beat an  England side, which included Ian Botham, in the final by 22 runs.  <p>  <p>Throughout his career he maintained a playboy's lifestyle. He married Jemima Goldsmith last year  and embarked on a political career, challenging the mainstream Pakistani parties on a platform of  anti-corruption. Ian Botham, 40, made his Test debut against Australia in 1977. Nicknamed 'Beefy', his  career as an all-rounder for Somerset and latterly Durham see-sawed as dramatically as his flamboyant  temperament.  <p>  <p>He resigned the England captaincy in July, 1981 with England one down in the Test series against  Australia. England went on to win the series 3-1 with Botham scoring 149 in the third Test at  Headingley, taking five for 11 at Edgbaston, and adding 118 in the fifth Test at Old Trafford to  secure victory in 'Botham's Ashes'.  <p>  <p>He has walked the length of Britain for charity, and admitted that he had smoked cannabis, which  brought him a brief Test ban.  He retired in 1993.  <p>  <p>Allan Lamb, aged 42, was born in South Africa, where he made his first class debut for Western  Province in 1972.  A batsman, he settled in Northamptonshire, the county he played for first in 1978, becoming captain  in 1989. After the qualification period, he made his Test debut for England in 1982.  <p>  <p>A renowned prankster, as is Botham, he was fined &#163;5,000 by the Test and County Cricket Board  after accusing Pakistani bowlers of ball tampering in 1992. The following year he was sued for libel  by former Northants and Pakistani paceman Sarfraz Nawaz. The case was settled out of court, but  effectively ended his England career after 79 Tests, three as captain. He retired from first class  cricket this year.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Guide to ball tampering</b>  <p>  <p>Conventional swing - By applying something like sweat (which is legal) to one side of the ball, the air moves faster  across the shiny side and drags on the dull side, thereby giving extra swing. It is illegal, however,  to apply hair oil or lip salve to one side of the ball to give it extra shine.  <p>  <p>Reverse swing - A method pioneered in the Indian sub-continent. If a bowler applies lots of sweat to one side of  the ball and the other side is left as dry and rough as possible then this makes the ball swing in  reverse to its normal motion. It is illegal to tamper with the rough side using bottle tops, nails or  gouging with finger nails.  <p>  <p>Increased reverse swing - By lifting up the quarter seam and packing it with something like dirt helps make the ball even  heavier on one side, therby increasing the reverse swing. Some bowlers remove the quarter seam, which  also causes extra swing. Both these practices are illegal.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
