 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Sandy Anderson, a former British Rail terminal manager, is set  to reap a bonus of £39.9m from the sale of his train leasing company </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sandy Anderson set to reap £39.9m from the  sale of his train leasing company </b><br><br><br><b><h2>2 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The 'fattest  cat' who is set to make £40m in just seven months  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Keith Harper</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>A former British Rail terminal manager, Sandy Anderson, was last night set to reap a bonus of  &#163;39.9m made in only seven months from the sale of his train leasing company, in what was  described by Labour as "the biggest privatisation scandal of them all."  <p>  <p>Mr Anderson, managing director of the Porterbrook leasing company, and three directors, will become  multi-millionaires if Stagecoach, the bus and train operator, gets official clearance for its  &#163;475m bid for the company. They were immediately nicknamed 'fat cat controllers' by Labour's shadow chancellor,  Gordon Brown.  <p>  <p>During the seven-month period, Porterbrook has seen its original stake of &#163;15m increase by  more than 500 per cent to &#163;80m.  <p>  <p>With three colleagues - finance director Ray Cork, engineering director Tim Gilberts, and chairman,  Peter Watson - Mr Anderson holds 15.76 per cent of the company. Their share was valued at  &#163;74.86m, but Mr Anderson had the lion's share at 8.4 per cent.  <p>  <p>Mr Anderson started out as terminal manager for BR's container handling subsidiary, Freightliner.  He is a former director of the leasing company, TIP, for which he worked for 12 years. He was then  managing director of a trailer rental company for six years. He has been at Porterbrook for two years.  <p>  <p>Mr Anderson's other colleagues will receive lesser benefits. Mr Cork's share of the company is 3.88  per cent. He will get &#163;18.43m; Mr Gilbert's share is 2.48 per cent. He will receive &#163;11.78m;  Mr Watson's share is one per cent. His stake is valued at &#163;4.75m. When their company was set up  last November, they and the rest of the 49 staff put up &#163;15m of the &#163;75m initial equity,  with the rest financed by the merchant bank, Charterhouse, and bank debt. Porterbrook is the smallest of  the three companies which own rolling stock run by train operating companies. Its total purchase was  financed by &#163;527m of venture capital. The Government has guaranteed 80 per cent of its revenue  for eight years.  <p>  <p>City sources last night said that the pay-outs were unprecedented. But they pointed out that huge  sums have been made from selling off the public utilities.  <p>  <p>Labour called for an investigation by the Commons public accounts committee and said that further  disclosures would emerge in the aftermath of the break-up of British Rail.  The shadow chancellor said that the scale of Porterhouse's profits showed BR had been "massively  undervalued" by the Government and the managers were now cashing in at the taxpayer's expense.  <p>  <p>BR was originally valued at &#163;6.4bn, but the core of its operation, Railtrack, was eventually sold off for only &#163;1.9bn. The Department of Transport  said last night that the rise in the value of Porterbrook was a mark of the success of privatisation.  <p>  <p>Porterbrook, which leases 3,774 trains to 16 rail companies, has not ordered new rolling stock  since it was set up.  <p>  <p>Stagecoach, which entered the rail business when it took over South West Trains from BR in  February, has made it clear that it will withdraw the offer for Porterbrook if it is referred to the  Monopolies and Mergers Commission.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
