 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Sandy Anderson, a former British Rail terminal manager, is set  to reap a bonus of £39.9m from the sale of his train leasing company </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sandy Anderson set to reap £39.9m from the  sale of his train leasing company </b><br><br><br><b><h2>3 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Jitters galore for 'fat controllers' at Labour's windfall tax resolve  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Patrick Donovan</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The tens of millions of pounds' profit made by the 'fat controllers' who sold off their former  British Rail subsidiary just seven months after privatisation will only strengthen Labour's resolve to  clamp down on the utilities. Already the front-bench Treasury team is well advanced in its plans to  levy a &#163;3bn to &#163;5bn windfall tax on former state-controlled companies. And fund managers who have met the team lately are becoming  uncomfortably aware that the levy may be far more wide-ranging than expected.  <p>  <p>Until now there has been an expectation that this windfall tax will be Labour's retribution for the  excesses of the water and electricity suppliers. It is the shares of these companies which have been  overhung from what is fast developing into pre-election jitters.  <p>  <p>But there are signs that the profit levy is to be extended to all privatised utilities, according  to City sources who have bent the ears of Mr Blair's team. Already the spectre of the tax, which was  first announced in 1993, is thought to have contributed to a 16 per cent underperformance by utilities  over the last year. Now it appears that election fears are by no means fully factored into share  prices. Ironically, the impact of any reassessment could be far less marked on the traditional victims  - the electricity and water companies.  <p>  <p>Instead, it could hit far harder companies such as British Gas and big generators National Power  and PowerGen. Given the controversy over British Rail, Railtrack has also been regarded as a target.  But sources say Labour is also running its slide rule over other transport companies, such as AB Ports  and BAA. British Telecom and even British Airways could feel the taxman's bite.  <p>  <p>Alas for the Fat Cats, it looks as though not even an accountant's sleight of hand will shelter  them from the full brunt of the windfall clampdown. This tax will be retrospective, a levy on the  bumper profits already made by utilities let loose into the private sector. In essence, they will now  have to pay through the nose for all those hundreds of thousands of job losses privatised firms  traditionally shed to drive profit growth.  <p>  <p>One of the biggest questions is how the tax will be levied. Labour has played its cards very close  to its chest. But the City increasingly believes Labour will take the view that share price is the  best measure and will be likely to weight the tax on market capitalisation. Hence the costs are likely  to fall much more heavily on the largest utilities rather than the smaller electricity and  water-distribution companies. The picture is further confused because so many of these have already  been swallowed up in takeovers or have doled back hefty lumps of cash to investors in the form of  special dividends. Other unresolved issues include the debate over whether companies which have given  rebates to customers should be treated more leniently.  <p>  <p>Even using a rough rule of thumb, it would seem that if Labour seriously wishes to raise &#163;5bn  by levying a tax on a market capitalisation basis, BT will be hardest hit, with a potential bill of  more than &#163;1.3bn. Next down the line is British Gas, with a possible &#163;500m bill. National Power comes in at just under &#163;370m and  BAA at nearly &#163;300m. Other companies facing a big knock will be PowerGen, Scottish Power and  National Grid.  <p>  <p>On this basis, a number of the water and electricity companies that have scandalised public opinion  by paying such over-inflated directors' salaries and share options will remain relatively unscathed.  Unfair, perhaps. But it seems the best way forward if Labour actually wants to achieve its goal of  injecting &#163;1bn back into employment and training schemes in its first year of office.  Sandy Anderson, the former British Rail terminal manager who trousered nearly &#163;40m this week  from his rail sale could well be the last of the privatisation 'fat cats'.  Big utilities will undoubtedly be hard hit by the increasingly pre-election jitters.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </