 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Johnson becomes the first man to win Olympic gold in both the  200m and 400m </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Johnson becomes the first man to win Olympic gold in both the  200m and 400m </b><br><br><br><b><h2>2 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Olympics: The  world bows to Johnson's double  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Stephen Bierley</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>They came. They saw. He conquered. Michael Johnson not only won the 200m in Atlanta last night to  complete an historic Olympic double with his 400m title; he also shattered his own world record of  19.66sec with a startling time of 19.32sec.  <p>  <p>Namibia's Frankie Fredericks, silver medallist in the 100m, had been thought of as a threat, having  beaten Johnson at Bislett last month, but he came nowhere near. Fredericks was second again but some  four metres behind in 19.68sec. Trinidad's Ato Bolden was third in 19.80sec.  <p>  <p>Marie-Jose Perec, the darling of the French, pre-empted Johnson's feat, becoming only the second  woman to achieve the double, after the American Valerie Brisco-Hooks 12 years ago. For two-thirds of  the race it seemed that Jamaica's Merlene Ottey might finally win an Olympic gold medal but Perec,  finishing superbly, was ultimately an easy winner.  <p>  <p>The United States maintained its tradition in the men's 400m hurdles with the gold going to the  world champion Derrick Adkins. Zambia's Samuel Matete, the silver medal winner in Gothenburg last  year, again came second. Kelly Holmes may be suffering from a hairline fracture of her left leg but  her chances of winning a 1500m Olympic medal to add to her world championship silver last year appear  to be increasing every time she runs. Yesterday she won her heat in 4min 5.88sec, conserving her  energies in the earlier part of the race and then positioning herself perfectly for the drive to the  line. And her hopes of a medal appeared to be considerably improved when Hassiba Boulmerka of Algeria,  the reigning champion, went out in the opening heat.  <p>  <p>Boulmerka had just gone through the bell when she stumbled and veered out sharply to the right. She  was unable immediately to negotiate the bend and completely lost touch with the other 11 runners. Her  chances of qualifying were gone - there always remained the possibility of a protest, but her coach  did not sound optimistic.  <p>  <p>Holmes's heat was not without its incident either. The British champion managed to stay out of  trouble when Kenya's Naomi Mugo went crashing to the track. Mugo was reinstated and the Romanian  Catalina Gheoghiu disqualified. Previously Ireland's Sonia O'Sullivan had dropped out in the heats  while Maria Mutola of Mozambique did not enter the event because of illness. Both had been among the  favourites for a medal. Immediately after the semi-final Holmes went straight off to have her ankle  put in ice.  <p>  <p>Earlier in the week, after the second round, she revealed she had a hairline crack just above her  left ankle. She now needs pain-killing injections before racing but has stated her absolute  determination to continue, no matter what the damage.  <p>  <p>In the men's 1500m final in Seoul Peter Elliott won the silver medal while suffering from a groin  injury. Elliott had a pain killing injection and after the Olympics had to spend two months in bed and  experienced long-term damage. Noureddine Morceli, the overwhelming favourite to win the men's 1500m  title tomorrow, the same day as the women's final, easily won his semi-final heat, accelerating from  third place just before the final bend and leaving everyone for dead.  <p>  <p>Morceli finished a thoroughly disappointing seventh in Barcelona four years ago but has dominated  the event ever since. His winning time yesterday was 3.32.88. The rising Moroccan Hicham El Garroudj  looked a distinct threat with an impressive victory in the other semi-final. Britain's John Mayock,  seventh in Morceli's heat in 3.34.55, qualified as a fastest loser.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
