 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - RUC decision to reroute apprentice boys' parade angers loyalists </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>RUC decision to reroute apprentice boys' parade angers loyalists  </b><br><br><br><b><h2>5 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The long march from Drumcree</h2>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Sharrock</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Ulster's favourite cry of 'No Surrender!' will echo from the walled city of Derry this coming  weekend across centuries of bloody history and Northern Ireland when the apprentice boys celebrate  Ireland's most famous victory of Protestantism over Catholicism.  <p>  <p>It was the apprentice boys who coined the perennial phrase when they slammed shut the gates of the  City of Derry against the approaching forces of James, Catholic pretender to the English throne, in  December 1688.  <p>  <p>After an 11-month siege the apprentice boys were finally relieved by Mountjoy in August the  following year. At Derry, Aughrim and the Boyne, the Jacobites were routed by William of Orange.  <p>  <p>To this day, Ulster Protestants celebrate it as a victory for religious liberty and the defeat of  popery (while ironists prefer to recall that the Pope supported William against James, who was the  ally of Rome's enemy France). 'No Surrender!' drops like a freshly-minted coin from the mouths of  every new generation of Unionist leaders.  <p>  <p>At Drumcree last month, when Orangemen faced riot police and Army troops across barbed wire and  Northern Ireland threatened to topple once more down the dark funnel of violence, it was the  expression most on the lips of militant Protestants intent on upholding their cultural right to parade  down a predominantly Catholic road in the Loyalist citadel of Portadown. But Derry - or Londonderry as  it is officially called - is different these days. The majority Catholic population has held the reins  of power in the Maiden City for a generation and the Protestants have mostly moved out, across the  River Foyle to the east bank of the Waterside.  <p>  <p>In 1969 it was the apprentice boys' annual parade along the walls of the city which precipitated  the arrival of British troops in Northern Ireland's streets as civil law and order began to crumble.  The serious rioting which erupted in Derry's Bogside spread like a bushfire to Belfast. Last year, for  the first time since 1969, the apprentice boys were allowed back on to the walls. There was more  violent opposition, but nothing on the scale of a quarter of a century earlier. And the ceasefires  were holding. In 1996 Northern Ireland looks back with sadness and nostalgia on its year of peace and  forward to the coming weekend with more fear that confrontation between Nationalists and Unionists in  Derry could once again ignite the fuse of sectarian violence.  <p>  <p>In the aftermath of Drumcree there is a vicious spirit set loose, with churches and Orange halls,  Protestant and Catholic businesses and homes the targets of attack from 'The Other Sort'. The kernel  of hope is that, unlike at Drumcree, the two local groups at loggerheads over the route of the march  are at least negotiating with one another. They have set a deadline of Wednesday however, and the  ground between them is still very wide. On one side stands the apprentice boys' Club, the smallest of  three 'loyal orders' (the others being the Orange and the Royal Black Institutions) with an estimated  12,000 members. While independent, many of its members are also Orangemen.  <p>  <p>The main purpose of the organisation is to hold parades to commemorate the two principal events of  the Siege of Derry, as they have done since the late 17th century.  <p>  <p>The heart of the organisation is the eight Parent Clubs, six of which are named after leaders of  the siege: Baker, Browning, Campsie, Mitchelburne, Murray and Walker, the other two being the  apprentice boys of Derry Club and the No Surrender Club. Between them they have a membership of up to  500 men, but there are a further 200 branch clubs across Northern Ireland, Scotland, England, the  Irish republic and Canada.  <p>  <p>While most apprentice boys live outside Derry the organisation's structure means that all decisions  taken on their behalf are made by those members living in the city.  <p>  <p>The other side is represented by the Bogside Residents Group, which does not want the apprentice  boys to parade along that section of the city's walls which overlooks their district lest the  exclusively Protestant organisation gives offence.  <p>  <p>Unless the two sides can resolve their differences and arrive at a reasonable compromise by  Wednesday Northern Ireland will be back at Drumcree, so to speak. The optimists are swearing until  they are blue in the face that, after peering over the brink last month, the divided people of  Northern Ireland have the common sense to pull back.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
