 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Doctors reveal a selective  abortion has been carried out on a woman carrying twins </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Doctors reveal a selective abortion has been carried out on a  woman carrying twins </b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>What do you think about the woman carrying twins who wants to abort one of them?</h2><h3>  Here, a birth control expert, a twin expecting twins and a twin whose other half died at birth express their own opinions   </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Lucy Manning</b><br><br><br>      <p>  <p><b>The expert</b>  <p>  <p>Ann Furedi is director of the Birth Control Trust.  <p>  <p>There is a lot of high moral posturing about the rights and wrongs of this issue. It is important  to remember that no woman undertakes an abortion lightly, particularly in these circumstances. The  fact that this woman knows a termination may threaten the entire pregnancy means it is a serious  decision and reflects the strength of feeling she has about how intolerable it would be to have twins.  <p>  <p>This decision can be seen in a positive light; she is giving one foetus the potential of life  rather than ending the pregnancy entirely. If she had done that, it would have been an uncontroversial  issue.  <p>  <p>People talk about the effect on this woman's future mental health if she wonders about the baby who  was not born. However, you have to consider her mental health if she were forced to carry on with the  pregnancy. The twin argument does not really figure. The baby will simply be born, like most, as a  singleton. There is no real difference between this and a mother who has an abortion, denying her  other children a sibling. There is also no difference between this and when a twin miscarries.  <p>  <p>Everything depends on what we choose to class as ethical. It is unethical to force a woman to  continue with a pregnancy she finds intolerable, just because a third party disapproves. The only  justification required is to square it with her own conscience.  <p>  <p>People are offering her money to keep the child, but the reasons for abortion are rarely just  financial. This woman has thought hard about her decision and I'd be surprised if she were swayed by  the offer of money.   <p>  <p><b>The pregnant twin</b>  <p>  <p>Alison Chapman, 34, is a twin and is expecting twins in November.<p>I definitely think there is a  special bond between twins. Although they are people in their own right, they are part of a whole unit  and you can't get away from that. I am 34 years old, but I still feel it. There is no way I would want  to abort one twin.  <p>  <p>It's my first pregnancy, so I don't know what to expect, but being a twin, I am not worried about  the physical side of having to care for two babies. Initially, I am sure it will be more tiring, but  when they're older there are advantages because they can amuse each other. Of course it will be a lot  harder financially. If I were on my own, I'd be more worried, but I have a very supportive partner.  <p>  <p>I am not opposed to abortion and I believe it is not a decision any woman takes lightly. But if  this woman is honest with the remaining child, I think her decision may have a major psychological  impact later on. It will be difficult for her, because if the child has problems, she may think:  should I have chosen the other one? If she carried both and put one up for adoption, the same would  apply.  <p>  <p>I feel very sorry for her, having to cope with all this attention at what must be a very stressful  time anyway. It must be so difficult, choosing one child over the other. Presumably the decision is  down to the doctor, which is better, I suppose, because as a mother, how do you decide? I have seen  the scans of my twins and they are real people, I think of them as part of each other.  <p>  <p>People always ask what it's like to be a twin, but it's hard to say because I have never known  anything else. I couldn't imagine life without my twin.   <p>  <p><b>The surviving twin</b>  <p>  <p>Senga Callum (not her real name), aged 40, was a twin. Her brother was stillborn.  <p>  <p>I have always felt the presence of my twin, but it is only in the past few years that I have really  been affected by it, especially since having children of my own.  <p>  <p>Last November, I read an article about twins and there was a small paragraph about people who had  never known their twin. I got in touch with the Lone Twin Network and it was a big relief to talk to  someone; I bawled for 20 minutes.  <p>  <p>The group gets together once a year and they are people who have never resolved their feelings of  loneliness, who are always thinking there should be another person with them. One facet of them is  wrong and missing. I was fascinated because I had never known that others were feeling the same thing  as me.  <p>  <p>I was born before my brother and I felt I was a very selfish person, fighting to get out. We were  both very heavy and he didn't have enough oxygen. I've always felt very guilty, as if I survived at  his expense. My mother is in her seventies and I was worried she would die before I could ask her  questions about my twin. It was never a secret, but I wanted to know what he looked like, what his  name was, what colour hair he had and whether she saw him. I knew I'd get upset and I wasn't sure  she'd understand that. My mum mentioned the story about this woman wanting an abortion. I didn't  really want to discuss it with her because I knew I'd get upset. I think this woman needs to have a  big think about what she is doing. She needs to talk to people who have lost a twin. She should be  made aware of the anger that will be directed at her by the survivor. That twin will feel really  guilty and that's a huge responsibility to give a child.  <p>  <p>I'm sure it is hellish having twins and I feel for her, but the decision is bigger than she  realises and she'll have to live with it for the rest of her life. Although I have three sisters,  there is still a sense of loss; he was a brother, he was special.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
