 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - The government lifts the Post Office's letter  monopoly</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>The government lifts the Post Office's letter monopoly</b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 August  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Minister acts to break postal strikes</h2><h3>Firms shun chance to step in  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Seumas Milne</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The Government last night confirmed its intention of moving against striking public service workers  with the announcement that it was lifting the Post Office's letter monopoly from midnight, as the  Communication Workers' Union announced four new 24-hour postal strikes on top of today's planned  walkout. In a move calculated to raise the political stakes in the escalating industrial disputes in  Royal Mail and the London Underground, Ian Lang, the Trade and Industry Secretary, said he was  breaking the monopoly on mail costing less than &#163;1 for a month.  <p>  <p>He warned that if strikes continued, he would extend the suspension for a further three months.  <p>  <p>Last week, Mr Lang revealed that the Government was considering new curbs on trade unions in  response to the outbreak of strikes, including the possibility of making unions financially liable for  disruption to public services.  <p>  <p>Yesterday's announcement came shortly after Alan Johnson, CWU general secretary, had declared that  Royal Mail's refusal to reopen negotiations over its plans for American-style 'teamworking' had left  the union's executive "very little alternative" to calling further 24-hour stoppages. These will run  from 3am to 3am on 14 August, 22 August, 30 August and 2 September.  <p>  <p>Mr Johnson dismissed the withdrawal of the 156-year-old monopoly as a "bit of crude politicking by  the Conservatives, who believe it will earn them Brownie points with the public. I think they have  misjudged the public mood completely."  <p>  <p>He said people would see that the Government, which had failed to privatise the Post Office two  years ago, wanted the dispute to continue. Mr Lang countered with a pre-election revival of the  language of the early 1980s. He said it was "wholly unacceptable that a group of extremists within the  CWU are able to hold the country to economic ransom."  He called on "spineless" Labour to condemn the postal strikes, insisting his monopoly withdrawal  was essential to protect consumers.  <p>  <p>Last night, Labour - in contrast with its excoriation of the London Underground strikes - refused  to condemn the postal walkouts. Stephen Byers, Labour's employment spokesman, said: "We are not  playing politics with this dispute".  <p>  <p>The response from private courier companies to the business opportunities beckoning as a result of  Mr Lang's suspension of the letter monopoly were also disappointing from the Government's point of  view.  Andrew Fitzmaurice, business development director for the country's largest parcel carrier, TNT,  said he would be delighted to take over the Post Office's delivery business, but not on a temporary  basis.  UPS, the largest international package distribution outfit, confirmed it would "not step in and  offer a solution to the strike".  <p>  <p>Today's stoppage by the 130,000 delivery and sorting workers, the fourth since the end of June,  will test whether the uncertain leadership from the CWU over the past 10 days has weakened commitment  to the industrial action programme on the ground.  <p>  <p>Post Office managers yesterday renewed their call for the CWU to put the package negotiated at Acas  last month - which includes a procedure to introduce teamworking through local trials - out to a  ballot of the membership.  There were fears among some union sources that indecision by the CWU executive might lead to a  weakening in support.  <p>  <p>The last time the Royal Mail letter monopoly was fully suspended was during an all-out postal  strike from January to March 1971.  <p>  <p>In return for the exclusive state franchise - which dates from the introduction of the Penny Post  in 1840 - the Post Office is obliged to deliver to every address in the United Kingdom at a uniform  price. Post Office managers, the unions and Opposition politicians fear that a permanent suspension  would allow private firms to 'cherry pick' the most profitable routes, which currently subsidise  deliveries to remote areas. Estimates of the real cost of delivering a letter from London to remote  parts of Scotland range from &#163;4 to &#163;16.  <p>  <p>The CWU believes that Post Office managers' 'teamworking' proposals - they envisage dividing local  offices into competing groups, who would have to cover for each other and continously improve  performance - would mean extra work for a new basic of only &#163;211 a week, set postal worker  against postal worker and undermine the local influence of the union. Post Office managers - with the  Government standing behind them - are prepared to delay the introduction of such a 'flexible working'  system, but are determined to secure it in the medium-term as a basis for future productivity growth.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
