 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Beat-a-cheat hotline service attracts more than 1,500 calls on its first day </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Beat-a-cheat hotline service is launched attracting more than 1,500 calls on  its first day </b><br><br><br><b><h2>10 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>'Shop an employer' hotline</h2><h3>Lilley  brings forward new fraud informer scheme as Labour joins blitz on National Insurance swindles  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Vivek Chaudhary</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The Government is to launch a hotline for people who want to report dishonest employers, after its  line for exposing suspected benefit cheats attracted more than 12,000 calls in less than a week.  <p>  <p>Hundreds of calls were from people reporting cheating employers, motivating the Secretary of State,  Peter Lilley, to order his officials to bring forward the separate scheme, which has been under  consideration for some time. A spokesman for the Department of Social Security said last night that  the benefits hotline, which Mr Lilley launched amid a blaze of publicity last Monday, was revealing  "across the board fraud, which we are determined to stamp out".  <p>  <p>Many calls have concerned employers with small businesses, such as those in construction, and  involve National Insurance fraud, which costs an estimated &#163;170m a year.  <p>  <p>The move coincides with plans announced by the Labour Party to tackle National Insurance fraud by  tighter rules to identify phantom numbers. Launching its campaign, Labour accused ministers of failing  to take tough enough action to protect the public purse from criminals, who use some of the millions  of numbers in existence from people who have died, moved abroad, or whose accounts are redundant.  <p>  <p>Labour's social security spokesman, Henry McLeish, called for a task force to find out the extent  of abuse and make urgent recommendations for improving security.  <p>  <p>Mr McLeish said a Labour government would toughen up the procedure for issuing numbers to stop  fraudsters assuming another person's identity to apply for benefits or to obtain a number; match all  existing numbers to information held by other government departments, for example the Inland Revenue,  to ensure claims are valid; and run spot checks on inactive numbers to ensure they are not being  abused.  <p>  <p>A spokesman for the Department of Social Security said the benefits hotline had been receiving 250  calls an hour since opening on Tuesday. Information was being passed to social security fraud  investigating officers. "The quality of the information has been very good. In some cases we have even  been given the National Insurance numbers of people suspected of fraud." The 'beat-a-cheat' hotline  has for the first time since the 1980s pushed the issue of benefit fraud to the front of the political  agenda. Already, more than 4,000 civil servants are employed in special teams trying to track down an  estimated &#163;1bn a year wrongly paid out. The attack is being led by a new cabinet committee under  the direction of Mr Lilley and Michael Heseltine, the Deputy Prime Minister.  <p>  <p>There is a growing cross-party consensus that the attitude to fraud needs to change from passive  acceptance to an active drive to combat it. Bernard Crofton, who as director of housing in Hackney,  east London, launched a campaign against housing benefit fraud, said: "People who suspect fraud tend  to keep their heads down. First of all, life is easier if you do that, but also people are genuinely  nervous of challenging fraud and are frightened of being called a grass or a racist."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
