 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - The discovery of fossilised 'bacteria-like' structures in a  meteorite gives new clue to life on Mars </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Discovery of 'bacteria-like' structures in a meteorite gives new clue to life on Mars  </b><br><br><br><b><h2>7 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Meteorite fossil holds clue to life on Mars</h2><h3>  Scientists welcome discovery of bacteria-like structures in rock as one of most sensational in history   </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Nick Varley</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>We may not have been alone. The scientific world was buzzing with excitement last night as rumours  circulated of new evidence of life on Mars. Reports of the discovery of a fossil in meteorite rock  from the planet had academics and researchers waiting with bated breath for further details from the  National Aeronautics and Space Administration (Nasa) in the United States.  <p>  <p>Nasa said last night that its findings pointed to the possibility that "a primitive form of  microscopic life may have existed on Mars more than three billion years ago."  The scientists based their theory of life on Mars on an examination of a Martian meteorite that  landed on earth 13,000 years ago.  <p>  <p>Nasa administrator Daniel Goldin said: "I want everybody to know that we are not talking about  'little green men'. These are extremely small, single-cell structures that somewhat resemble bacteria  on Earth. There is no evidence or suggestion that any higher life form ever existed on Mars."  <p>  <p>Science magazine, the academic journal which was due to publish a paper on the work next week,  announced that it would bring forward publication to today.  But scientists who have debated the question of life on Mars for decades were struggling to wait  that long.  <p>  <p>Dr Monica Grady of the Natural History Museum said the findings, if correct, were some of the most  sensational in scientific history.  "It's entirely possible that very, very primitive organisms might have arisen," she said.  I'm not talking about ammonites or corals or anything like that but something incredibly primitive  such as micro-fossils from highly primitive organisms. It's absolutely fascinating to find these."  <p>  <p>Former Cambridge University physicist Fred Hoyle, who maintained in the early 1980s that there was  life on Mars when Nasa was insisting the planet was sterile, said: "I'd be very pleased if it was true  and what we published in the Eighties was right."  <p>  <p>But he struck a note of scepticism: "I have certain reservations. Considering Nasa is absolutely  avid to get funding from Congress, one has to be a bit suspicious.  It is within the realms of possibility but I think one has to be cautious - and I'm triply  cautious if it's the result I want. Nasa is fighting by any means it can to get money."  <p>  <p>Astronomer Patrick Moore said more evidence was needed. "For a long time we have known there was  once running water on Mars because we have seen the evidence of it. There has long been the theory  that life started there but died out.  "But for all that I still need to be convinced by hard evidence. It is still not confirmed that  these meteorites definitely came from Mars - though they are very similar in composition to what we  believe their make-up would be if they were.  I defer judgment. If it is proved that these do come from Mars and that they contain life, all it  proves is life can exist in these places but not that it still does or has evolved to significant  levels."  <p>  <p>The Nasa research centres on meteorites found in Antarctica in the 1980s as ice melted. It is  thought they are fragments of meteorites from Mars created when an asteroid collided with the planet  and deposited on earth. Analysis of the rock at the Natural History Museum has revealed remnants of  organic material, possibly from underground water reserves. Scientists have long suspected these  subterranean pools - feeding rivers whose dried-up beds can be seen on the surface of the planet -  could have supported life. But a mini-laboratory, sent to examine the surface 20 years ago, killed the  theory when it found no evidence to prove it.  <p>  <p>Now the discovery of a fossil would turn the conventional wisdom of the last 20 years on its head.  It would only indicate the existence of the most primitive life - and with the typical temperature  -23&#176;C and the poles capped by frozen carbon dioxide, it is impossible for anything to live there now.  But it would confirm for the first time that life has been supported by a planet other than earth.  <p>  <p>It would also give some basis for the fascination everyone from HG Wells to David Bowie has had  with the Red Planet for hundreds of years. Most famously Orson Welles caused panic in 1938 when a  radio broadcast of 'War of the Worlds' telling of a Martian invasion was taken as the truth by many  Americans who heard it.  <p>  <p>The facts to be revealed later today will be less dramatic but without question far more  significant.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
