<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Discovery of fossilised 'bacteria-like' structures in a
meteorite gives new clue to life on Mars </TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">
<A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Discovery of 'bacteria-like' structures in a meteorite gives new clue to life on Mars</b><br><br><br><b><h2>8 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Secrets of the Red Planet</h2><h3>As scientists claim that Fossil evidence indicates there have been life forms on Mars, we may have to come to terms with the fact that, after all the fiction, we really are not alone</h3>
<br>By <b>Ruaridh Nicoll</b><br><br>


<p>
<p>Bill Clinton ushered Daniel Goldin, his chief adviser on off-world matters into the Oval Office and
sat him down. Nasa's administrator wanted to brief the president and Al Gore on news that would soon
hit Earth with the power of a meteor - life had finally been found on Mars.
<p>
<p>Beyond the walls of the White House, America's cinema screens flickered with the violence of
Independence Day depicting the carnage brought by an invading alien horde. It was turning out to be
one of the stranger moments in Clinton's term.
<p>
<p>Goldin went public late on Tuesday, quashing more imaginative reactions. "I want everybody to know
that we are not talking about 'little green men'," he said. "These are extremely small, single-cell
structures that somewhat resemble bacteria on Earth. There is no evidence or suggestion that any
higher life form ever existed on Mars."
<p>
<p>But this was science, not science fiction, and the sensible were stirring with the news, excitment
spreading in antipation of the article which would cause the storm. The academic journal, Science, was
going to press and when it arrived late last night the news was as good as people had hoped. The
beauty was in the payoff: "We conclude there is evidence for primitive life on early Mars," the
authors wrote.
<p>
<p>In the White House, Clinton and Gore were said to be excited. Theories were collapsing, others
gaining strength, and scientific intrigue was at its most fitful. "We have evidence that life as we
know it is not unique to this planet," said Colin Pillinger of the Open University, with all the
weight due such a discovery.
<p>
<p>The emergence offers views of the start of the worlds. Back at the beginning of time in the deep,
dark horror of space, the Earth and Mars were beginning to cool. It was 4,500 million years ago and
the crusts were forming, volcanoes bursting through their thin surfaces. There are arguments about
where the water came from but it is clear that once here it would support life. Where life came from
provides its own mysteries.
<p>
<p>To look at Mars it is necessary to look at Earth. However life came to be, it was on earth as far
back as 3,500 million years ago, the tiny fossils showing up in some of the world's oldest stone.
Details are sketchy, over such periods of time a planet eats itself, swallowing its surface and
sending it back into the intense pressures of its interior before spitting it out again.
<p>
<p>"It's more likely life evolved on Earth than in space," said Graham Durant of Glasgow University's
Hunterian Museum, assuming that any life on Mars followed suit. But what was here, and what was added
from space over the eons by the constant stream of meteors that hit the earth? There is an argument
that says because space contains the basic building blocks of life - the amino acids within everything
living - that the life was delivered from outside.
<p>
<p>Two scientists who have helped construct this theory are Sir Fred Hoyle and Professor Chandra
Wickramasinghe, who started looking at the stuff that made up space in the early moments of the
science. "We were struggling to understand the intersteller dust," said Wickramasinghe about how they
began. After decades their conclusion was: "The universe must be teaming with life."
<p>
<p>Still the main theory is that out of the bubbling primordial soup, life received the spark which
caught and which has burned to this day. But even this makes academics uncomfortable. "What makes it
slightly worrying is the speed which it happened," said one scientist. Life in a mere 1,000 million
years.
<p>
<p>Eventually, of course, it led to humankind and the search into space. Astronomers have always been
fascinated by the Red Planet - at the end of the last century, Giovanni Schiaparelli thought he saw
canals on Mars built by sentinent beings. The chase was taken up by Percival Lowell who mapped a
criss-crossing network and decided there was an advanced civilisation across the way and that they
were desperate for water.
<p>
<p>By 1976 the US was in a position to check what was on the planet. Although an earlier Mariner
Mission had photographed it from space, the two Viking probes would actually land and use a
spectrometer to beam back analysis of the surface. The probes went in and took their readings, which
when transmitted to Earth caused enormous excitment which quickly faded into the dull realisation that
the probes said no, the planet was dead. The world, which had feared for its existence in the face of
aliens, almost seemed to fall into a state of loneliness. "It was the equivalent of somebody landing a
spacecraft in the middle of the Gobi desert and saying that there is no life on earth," said Douglas
Millard, assistant curator of the Science Museum in London.
<p>
<p>For Hoyle and Wickramasinghe the failure of the Viking probes knelled the death of the scientific
establishment's interest in their work. All talk of other life in the solar system was scoffed at and
research moved on to other things. For the scientists, a life's work being trashed was hard to bear.
"It came to the point where we were not getting listened to at meetings," said Wickramasinghe.
<p>
<p>But, back on Earth, scientists were busy collecting rubbish in the most pristine area of the
planet. While the Apollo moon landings are high on the list of the most dramatic events on history
they were also giving a perfect analysis of the makeup of the Moon. The Viking landings had done the
same for Mars. Now the scientists, as far as rock, dust and air goes, knew what was there.
<p>
<p>Bill Cassidy was battling the vicious Antartic weather as he and his team of American colleagues
embarked on a very strange Easter egg hunt. They were wandering the freezing wastes of the Allan
Hills looking for meteors from Mars. The idea that pieces of another planet could be on Earth had long
seemed absurd, a fantasy of the lunatic fringe. But then after the Apollo missions a meteor was proved
by analysis to have come from the Moon, its qualities matched material brought home by astronauts.
<p>
<p>The same went for Mars. Viking had sent back quality readings which allowed researchers to be sure
whether a piece of rock came from the distant planet. The team found a melon-sized piece of rock which
was quickly dispatched back to Houston.
<p>
<p>The process by which the rock had found its way to earth was a amazing. About 15 million years ago
a giant asteroid ploughed into Mars, cutting into the planet's surface and throwing up vast amounts of
the surface. One chunk, ALH84001, found itself floating around in space. It stayed there until about
13,000 years ago when the Earth's gravity grabbed and pulled it in and it buried deep into the Allan
Hills' ice.
<p>
<p>Back at Houston the rock was split up and sent around the globe to be analysed by every scientist
who had an interest. "The strange thing is that it seems to have been forgotten about," said
Pillinger. But finally they started to test for organic materials and something unexpected turned up:
"A number of minerological features observed in the rock, [that] may be evidence of ancient Martian
micro-organisims."
<p>
<p>The scientists were keen to stamp on suggestions that this was any proof that life is seeded from
the heavens or, in some cases, that this was proof of anything at all. "If, after much more
investigation, it proves to be true that life did - or does - exist on Mars then that is a truly
amazing discovery," said one. "It also should be pointed out that the critters were buried under rock
almost 3.6 million years ago."
<p>
<p>Mars is a hell of a place. For a third of the year sandstorms blanket the surface, the poles are a
mixture of permanently frozen ice and carbon dioxide, and even at its best the temperature rarely
rises above minus 25 degrees.
<p>
<p>But there is a group of scientists who have been discovering life in the strangest places.
Biologists were shocked to find life close to the ocean floor, near the mouths of volcanoes. Down
there the pressure is extreme, the temperatures well over 100 degrees and there is none of the
sunshine that makes the rest of us glow. "The essential ingredient is water," said Millard.
<p>
<p>Quite apart from their size, our little neighbours have a couple of other problems. Many scientists
believe that if they were alive, they have long since gone. Although there is still hope that they can
survive underground or near some of the planet's volcanoes, looking across the homeland now seems a
little bleak.
<p>
<p>Of course, to find out for sure American's cash-strapped space agency will have to send some
missions out there and they have quite a programme lined up. There have been a number of suggestions,
which no scientists will put their names to, that Nasa might be after funding.
<p>
<p>After years of being attacked Hoyle is urging caution while saying that if the claims are true it
is wonderful. Wickramasinghe was less charitable, hoping that those who attacked them would get over
the "psychological response to accepting that there is life outside the earth". Others say that if it
is life then it is far too early to say where it came from, but even Wickramasinghe would agree with
that. "The ultimate source of life is still an unscratched surface," he says.
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>
<td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td>
<td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td>
<td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td>
<td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td>
<td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
