<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Two trains collide on main west coast line </TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">
<A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Two trains collide on main west coast line</b><br><br><br><b><h2>9 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Trains collide in 'blinding flash'</h2>
<h3>Experts hope 'black box' will provide clues  </h3><br>By <b>David Connett</b><br><br>


<p>
<p>Rail crash experts were last night trying to discover how two trains were involved in a collision
which killed a woman and injured 69 people, four seriously.
<p>
<p>Investigators hope to retrieve two aviation-style 'black boxes' from the wreckage today. The boxes
could tell them what happened. It is thought to be the first time they have featured in a rail crash
inquiry.
The Health and Safety Executive said two inspectors from HM Railway Inspectorate had also been sent
to the scene.
<p>
<p>Railtrack sources said the investigation would focus on why two trains were travelling on the same
line. Initial reports said the empty southbound train was changing tracks at a cross-over point south
of Watford Junction, Hertfordshire, when it and the crowded 5.04pm from Euston to Milton Keynes
collided. Emergency services fought to release up to 40 passengers who were trapped inside one
carriage.
<p>
<p>Experts said the empty train appeared to be correctly crossing to a safe track when the full
passenger train struck it. They speculated that the packed train either received a faulty signal or
passed a warning signal. Witnesses reported that the driver and the guard of the empty train threw
themselves out of the cab when they realised a crash was inevitable. The line on which the accident
occurred is the main west coast line between London and Glasgow. It is expected to be closed for 24-48
hours. Bryan Leaker, commercial director of North London Railways, the company which runs both
services, said: "It was the empty train that was crossing over the line. The two trains normally run
every day and neither of them was running late yesterday. It's standard practice to move from one line
to another when we are moving rolling stock. There's signalling to detect any problem but we are not
aware of any work going on in the area. There will be a full investigation.
<p>
<p>"Using signalling that's in place, mostly likely one of the trains would have stopped and the other
would have passed. I don't know which of these trains would normally have waited."
<p>
<p>Peter Rayner, a former BR manager who was in charge of the West Coast Main Line for six years,
said: "Because the track is owned by Railtrack, the trains are owned by someone else, and the driver
employed by someone else, we are in a situation where to conduct an inquiry is so much more difficult
because everyone wants to protect their own interests.
<p>
<p>"The big weakness is that no longer is there one railway authority to take its own inquiry and feed
that to the Health and Safety Executive. They are all now tainted with commercialism."
<p>
<p>Sir George Young, the Transport Secretary, expressed "my deepest sympathies for the families of the
dead and injured" and praised the rescue services. He pledged that the investigation findings would be
made public. Witnesses to the crash said carriages smashed into the overhead power lines when the
impact forced them off the rails. There was "an incredibly loud bang and a blinding flash".
<p>
<p>One injured passenger described how he was thrown across the carriage. Mick, a builder from Milton
Keynes, said: "There was a huge bang and a crash as the wheels of another carriage came through the
window. People were flying everywhere. When it stopped there was blood pouring down the faces of
people near the broken window. Someone smashed the window of the emergency door and opened it but the
overhead wires were wrapped round the train and still sparking.
There was a girl with a broken ankle who had to be carried on to the track but most of the other
people were able to walk."
<p>
<p>As they walked away, he said, they saw a carriage on its side. "We could see about 40 people in it.
They could not get out but very soon firemen were there helping them."
<p>
<p>Police said 69 people were taken to hospital, included 64 to the Watford General. Fourteen were
detained, including a pregnant woman, and four with serious injuries. One passenger with a serious head
injury was evacuated to a London hospital.
<p>
<p>The dead woman's body was retrieved from the wreckage four hours after the collision. David Larkin,
chief executive of the Hertfordshire and Bedfordshire Ambulance Service, said a search of the
carriages and the surrounding area was continuing. "Sixty people were trapped in the carriages
although 40 were able to get out on their own. Others had to be rescued with the assistance," he said.
<p>
<p>British Transport Police said between 300 and 400 people were travelling on the train.
<p>
<p>An injured commuter told how the impact threw him around the carriage "like a pea in a concrete
mixer".
<p>
<p>Barry Keates, aged 61, a group personnel officer with a London firm, was in the front carriage. He
suffered a broken arm and later had stitches for a gashed forehead.
He said he was on his way home to Hemel Hempstead, Hertfordshire. "I knew the train was in trouble
at the very last minute because the driver started to sound his horn and sound it increasingly," he
said.
<p>
<p>"Then we felt the brakes come on and there was just a tremendous bang. The carriage tipped on to
its right. We were thrown about in all directions. It was like being a pea in a concrete mixer. When
we stood up we were standing on the windows."
<p>
<p>Passenger groups and unions have warned that the West Coast Main Line is "worn out" and
"cash-strapped".
<p>
<p>Commuter and long distance services out of Euston have been subject to serious disruption over the
past year with speed restrictions in place on both North London Railways and the West Coast Main Line
because of the poor condition of the track.
<p>
<p>The main rail union, the Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers union, warned this year that the
track running through Harrow and Wealdstone station would collapse unless urgent repair work was done.
<p>
<p>
<p>
