 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Sweden hosts world congress on sex crimes against children </TITLE></HEAD> <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea"  vlink="#adeaea"> <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sweden hosts world congress on sex crimes against children </b><br><br><br><b><h2>27 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>World congress on sex crimes against children opens in Sweden  </h3> <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Elizabeth  Williams</b><br><br>      <p> <p>Recognising a paedophile would be easy if they had some sort of distinguishing mark, but they don't. In reality, they live in our  communities unsuspected. They are usually someone you know. <p> <p>When my son was two, he was sexually abused by his childminder's husband. He  had been cared for by her since he was five months old and I had returned to work full-time. It was a good arrangement, I thought, providing my  baby with a warm and loving domestic environment. My friendship with the childminder developed over time and extended also to her husband and  two children. She was registered with the local council, took her job seriously and was particularly committed to my son because the  relationship had begun when he was so tiny. <p> <p>The first indication that anything might be amiss was just after my son's second birthday  when, during some after-bath play, he pulled on his penis, looked at me and lisped, with all the inaccuracy of two-year-old speech: "Ken does  this." Gentle questioning elicited no response, so, perplexed, I dropped the subject. A few days later he said a similar thing, but its meaning  still remained unclear. <p> <p>Within the next few months, I changed my childcare arrangements, for reasons entirely unconnected with any  indication of mistreatment. In retrospect, however, I am deeply grateful that I did. Several months after this, we were driving to see friends  and passed the end of the road where my son's childminder lived. With piping clarity, a small voice from the back said: "Ken lives there. Ken  put his willy in my mouth. I put my willy in Ken's mouth." My son's speech, now he was almost three, had progressed to the extent that he could  now tell me what had happened. <p> <p>I was speechless. I also had no idea what I should do with this information. I talked to numerous friends  who offered different advice, ranging from do nothing to kill the bastard. As I considered the details, my priorities emerged. I had to make  sure that my son had suffered no emotional damage, even if I was reasonably sure there was no physical damage. I actually had no idea, over and  above what he had told me, about what had happened. I rang a child psychologist who worked within my area to ask her advice. She was  unequivocal: I must report this man to social services. She would support me, she said, and make herself available for any intervention with my  child, should the child protection team request it. <p> <p>I rang social services and asked to speak to the duty social worker. They were  unhelpful, asking why, and I was forced to blurt out over the phone that my ex-childminder's husband had sexually abused my then two-year-old  son. I was asked to come in and give further details. <p> <p>While the social worker was kind and solicitous, I was very aware that she was  trying to judge the veracity of what I was telling her. Was I, she seemed to think, some hysterical middle-class mother with an axe to grind?  Or even someone with Munchhausen by proxy, perhaps? While I sat there bereft, facing the reality of my failure to protect my son and not  knowing what damage had been done, she made light of the situation. I was told not to worry, she would confer with her boss, contact the child  protection unit and they would deal with it. I had no further role to play; by reporting this man, I had discharged my responsibility. <p>  <p>The next day she rang me. If I wanted to make an allegation of child sexual abuse, she stated as if reading from a manual, then I had to do  so formally and both I and my child would need to be interviewed by the police. I said that I didn't want to make an allegation, I was simply  passing on information disclosed by my young son, and it then became their responsibility to do whatever was required to protect other children  being cared for by this man's wife, not to mention his own young children. She repeated her statement. There was nothing they could do unless I  made a formal allegation with which they could confront him. <p> <p>This involved an interview with me and my child, in my home, with the  social worker and female police officer who worked with the child protection unit. I was terrified about what repercussions might follow in the  future. This man knew where I lived, alone with my child in a ground-floor flat, and as he lived locally, it was likely that at some time, in  the years to come, I would pass him in the street. I didn't sleep well for a long time afterwards. <p> <p>We went ahead. The first interview  led to another between my child and the psychologist behind a two-way mirror. She had been concerned because my son seemed so angry with me,  yet seemed also to be trying to protect me, so she had advised a subsequent session at which she could talk to him alone, without my presence  in the room. So we sat, his father and me, a consultant child psychiatrist, the police officer from the child protection unit, three social  workers (two trainees), another child psychotherapist, the room crowded with all these professionals. <p> <p>The psychologist began her gentle  routine, taking my son through various daily events with the childminder. Without a single leading question, she began to talk about Ken and,  after a while, my son looked up and reiterated very clearly the disclosure he had made to me all those months ago. The atmosphere on our side  of the two-way mirror was electric. I could only weep silently, as I do now at the memory, yet my son seemed strangely unburdened by the  sequence of events; he seemed to relieve himself of the responsibility of disclosing something he must have been told was secret. I have no  idea whether any threats, verbal or physical, had been made, or whether my son had been told that he mustn't ever tell, although I can only  imagine that this must have been the case. <p> <p> <p> <p>The child psychotherapist took me to one side and told me categorically that she felt  sure he was undamaged emotionally. The police officer recommended that I didn't prosecute, as it would be too traumatic and damaging for my son  in the long run. <p> <p>Some weeks later, the same police officer visited me, unexpectedly, early one evening. She had just come from a meeting  with Ken, at which she and a male colleague had confronted him with my "allegation". She told me that he was entirely convincing in his  protestation that he had loved my son and would never have done such a thing. She said that if she hadn't witnessed my son's disclosure, she  would have believed him, and she was obviously shaken and upset. But I knew him well and I could imagine him sitting there, distressed and  shocked himself that anyone could accuse him of such a thing, when he loved children. And indeed he does, but he was abandoned by his mother as  a baby and brought up by an uncle and aunt who, although brother and sister, lived together as man and wife. I'm sure he does love children but  somewhere along the way this has become confused with sexual interest, perhaps from his own experience of sexual abuse as a child. He is, and  continues to be, a paedophile. <p> <p>After a case conference, it was decided that his wife could continue to work as a registered childminder,  with the proviso that he shouldn't ever be left alone with the children. I was never told this formally - what happened subsequently was judged  to be none of my business - but the psychologist who had supported me let me know. That is the best they could come up with. Let's hope that  subsequent children get off as lightly as my own son. Eight years later, I see him playing with his two-year-old brother - confident, outgoing,  happy and secure - and I know I was right to take the path I did then: to ensure he was OK and to leave it at that, protecting him from the  further trauma that prosecution would have involved. In time, I felt reassured, comforted even, that my child had been able to tell me what  happened and that I had listened and acted on what he had told me. A sense of perspective eventually returned and I have managed to avoid the  worst inclinations of overprotectiveness. But a paedophile remains unchecked. All names have been changed. <p> <p> <p> <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr> <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A  HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A  HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td> </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
