 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Seven Iraqi hijackers looking for political asylum give  themselves up at Stanstead airport after diverting a flight from Jordan </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Seven Iraqi hijackers looking for political asylum give themselves up </b><br><br><br><b><h2>31 August 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Running from  Saddam</h2><h3> Six Iraqi women being held at Gatwick Immigration Centre after arriving on board the hijacked  Sudan Airways jet on Tuesday are seeking asylum in Britain </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Alan Watkins</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Basra was the epicentre of the brief but bloody uprising that shook southern Iraq after the allied  victory over Saddam Hussein. Vengeance came quickly and brutally for the rag-tag Shi'ite Muslim  rebels, with thousands killed or driven into exile in Iran or into hiding in the nearby marshes. Some  dead were left to rot where they fell. Others were strung up on telephone poles. The signal for the  rising was given on 1 March 1991, by a Republican Guard tank driver, returning from the slaughter in  Kuwait, who fired his cannon at a giant portrait of Saddam. Ba'ath party officials and secret  policemen were brutally slaughtered before a government counter-offensive wiped out the opposition.  <p>  <p>One witness saw 400 people executed. Other civilians were used as human shields. Resistance  continued sporadically but had died out by the end of March. Throughout, the Allied forces allowed  Iraqi helicopters to fly in support of anti-rebel operations, though the distraction permitted the  Kurds to rise in the north.  <p>  <p>The conflict shattered families and flung their remnants throughout the Middle East in the frantic  search for safety. On Tuesday, six of the survivors found themselves in Britain on board a hijacked  Sudanese jet. The six Iraqi women - a mother in her 50s, her four daughters aged between 18 and 28 and  another woman related to one of the male hijackers by marriage - claim they did not know they were  coming to Britain. The plane left Khartoum and was bound for Jordan before being hijacked.  <p>  <p>The plight of the women, who do not want to be identified because of the risk to relatives at home,  was graphically described yesterday by David Watts, an Essex lawyer, who has been advising them since  their arrest at Stansted airport.  <p>  <p>All the women are related to people who played a prominent part in the abortive Basra uprising. The  husband and two sons of one of them were executed by Saddam's security officers.  <p>  <p>She learnt of the death of the second son when the Iraqi security forces presented her with his  ears.  <p>  <p>She and her daughters have twice been imprisoned and were released on the last occasion under a  general amnesty proclaimed by the Iraqi dictator. Mr Watts said yesterday he believed all had also  been tortured during their detention. He had not specifically asked them for details, although they  had indicated to him that they had suffered brutality and ill-treatment during their time in prison.  <p>  <p>Also with the party are the two children of one of the detained women, a girl aged eight, and a boy  aged five. The oldest of the women, who has heart trouble, was taken to hospital upon her arrival at  Stansted and receives daily medication.  <p>  <p>About four years ago, said Mr Watts, the women fled Iraq and were smuggled into Jordan. Since then  they have been to Yemen, back to Jordan and most recently to Sudan, all the time moving from one safe  house to another for fear of detection by the Iraqi security services.  <p>  <p>In each country all six had made applications for a visa to Britain, the Netherlands, Canada and  Italy but had been refused each time, believing that the refusal was always because they were Iraqi  nationals.  <p>  <p>During their last visit to Jordan they approached the British consul to ask for a UK visa but once  their background became known they were seen only by a Jordanian official, who refused their request  and declined to allow them to press their case with the British consul.  <p>  <p>Mr Watts said that, through his own interpreter, the women had told him they had led a life  virtually in hiding for the past three or four years, dependent for their safety on help from groups  opposed to Saddam. About 12 months ago they tried to go to Kuwait as a possible refuge but found that  Iraqi soldiers were still guarding every border. They abandoned the plan for fear of being captured.  <p>  <p>Mr Watts said all the women had boarded the flight in the belief that they were going to Jordan  where they had been told that someone who could arrange a visa to a safe country had been found.  <p>  <p>He added: "When the hijack attempt began they were as frightened and surprised as the rest of the  passengers and were treated in exactly the same way. They were ordered to sit in their seats and look  straight ahead." When he first saw them after their arrest they were barely able to speak because of  their distress. He said: "There are two incidents which graphically illustrate both their fear and  their mental state. When one of the women was removed from her seat by the police at Stansted she  refused to come down the aircraft steps because she could see a number of armed police officers  standing there and assumed that she would be shot either as she walked down or when she reached the  ground. It took a great deal of persuading that she would be physically safe if she left the plane.  "The trauma for these people continued when they were taken to the police station at Colchester. There  was a drunk in the cells who was kicking and screaming to be let out and the effect upon this party of  women was quite extraordinary. Because of their own experiences they naturally assumed that the man  was being tortured and they all but collapsed as the result of hearing what was simply a noisy drunk.  <p>  <p>"Two more were brought in during the evening before the police had the good sense to see the effect  that it was having on the women and dealt with the matter by moving our local alcoholics to another  police station." Mr Watts said that when he first interviewed them they were terrified because they  assumed he was some sort of prosecutor rather than a lawyer sent to represent them.  <p>  <p>He said: "It is impossible for me to overstate the fear and trepidation with which these women now  confront the world each day. They know that if they are not allowed to remain here they will go to  their death and no doubt it will be a death made as hideous and painful as possible. I cannot believe  that once their case is properly investigated and their story is heard fully by the authorities that  there can be any other just decision except to allow them to stay."  <p>  <p>Michael Howard, the Home Secretary, is likely to make a decision on their asylum application within  the next three weeks.  <p>  <p>Iraqi exile sources said last night that the women's claims were wholly credible. "There is  absolutely no question that people coming from these areas who have been abroad or have family members  who were involved in the Basra uprising are under threat - whether that means death or imprisonment,"  said Leith Kubba, of the Iraqi National Council (INC).  <p>  <p>"They would take a huge risk by going back. Life is cheap in Iraq. People can just disappear and no  one will even ask what happened to them." More than a million Iraqis have fled the country in recent  years, scores of thousands from Basra alone. There are an estimated 300,000 Iraqi exiles in Iran and  an unknown number of Iraqi Kurds in Turkey. Britain is the main centre for organised opposition groups  that work under the umbrella of the INC.  <p>  <p>Mr Watts said that if the asylum applications were rejected he would use the appeals procedure and  continue to take the matter through all available legal channels. At present, his representation is  being funded by the legal aid system.  <p>  <p>* The seven men, who had been questioned at Harlow police station, were charged with hijacking under  the Aviation Securities Act 1982.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
