 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - The Prince and Princess of Wales divorce</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>The Prince and Princess of Wales divorce</b><br><br><br><b><h2>28 August  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Support for monarch as leader of Church falls  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Madeleine Bunting</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Prince Charles as a divorced man should not hold the position of Supreme Governor of the Church of  England, according to a majority of churchgoers. Remarrying would prompt the opposition of more than  half the Anglican clergy.  <p>  <p>There has been a marked erosion of support for the traditional links between Crown and Church, once  viewed as beyond debate by the vast bulk of the Church, according to a Gallup poll commissioned by the  Protestant Reformation Society and published today. Since their last survey in 1984 the number of  Anglican laity who want the Queen to continue as Supreme Governor has fallen from 88 per cent to 71  per cent. Fewer than half of the Anglican clergy said the reigning monarch had to be a member of the  Church. Fifty-five per cent of Roman Catholics, 50 per cent of free churches and 46 per cent of  Anglicans were opposed to a divorced monarch as Supreme Governor, regardless of whether he remarried  or not.  <p>  <p>Anglican clergy were more tolerant of Prince Charles divorcing - 45 per cent accepted it, 40 per  cent opposed - but objected strongly to the idea of his remarrying, with 56 per cent opposed to it and  only 29 per cent accepting it.  <p>  <p>The survey of 1,000 Anglican clergy and a sample of the general population (the response rate of 25  per cent of bishops was too low to be accurate) also found a huge majority against one of the key  pillars of the establishment of the Church. Nearly 80 per cent of clergy and 72 per cent of the active  Anglican laity do not want Parliament to have the final say on decisions relating to the Church, nor  do they want the Prime Minister to have the right of veto in the appointment of bishops.  <p>  <p>Yet in contradiction to these findings, a majority still wanted the Church to remain as the  established church. Significantly, support for this position was lower among clergy than among laity,  and 35 per cent of clergy want dis-establishment.  <p>  <p>"There has been a falling off of support for the constitutional relationship of Church, state and  monarchy, and a significant drop in support for the Queen as Supreme Governor," said the David  Samuels, president of the Protestant Reformation Society.  There is a real contradiction in the Church's views about its established status."  <p>  <p>The survey, Current Beliefs and Attitudes Towards the Church, covered a wide range of doctrinal,  moral and constitutional issues.  <p>  <p>The Church should ordain women as bishops, according to a significant majority of both clergy and  laity. On doctrine, Anglican laity showed an increasing uncertainty, opening up a gulf between their  beliefs and those of their clergy; a majority of laity no longer believe that Jesus Christ was raised  bodily from the dead, and they are equally sceptical of miracles in the New Testament.  <p>  <p>On one thing clergy and laity were in agreement - they don't know what hell is.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
