 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - 'Stormin' Norma Major joins Conservative campaign trail</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>'Stormin' Norma Major joins Conservative campaign trail</b><br><br><br><b><h2>4 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Stormin' Norma braves Scots' no-fly zone</h2><h3>How 'first lady' may swing it for Major with the older generation  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Hencke</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Norma Major has the reputation of a woman who tells her husband the truth about what the electorate think of his policies.  <p>  <p>A shrewd judge of character and a brilliant gladhander with the party faithful, she is said by Conservative Central Office to be the perfect consort for the grey man of politics - "a Denis Thatcher without the gin". But experts believe that the Tories' new campaigning strategy, to use Mrs Major as a come-on to wavering voters, is quite another matter. Her main political act, after all, has been to arrange quiz shows for the party faithful in Mr Major's Huntingdon constituency.  <p>  <p>Bob Worcester, chairman of Mori, the opinion poll organisation, believes the Tories want Mrs Major to woo the older woman back to the fold. He says she might be an antidote to Cherie Blair's image as a strong, independent woman and bring the more conventional older generation back on side. Ms Blair, who has carved out a successful and highly-paid career as a barrister, is judged to have added to Labour's appeal among younger female voters.  <p>  <p>A recent opinion poll involving more than 18,000 voters shows a big generational divide among women which could give the Tories an improbable fifth election victory.  <p>  <p>Labour has a startling 50 per cent lead among 18 to 24-year-old women which falls to 38 per cent among the 25 to 34-year-old age group and to 28 per cent among 35 to 54-year-olds. There is only a nine per cent lead for Labour among the over 55s. So Norma, aged 54, could be the ideal person to persuade them that perhaps another five years of John is not a bad deal after all.  <p>  <p>But Mr Worcester says that while America has had almost 50 years of strong women who have made a big impact, right up to Hillary Clinton, Britain has no such tradition. "The evidence is that even Glenys Kinnock, who went on stand for the European Parliament in her own right, had no real impact on voting intentions in 1987 or 1992," he says.  <p>  <p>Peter Golds, a public relations consultant who introduced John to Norma in the 1970s, sees her as a perfect backroom woman rather than a vote-getter. "Contrary to the public image, Norma does enjoy politics, but just as she is someone who does not flaunt her interest in people with learning difficulties, her work with Mencap for over 30 years, her role in delivering meals-on-wheels in the constituency, she doesn't rush to talk about it. She is extremely good at talking to people, shrewd and perfectly capable of conveying their views to her husband."  <p>  <p>Certainly the official role Central Office was claiming for her yesterday will centre on meeting and greeting businessmen and women at Tory dinners, and being by John Major's side as he campaigns. But there will be no policy speeches and no standing on crates.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Norma Major</b>  <p>  <p>Age: 54  <p>  <p>Upbringing: Brought up by her mother, Edith Wagstaff, in Bermondsey, after her father's death in a motorcycling accident in Belgium at the end of the war.  <p>  <p>Education: Boarding schools, then state school in Peckham, then teacher training college.  <p>  <p>Married: 1970 to Lambeth housing chairman, John Major.  <p>  <p>Children: Two. Elizabeth, 24, and James, 21.  <p>  <p>Favourite charity: Mencap, which says she brings in &#163;1m a year. <p>  <p>Career: Taught domestic science and needlework. Became a nanny for Australian opera singer June Bronhill. Gave up work after marriage. Wrote a book about Joan Sutherland in 1987.  <p>  <p>Salary: nil.  <p>  <p>Magazine appearances: Front cover of Tatler.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Cherie Blair</b>  <p>  <p>Age: 41  <p>  <p>Upbringing: Brought up in Bury, Lancashire, by her mother, Gale Smith, after her actor father, Tony Booth, walked out.  <p>  <p>Education: State school in Liverpool, read Law at the London School of Economics (first class honours).  <p>  <p>Married: 1980 to fellow Bar pupil Tony Blair.  <p>  <p>Children: Three. Euan, 11, Nicky, nine, and Kathryn, six.  <p>  <p>Career: QC and assistant recorder. Has ambitions to be judge. Salary: &#163;1,000 a day as a employment barrister, now &#163;270 a day training to be a recorder.  <p>  <p>Favourite charity: On the management board of Refuge, the battered wives retreat.  <p>  <p>Magazine appearances: Guest edited Prima, biggest selling women's monthly magazine, full of knitting patterns and budgetary tips.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
