 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Sole female editor Sue Douglas resigns from the Sunday Express </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sole female editor Sue Douglas resigns from the Sunday Express </b><br><br><br><b><h2>5 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>A case of poor circulation?</h2><h3>So Sue Douglas has been sacked from her post as editor of the Sunday Express - An everyday tale of newspaper folk, or a victim of her own ambition?  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Angela Neustatter</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Sue Douglas had one senior writer at the Sunday Times almost incoherent with lust the day she came in wearing "a minute doeskin outfit and cowboy boots", and she had no compunction about voicing the stuff of pre-never mind post-feminist thought when she declared that using her sexuality to further her career, if she could, was quite legitimate. Yet nobody is suggesting that her unceremonious removal from much-prized job as editor of the Sunday Express is sexism. Indeed, one fiercely feminist journalist sums up the widely-held view that: "Sue was removed because she threatened to take circulation below one million."  <p>  <p>Ginny Dougary, author of a book on women and the media, feels the same. "It's pure economics," she says. "I think it would be quite wrong to portray Sue as a victim in an anti-female act."  <p>  <p>Certainly victim is not the word that comes to anybody's lips and it is to Douglas's credit that, whatever anyone says about her editing abilities - and opinions are as different as editorials on the Sun and the Times - she has created an image for herself that has defined her very vividly in the collective consciousness. As one colleague on the Sunday Times says with a smile: "Sue made sure she was noticed in as many ways as possible, from the minute she parked her TVR Griffiths sports car outside on the first day. She dressed with huge style and suggestiveness, and she feminised the office in a way that is sadly missed now. There was lots of sweet talk and coaxing and flirting and making us all feel loved."  <p>  <p>She left not an ounce of doubt about her towering ambition, which doubtless endeared her to the likes of Andrew Neil, who recognised that appointing a woman as deputy would be a smart move, but who would have been unlikely to feel warmly towards a Ms who kept needing days off for kids' dental appointments or to stand in for sick nannies. And Douglas has made it publicly plain that this is not a threat, with the most-quoted utterance of all, when she said she felt fine about spending four nights a week staying in her London flat, while her children, Freya and Felix, were still almost toddlers: "They are too young to realise I'm not there much," she said. "The loser isn't them, the loser is me."  <p>  <p>This as much as anything polarised views on Douglas. After all, her decolletage and thrust, her overt sexiness, pales beside that of predecessor, Eve Pollard. But for a mother to be so unapologetically ambitious that she disregards the reams of psychological research about how much children may suffer if they are left too long with nannies pushed her outside the realm of empathy, even of women who support to the hilt a mother's right to work. It evoked the passion of columnist Carol Sarler, a mother herself: "Every mother in the land read that with a shudder. There was sympathy for what she is missing, but it was a shudder unrelieved by her pointing out that men have done it for ever."  <p>  <p>After all, if Douglas were using her femaleness as an asset in her career - one former colleague quoted the story, which may be apocryphal, that during her unsuccessful interview for editorship of the Sunday Times, Douglas leant across and touched Murdoch's knee - she could not have it both ways. And that applied to her tenure. The circulation of the Sunday Express, which had certainly been declining for the best part of a quarter century, stood at 1.23 million when Douglas took over in January and has now dipped to 1.2 million. <p>  <p>Veronica Wadley, associate editor of the Daily Mail, sees it as entirely logical that this has happened. Like Douglas, she has operated from an utterly focused ambition and has climbed the ladder steadily in the midst of ambitious male hierarchies, although, unlike Douglas, Wadley has kept her personal profile low, believing that success is not the cult of the individual but that you must be judged by what you produce. She says: "The only thing anyone can be judged by is results."  <p>  <p>A section editor from the Sunday Times recalls - somewhat sadly, in light of the affection he clearly felt for Douglas: "When she came in as deputy editor, it seemed plain to me that she wasn't up to it. She had tabloid ideas for a broadsheet paper. She is not a good judge of writing. But as stupid as anything was the people she insisted on taking on at the Express - writers like Christa d'Souza and Julie Burchill who were utterly wrong for that paper."  <p>  <p>Yet, in the view of Lesley White, who also worked for Douglas at the Sunday Times, she could have made a go of it. "She was making radical changes and she had the courage of her convictions to keep going. She was a terrific boss, very inspiring for writers. The best of editors make waves and it is the job of management to support them."  <p>  <p>Although the raft of writers Douglas removed within a fortnight of arriving at the Express do not feel the same, the interesting thing about this woman is that even they suddenly voice a sort of protective warmth. Take Harry Ritchie, who was literary editor at the Sunday Times under Douglas. "At first I was perplexed by her," he recalls, "but I gradually came to like her. She would flatter more than threaten, which was by no means house style. And the thing I really admired was that she was brilliant at putting up with people's hostility. When she first came to the Sunday Times, the management hated her, but she didn't let it affect her. I would have gone home in tears."  <p>  <p>A woman writer who declares that she believes Douglas is in a way two people rolled into one may well get closest to pinning the essential truth. She says: "You could go out and have a girlie lunch with her and talk about men, clothes and all that and be really cuddly. But then you saw how absolutely, terrifyingly ruthless she was as well."  <p>  <p>Douglas, forging her way in a world that makes shark-infested waters look like a teddy bears' picnic, attempted to mould these two personas into one, believing that this formula could work for her ambition. And, while she must look back with bewilderment on the splendid, glittering party the Express powers-that-be held for her just a month ago, Douglas is unlikely to be crawling home to Oxford cowed and beaten. Indeed not, says White, a friend as well as colleague. "She'll be burning with frustration," she says, "because she will know she could have made a success of the Express, given time. But while some of us might be licking our battered egos and wanting to keep out of sight, she'll be planning her comeback. I imagine she's on the phone right now."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
