 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - The former INLA leader, Hugh Torney, shot dead</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>The former INLA leader, Hugh Torney, shot dead</b><br><br><br><b><h2>5 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Murder of INLA leader "signals end of feuding"</h2><h3>A republican group's position after 21 years of bloody dispute  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Vivek Chaudhary</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The political wing of the Irish National Liberation Army (INLA) said yesterday that the murder of Hugh Torney, its former leader, could signal the end of bloody internal feuding that has plagued the organisation since it was founded 21 years ago.  <p>  <p>Torney, aged 41, was shot dead outside a house in Lurgan, Co Armagh, on Tuesday night. He had been staying in the safe house after jumping bail on arms charges in the Republic of Ireland.  <p>  <p>Torney was arrested with three other men early last year after they were caught moving a big arms consignment outside Dublin during the IRA's ceasefire.  <p>  <p>His killing is the latest episode in a power struggle within INLA, which has claimed the lives of six people since January, including a nine-year-old girl who was accidentally killed during a shoot out between rival INLA members.  <p>  <p>A spokesman for the Irish Republican Socialist Party, INLA's political wing, said: "The feud is all but over. Torney and a handful of others led an insignificant breakaway faction. Many of his men have defected and there are no experienced gunmen left to take over."  <p>  <p>The feud started after Torney, who was married with three children, was deposed as INLA chief of staff when he independently declared a ceasefire from a Dublin court after his arrest on arms charges.  <p>  <p>Gino Gallagher took over as the INLA's leader, but the organisation split between his Belfast Brigade and Torney's GHQ faction, leading to a bloody battle for control. In January, Gallagher was shot dead in Belfast, sparking the latest round of killings.  <p>  <p>Torney was first imprisoned in 1971 when, aged 17, he was shot by a British soldier while holding a shotgun. He was an active member of the IRA but left in 1975 and joined INLA, a breakaway faction.  <p>  <p>Torney, who became known as 'Cueball' because of his baldness, survived several assassination attempts both by rivals within his own organisation and by loyalist groups. He wore a blond wig and glasses when he last appeared in public at the funeral of Dessie McCleery, a close friend and leading republican.  <p>  <p>In 1993 Torney was named as the INLA's chief of staff during an Old Bailey trial in which two Irishmen were convicted of trying to steal explosives from a North of England quarry.  <p>  <p>The INLA became know for some of the worst attacks during the troubles and for its internal disputes. It was held responsible for the car bomb that killed Tory MP Airey Neave, the chief opposition spokesman on Northern Ireland, at Westminister in March 1979.  <p>  <p>With Torney now dead, many in Northern Ireland fear that the INLA will try and unite its members by concentrating attacks on security forces and the mainland.  <p>  <p>* Up to 3,000 people marched to the centre of Portadown, Co Armagh, last night in support of Billy Wright, the loyalist who continues to defy the Protestant paramilitary leadership's death threats if he does not leave Northern Ireland.  <p>  <p>The march ended in a rally addressed by Mr Wright and the Rev William McCrea, Democratic Unionist MP for Mid Ulster. Outlawed Ulster Volunteer Force members also attended.  <p>  <p>Mr Wright said that it represented a massive show of support for his stance against the way the peace process was going and loyalist parties' involvement in it.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
