 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Cardinal Basil Hume says the government has a "moral duty" to asylum seekers </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Cardinal Basil Hume says the government has a "moral duty" to asylum seekers </b><br><br><br><b><h2>7 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Hume's plea for asylum seekers</h2><h3>Government's "moral duty" to restore some aid  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>James Meikle</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Cardinal Basil Hume, leader of Roman Catholics in England and Wales, yesterday said the Government should show "moral responsibility" by restoring some state aid to asylum seekers. He said that voluntary and church groups trying to help up to 10,000 people stripped of their benefit and housing rights might not cope this winter. Britain's response to their plight would be a touchstone of its moral health.  <p>  <p>The Government should devote part of the &#163;400m a year it may save through the curbs to prevent destitution and "acute social distress". Cardinal Hume, opening a 50-bed night shelter in central London to which he is said to have made a "very generous personal donation", said the Government had a legitimate interest in ensuring fair and efficient procedures for genuine asylum seekers.  <p>  <p>But such people, often blamed for being a burden on the state or taking others' jobs, were "a useful scapegoat for those who wish to appeal only to other people's self-interest or who promote a narrow nationalism". The curbs apply to asylum seekers who fail to seek refugee status on arrival in this country or who are appealing against rejection of their applications.  <p>  <p>But Cardinal Hume said even those granted refugee status were often surviving on income support and living in overcrowded accommodation. The need for the shelter was a grim omen, he said.  <p>  <p>"I do believe the Government have a moral responsibility... to provide financial support to those voluntary organisations which are taking the strain."  <p>  <p>By denying asylum seekers funds, the Government was denying them the chance to pursue legal claims.  <p>  <p>He and the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr George Carey, had met the Social Security Secretary, Peter Lilley, in January and had warned him of the "grave misgivings" about the effects of the changes, which were first introduced in February.  <p>  <p>Voluntary groups say a crisis is approaching, especially since emergency legislation in July put the policy on a legal basis following an Appeal Court ruling in June that the initial benefit cuts were illegal. Increasing numbers are thought to be sleeping rough although most are still being offered shelter in their different communities. Some may wait three years for their cases to be determined.  <p>  <p>The shelter, run by the Refugee Council, includes an advice centre, washing and laundry facilities, a medical centre, room for prayer, and English classes. Several organisations and companies, including the building industry's charity, Crash, have helped provide the centre, which will cost nearly &#163;400,000 a year to run. There is only enough cash at present to last to December.  <p>  <p>The Department of Social Security said yesterday: "Genuine refugees currently not getting benefit but granted asylum will get benefits backdated. "They can then pay the voluntary organisations and church groups who have been accommodating them."  <p>  <p>Voluntary organisations would have to take the strain. "If a church is convinced of an individual's case, they can be confident there will be money there at the end of the day."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Extracts from Cardinal Hume's speech yesterday</b>  <p>  <p>Asylum seekers are not generally popular. They easily arouse hostility and resentment - because they are foreign, or apparently a burden on social security, or suspected of taking jobs for low wages from citizens of this country. They make a useful scapegoat for those who wish to appeal only to other people's self-interest or who promote a narrow nationalism which denies our obligations as members of a single human family to those who come here fleeing persecution.  <p>  <p>It seems to me that the reception given to those applying for asylum is an illuminating indicator of the state of a society's moral health. Most refugees and asylum seekers come from very poor countries and flee to neighbouring very poor countries. By far the greater part of the burden of helping refugees in today's world falls upon those with least to share with them. How do we react to the far smaller numbers who come here? I do believe the Government has a moral responsibility not only to monitor the situation very carefully, but also to provide financial support to those voluntary organisations who are taking the strain. They cannot and should not be expected to cope unaided when the humanitarian demands they are faced with have become so much more acute as a direct consequence of government policy.  <p>  <p>There is a question of justice here. Those deprived of benefits include all who apply for asylum 'in-country' rather than at the port of entry, and all who are appealing against a negative decision. Both are in the middle of a legal right to seek asylum. But the acute lack of funds deprives them of the basic means of living and of paying the telephone, stamps, and travel costs of pursuing their legal claims.  <p>  <p>For this reason the Court of Appeal ruled earlier this year that the denial of benefits effectively rendered their legal right to apply for asylum valueless. The Government overruled the court by amending the Asylum and Immigration Bill. But the moral and practical force of the court's judgment still stands."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
