 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Australian man first to die by legal euthanasia</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Australian man first to die by legal euthanasia</b><br><br><br><b><h2>10 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Dignity in death - Doctor at Large  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Luisa Dillner</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Today Annie Lindsell, a 45-year-old businesswoman who suffers from motor neurone disease, will be seeing a human rights lawyer, in her quest for euthanasia. Lindsell, backed by the Voluntary Euthanasia Society, can no longer use her arms and knows that death, when it comes, will involve a gradual paralysis that will leave her unable to use her muscles to breathe. Understandably she would, like most of us, like to die with dignity. Knowing that she could ask a doctor legally to help her to die would, she says "transform my quality of life".  <p>  <p>Under British law, assisting in a suicide is a criminal offence subject to 14 years in prison, whether the person helping out is medically qualified or not. Active euthanasia, which differs from assisted suicide because it involves an action (usually) by a doctor actively to end a life, is also illegal. Although the law is fairly flaky on charging people who carry out euthanasia with murder it is entitled to do so - murder carries a mandatory sentence of life imprisonment.  <p>  <p>Dr Nigel Cox escaped relatively lightly in 1992 when he was found guilty of attempted murder after injecting potassium chloride (in a lethal quantity) into a woman who was suffering from rheumatoid arthritis. Cox was only given a year's suspended sentence and allowed back to work; the woman was already ill and may have died soon anyway.  <p>  <p>But until the law is changed, there can be few doctors who would risk a lifetime behind bars in the interests of openly providing a guaranteed death with dignity. The only exception seems to be US pathologist Jack Kervorkian - whose 40th assisted suicide was raided last week. Isabel Correa, who reportedly suffered from intractable pain in her spine, promptly held a press conference denouncing the violation of her final hours. Shortly afterwards the assisted suicide sneakily went ahead.  <p>  <p>There are some people who would accord Kervorkian heroic status on the basis that he relieves suffering. But many doctors question his cavalier approach (no second opinion or psychiatric assessment and not every patient has a terminal condition) and dislike his 'in your face' manner. Undeniably his actions, like the cases of Cox and Lindsell, make doctors feel uncomfortable.  <p>  <p>Euthanasia is practised in hospitals every day, in silence and in secret. I once heard a consultant issue instructions that he did not want "this patient to be here when I do my ward round tommorow". He wasn't, on this occassion, talking about care in the community. The patient was suffering from cancer, gangrene, and required large doses of morphine to control his pain. A bit more morphine and he wasn't around the next day. He was nudged, rather than pushed, but all of us involved in his care felt uneasy and duplicitious. There was no full and frank discussion - even among ourselves. I know that this is not, strictly speaking, euthanasia, even if it felt like it at the time. The law allows for morphine to be given to relieve suffering in doses that may hasten death. It also allows, in certain cases, withdrawing or withholding treatment. All are quantifiably different from administering a lethal injection, at a patient's request, with foresight and planning. The ethical dilemma is exactly how different, and whether patients have the right to medical help in ending their lives.  <p>  <p>The latest national opinion poll found that 79 per cent of the public believe that people should be entitled to medical help for a peaceful death if they are suffering from an incurable, intolerable illness, provided they have made the request in writing. A BMA news review survey of 750 doctors published last week found that 46 per cent (a small majority) would favour a change in the law to accommodate euthanasia, although only 37 per cent would be willing actively to end a life themselves. Most of the arguments for euthanasia are based on patients' autonomy, which in the age of medical consumerism is increasingly hard to ignore. Palliative care is improving, but there will always be some patients who actively choose death. Terminally ill patients usually cite their fear of dependence and loss of self respect as reasons for wanting to die, above their fear of pain.  <p>  <p>Opponents of euthanasia argue that any sanctioning is the beginning of a slippery slope and that the old and disabled will be put under pressure to request it. The practise could be extended to those incompetent to make the decision (children or the demented) and encouraged by cost-cutting managers. The availability of euthanasia will erode the trust that doctors have with their patients - if the latter think the former are keen to dispatch them. The only open use of euthanasia is in the Netherlands, which has been criticised for already slipping down the ethical slope (a woman who was depressed over the death of her family was helped to end her life by a doctor), but it has tried to bring the whole business above board. Euthanasia is illegal, but doctors are immune from prosecution if they follow stringent rules, including getting a second opinion. About 1,400 cases of euthanasia are reported each year but an estimated 2,300 are not. The Northern Territories in Australia recently passed an act making voluntary euthanasia legal, which had more thoughtful and more stringent requirements than the Netherlands, including a psychiatric assessment and a full exploration of palliative care options. But the act has met with such fierce opposition from doctors and pro-life groups that it may well be reversed before anyone can utilise it.  <p>  <p>In Britain it would require an Act of Parliament to change the legal status of active euthanasia. Linsdell is therefore unlikely to succeed in her legal battle. It is to be hoped that when the time comes, if she still feels as she does now, she will find a sympathetic doctor to do what doctors have been doing, unregulated, for centuries.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
