<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Stephen Byers's controversial comments on Labour links with TUC</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">
<A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Stephen Byers's controversial comments on Labour links with TUC</b><br><br><br><b><h2>13 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Blair caught in union split controversy</h2><h3>Leadership denies plan to ballot over voting rights</h3>
<br>By <b>Rebecca Smithers</b><br><br>


<p>
<p>Labour was last night embroiled in fresh embarrassment over its relations with the unions - potentially the most explosive row in a week of friction at the TUC conference in Blackpool.
<p>
<p>Tony Blair's office embarked on frantic damage limitation after reports that the Labour leadership was preparing to end the party's links with the unions after the general election.
<p>
<p>The reports were based on comments made by Labour's employment spokesman Stephen Byers at a dinner with four lobby journalists. They claimed the party leadership planned to ballot members on whether they wanted the unions to retain voting rights at the party conference and their seats on Labour's ruling body, the National Executive Committee.
<p>
<p>A ballot could take place within weeks of Mr Blair becoming Prime Minister, should his fears of a 'summer of discontent' through disruptive strike action materialise, it was reported.
<p>
<p>Any such move would spark civil war in the party, and it was a measure of the Labour leadership's concern that officials issued swift denials, hours before the story had appeared on the front pages of four newspapers. A spokesman for Mr Blair said last night the journalists had misinterpreted Mr Byers's comments. "The story has no foundation at all. Mr Blair has made no such proposal and no such proposal is even under discussion." Mr Byers, the MP for Wallsend, was promoted to the employment portfolio in Mr Blair's recent reshuffle and is strongly identified with the party's modernising wing. He was unavailable for comment. But in a statement he said: "I understand four political correspondents are running a story based on a conversation I had with them. I said nothing to justify the ludicrous interpretation being put on our conversation."
<p>
<p>Despite the denials, the suggestion that the leadership was seeking to sever links with the union movement - which founded the party at the turn of the century - is consistent with Mr Blair's attitude in recent debates on the direction of the party.
<p>
<p>During the battle over the selection procedure for parliamentary candidates, he argued in meetings with senior Labour and union leaders that the party should break its formal union links and become a fully 'one member one vote' organisation.
<p>
<p>At last year's TUC Congress a leaked memorandum drawn up by Mr Blair's campaign strategy consultant, Philip Gould, noted that the leadership's long-term aim was to become "a genuine one member one vote party". The unions agreed to acquiesce in a reduction of their share of the party conference votes to 50 per cent on condition that no further moves were made this side of the election.
<p>
<p>Lew Adams, general secretary of the train drivers' union Aslef, said last night: "The trade union movement has seven million members, the vast majority of them traditionally vote Labour. If these reports are true, it's political suicide. The Labour party cannot deny its parenthood."
<p>
<p>This week has been a tempestuous one in the party's relations with the unions. The TUC has defied Mr Blair over setting a level for a minimum wage under a Labour government, while there was also confusion at the top of the party over the way Mr Blair and the shadow education and employment secretary, David Blunkett, announced their proposals to limit public sector strife.
<p>
<p>Last night the Tories seized on the stories as evidence of confusion in Labour ranks. "This sounds like a typical Labour ploy of planting stories attributed to 'Labour sources' which the Labour leadership will hope will appeal to middle-class voters but then denying them," a spokeswoman for Conservative Central Office said.
<p>
<p>"Labour's official spokesmen must now say publicly what their policy is and not leave it to the spin doctors to weave conflicting stories." Yesterday unions voted for a much greater expansion of workers' rights than is acceptable to Mr Blair, in a 14-point list of demands.
<p>
<p>On Wednesday the leader of the Communications Workers' Union, Alan Johnson, rejected Mr Blair's intervention in the postal strike, when he called for a fresh ballot of workers. Further, although 10 days ago TUC leaders were confidently expecting a minimum wage of &#163;4.26 an hour to be defeated at Congress, it was subsequently approved.

<p>
<p><b>ICM poll</b>
<p>
<p>Conservative hopes that the Government's summer recovery would co ntinue were dashed yesterday as Labour reopened a 15-point lead in the latest opinion poll.  Labour's lead over the Tories is up by three points, according to the September Guardian-ICM survey.
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
