<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Stephen Byers's controversial comments on Labour links with TUC</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">
<A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Stephen Byers's controversial comments on Labour links with TUC</b><br><br><br><b><h2>17 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Shadow minister in union row makes jobless benefit gesture  </h2>
<br>By <b>Rebecca Smithers</b><br><br>


<p>
<p>The shadow employment spokesman at the centre of last week's row over Tony Blair's plans to sever links with the unions will today make a conciliatory gesture to the unemployed, pledging for the first time that a Labour government will allow those doing more than 16 hours' voluntary work a week to continue to receive benefit.
<p>
<p>Stephen Byers, Labour's spokesman for training and industry, will make the commitment as part of a programme to help the long-term unemployed back into the workplace.
<p>
<p>At the moment those working in a voluntary capacity for more than 16 hours a week become ineligible for benefit because they are considered not to be actively seeking work. In a speech in Edinburgh today to the annual conference of the Institute of Careers Guidance, Mr Byers will say that Labour believes volunteers should not be financially penalised, especially as such experience could stand them in good stead when it comes to applying for jobs. Mr Byers kept a low profile over the weekend after a political row blew up over his briefing of four journalists at the TUC conference in Blackpool. Labour stressed its "evolving relationship" with the trade unions after Mr Byers supposedly briefed the journalists on his party's contingency plans to cut ties with the unions should it win power after the election. Revealing further details of Labour's plans for the unemployed, Mr Byers will today also announce proposals allowing people who have been without work for more than a year to receive interest-free loans which would be repaid once the individual got a job.
<p>
<p>A Labour government would also appoint 'job advocates' to individuals who are either long-term unemployed or facing that prospect. Each unemployed person would have his own individual career plan.
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
