<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Joe Haines reveals Harold Wilson tried to have Idi Amin assassinated in the 1970s </TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">
<A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Joe Haines reveals Harold Wilson tried to have Idi Amin assassinated in the 1970s </b><br><br><br><b><h2>18 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Wilson 'tried to organise assassination of Idi Amin'  </h2>
<br>By <b>Michael White</b><br><br>


<p>
<p>Former prime minister Harold Wilson tried to organise the assassination of the Ugandan dictator, Idi Amin, in the mid 1970s, his former press secretary Joe Haines revealed last night.
<p>
<p>At the time, in 1974/75, Foreign Office officials told Mr Wilson that they were "very much against it" and later said they had no-one capable of such work, Mr Haines said.
<p>
<p>The story will emerge in a BBC television documentary on Sunday entitled 'How To Be Prime Minister', but Mr Haines, a close lieutenant of Mr Wilson, who died last year, said: "Harold called me up to his study one day. At the time Amin was killing about a thousand people a day. He was worried about it and said he thought Amin should be killed.
<p>
<p>"He asked my opinion. Then he said he was going to see what could be done." Mr Haines admits that he supported the idea in the exceptional circumstances then prevailing.
<p>
<p>Amin, a former colonial army sergeant who was later driven into exile in Saudi Arabia, staged a prolonged period of terror in Uganda as well as expelling thousands of Ugandan Asians who were the mainstay of much of the local economy. Many came to Britain in the early Seventies.
<p>
<p>Later, when Labour had returned to power, Mr Wilson's foreign secretary, Jim Callaghan, had to visit Kampala in person to obtain the release of a British lecturer Denis Hills, who was under threat of execution.
<p>
<p>Mr Haines said last night that Lord Wilson, as he later became, was concerned about massacres and terrorism in Africa and the Middle East and often wanted to take action. He had not mentioned it in his own book on 'Life In Downing Street', Mr Haines admitted, "It was not mentionable at the time." 
<p>
<p>
