<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Women's groups condemn ruling by Italian court of
cassation on violent husbands </TITLE></HEAD> <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000"
link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea"> <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG
SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Women's groups condemn ruling by Italian court of cassation on violent husbands </b><br><br><br><b><h2>20 September 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Italian ruling sparks outrage for 'sanctioning wife-battering'  </h2>
<br>By <b>John Hooper</b><br><br>


<p> <p>Italian women across the political spectrum joined yesterday in condemning a ruling by
the country's highest court which they fear could legitimise wife-battering. <p> <p>Yet the
Sicilian victim in the case said she was delighted with the decision. <p> <p>The court of
cassation ruled that a man could not be convicted of maltreatment if his violent actions were
occasional, provided his partner did not report him. It gave weight to the claim that the
attack by Francesco Lombardo, aged 42, had been prompted "solely by jealousy". <p> <p>Anna
Mannino, aged 39, described her husband yesterday as "a good man and a good husband who doesn't
deserve to be hounded by the courts". She dismissed the attack as "one of those things that can
happen in any family". But the equal opportunities minister in Italy's centre-left government,
Anna Finocchiaro, said: "The ruling introduces a dangerous distinction between violence and
violence - violence is always an offence." <p> <p>Tina Lagostena Bassi of Silvio Berlusconi's
Forza Italia movement said: "To ask the victim to demonstrate the continuity of
ill-treatment... is diabolical." Alessandra Mussolini, a far-right MP and granddaughter of the
late fascist dictator, said the ruling "legitimises violence". A spokeswoman at the centre in
Rome for victims of violence against women called the ruling "scandalous", while the
anthropologist and feminist Ida Magli said: "I find it grotesque that we are still arguing over
issues of this sort." <p> <p>In 1990 Mrs Mannino went to a hospital at Capaci, in Sicily, her
face covered with bruises which doctors said would take a week to heal. Her husband had beaten
her, accusing her of acting provocatively and causing gossip. <p> <p>"Like all Sicilians, my
husband is jealous," Mrs Mannino said in an interview published yesterday. <p> <p>She refused
to report the attack, which was reported by doctors. The ruling overturned an eight-month jail
sentence for ill-treatment. <p> <p> <p> <p> <p> <p> <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td
width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG
