 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Fred and Rosemary West's house demolished to deter souvenir hunters </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Fred and Rosemary West's house demolished to deter souvenir hunters </b><br><br><br><b><h2>8 October 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The house of horror vanishes  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Alex Bellos</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>They were among the first visitors to 25 Cromwell Street when the details of its gruesome past were first becoming known. Yesterday Teresa Perkins and Jane Smith went back for the last time to watch the beginning of the end for this most notorious address in recent British history.  <p>  <p>Mrs Perkins, aged 31, from Evesham, who admits to being obsessed with the house's former occupant, said: "It's part of (Fred West) coming down. He's going and that's that."  <p>  <p>The two women looked on as workmen put up a scaffold at the end-of-terrace house in the centre of Gloucester where Fred and Rose tortured and killed many of their victims.  "It's not bloody fair - they're up there getting a good view and we get nothing," remarked Miss Smith, aged 26, clasping an Instamatic camera. "Do you reckon that copper will let us go and have a look?"  <p>  <p>Attention turned yesterday to what will happen to the site once the bricks, rubble and masonry are ground to dust, the timbers are burned, the few remaining fittings are thrown into a furnace and a concrete cap is laid on top of the site.  <p>  <p>Gloucester city council announced a two-stage consultation exercise, costing &#163;15,000, which will seek the views, first of the relatives of the victims - including some of the West family - and then of the people who live in the area.  <p>  <p>It is even possible that Rosemary West may have a say. Council spokesman Mike McCabe said: "We have made it very clear that everyone within the city has a right to put their views forward. We will not be contacting Rosemary West, but if we receive any opinions via her solicitor then they will be looked at along with everything else that is put forward in this consultation process."  <p>  <p>Few people watching the first day of demolition work felt any ghoulish attachment to the three-storey Edwardian building, the so-called House of Horrors. Many residents feel their lives cannot return to normal until the last brick is removed.  <p>  <p>Michelle Sherwood, who grew up opposite number 25 and whose family knew the Wests well, was back to nurse her mother through this week's media coverage. "My mum's still affected by the whole thing. She has started getting visions again. She's on some kind of tablets. Only when all this is over will she get better."  <p>  <p>Two of the Wests' children visited the house yesterday. Stephen, aged 23, put a bouquet of flowers by the gate of the house for his sister Heather, who died there.  <p>  <p>He later told a radio station: "I think there should be some kind of memorial - a few flowers and pots and park benches, somewhere where me and other relatives can go and sit and think about our lost loved ones. Let's face it, that's where they were buried first and that's where they died." Anne-Marie Davis, Fred's daughter by his first wife, also visited the scene of her torture.  "I felt that I needed to visit the house for one last time to lay it to rest," she said.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Addresses with a past</b>  <p>  <p>10 Rillington Place, west London: In 1952 the necrophile John Christie killed six women there. The street was renamed Rushton Mews before it was demolished.  <p>  <p>23 Cranley Gardens and 195 Melrose Avenue, north London: Dennis Nilsen murdered and dismembered 15 men at these addresses. Sold cheaply, renovated and turned into flats.  <p>  <p>2 Dalton Square, Lancaster: The site where, in 1935, Dr Buck Ruxton murdered his wife and maid in a jealous rage before dismembering them in the bath. Lay empty for 40 years, now HQ of the town's planning department.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
