 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Handguns banned</TITLE></HEAD> <body  bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right  BORDER="0"></A> <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Handguns  banned</b><br><br><br><b><h2>16 October 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Handguns outlawed</h2><h3>Public outrage forces late decision to ban all weapons except .22 pistols </h2>
 <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ewen  Macaskill</b><br><br>      <p> <p>The Government will today bow to public anger over the private ownership  of guns in the wake of the Dunblane massacre by announcing a ban on almost all  handguns. <p> <p>In an extraordinary move decided yesterday at a two-hour Downing  Street meeting to discuss Lord Cullen's public inquiry into the massacre, the  Government will outlaw the vast majority of handguns, and say they must be handed  in. Owners will be compensated. <p> <p>The exception will be .22 single-shot  pistols, which account for less than 10 per cent of legally held handguns in  Britain, and which can be used for sporting purposes. But they will have to be  kept in secure gun clubs. Only the police and military will be allowed to retain  other handguns. The move goes further than Lord Cullen's recommendations,  expected to say guns should no longer be held at home but could be stored in  clubs. The Government had previously been thought ready to back the Cullen  report, published today. <p> <p>The ban, which will leave Britain with one of the  tightest sets of gun regulations in the world, will outrage shooting  organisations which have lobbied hard to protect the rights of their members. But  it will not satisfy Snowdrop, the anti-gun pressure group set up after Dunblane,  which will argue that .22s can also kill. <p> <p>Michael Forsyth, the Scottish  Secretary, will make the first of two Commons statements this afternoon, setting  out the Government's general response to Lord Cullen, such as tightening school  security. He will be followed by Michael Howard, the Home Secretary, who will  announce the changes to the gun laws, which are to be included in the Queen's  Speech. <p> <p>The Government's U-turn is a victory for Mr Forsyth, whose  Stirling constituency includes Dunblane, and who was pressing for the ban, while  Mr Howard favoured a less stringent approach. Mr Forsyth was prepared to resign  from the Cabinet if tough action was not taken. In the event, he had the support  of Mr Major, who chaired yesterday's meeting and who is believed to have been  disappointed that Lord Cullen did not propose a wider ban. The .22 single-shot  pistols exempted are the kind used for Olympic shooting. Twenty thousand are  legally held. <p> <p>The Government will find itself outflanked by Labour, which  moved yesterday to demand a blanket ban, including .22 pistols. The Labour  leader, Tony Blair, the shadow home secretary, Jack Straw, and the shadow  Scottish secretary, George Robertson, met yesterday to discuss the party's  response to Lord Cullen's report, which will not be made available to them until  today. <p> <p>Labour, which may force a Commons vote, will claim the Government  is panicking because it does not want to be seen to be out of step with public  opinion. But government sources insist the deciding factor was the simple  argument that a disturbed individual should not have been able to keep powerful  handguns in his home in Dunblane. <p> <p>The ban will create trouble with  sections of the Tory party, which is traditionally the party of the shooting  lobby. Many gun clubs will have to close. <p> <p>A Commons motion calling for a  complete ban on handguns was gaining cross-party support. The Conservative MP  Hugh Dykes said it had been tabled to make sure ministers knew the depth of  feeling before making a final decision. <p> <p>"It is really to focus the debate  very strongly on this growing perception amongst the public that nothing less  than the complete prohibition on the private ownership and use of handguns will  do," he told BBC Radio 4's 'World at One'. <p> <p>"This is obviously a free vote  and will be a matter for the whole of Parliament and I would guess that there is  a very large majority in the House of Commons for an outright prohibition. This  is an unrivalled opportunity for us in Britain to get away from the menace of the  American gun culture which is beginning to take a grip." <p> <p>Ann Pearston, of  the Dunblane Snowdrop petition, whose address to the Labour Party conference  appears to have been crucial in pushing Mr Blair to demand a total ban, welcomed  the Government's shift but demanded a complete ban. The gun lobby, which claims  up to four million guns are illegally held in Britain, doubted whether the  Government's proposals would work. Michael Yardley, a firearms expert, claimed a  ban "would be simply scapegoating the shooting community". He added: "It doesn't  take much imagination to see that banning handguns but not shotguns is  pointless." <p> <p> <p> <p><b>Gun factfile </b><p> <p>Handgun: a small gun (pistol  or revolver) which is designed to be capable of being held and fired using one  hand only (though marksmen often use double-handed grip in practice). <br>0.22  inch calibre: diameter of the ammunition used - Olympic games and  many other international target shooting disciplines are restricted to 0.22  calibre guns <br>Number of people holding firearm certificates for handguns in  Britain: 57,510 <br>Number of legally owned handguns: 200,490 - of which 10 per cent  are 0.22 inch calibre <br>Number of offences in Britain in which firearms used  (1994): 14,755 <p> <p> <p>  <p> <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr> <td  align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG  border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=center valign=middle  width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=right valign=middle  width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td> </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
