<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Clare Short reunited with
son</TITLE></HEAD> <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000"
alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea"> <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG
SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Clare Short reunited with son</b><br><br><br><b><h2>18 October 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The eternal joy of motherhood</h2>
<h3>Clare Short's reunion is bliss for her and a model for others  </h2> 
<br><b>Leading article</b><br><br><br>


<p>Clare Short did more than just a good turn to herself in placing her name on
the register where adopted people can look for their birth parents. Her joy at
her reunion with her son - whom she gave up for adoption in 1964 when he was six
weeks old and she was an 18-year-old student - will have brought pleasure to all
those who read the exuberant accounts yesterday. Mother and refound son hugged
each other for the press but even cynical Fleet Street photographers recognised
this was not confected. The couple have enjoyed a euphoric reunion. But in
addition to helping herself - and her son - Ms Short has helped two other groups:
the thousands of women who gave up babies in the 1960s who may want to search for
their children but feel ashamed at having given a baby away; and the thousands of
people who were adopted who are searching for their birth parents. <p> <p>Ms
Short rightly feels no shame - only pain for what happened in the Sixties. It may
only have been three decades ago but it was another world where women were not
counselled before they gave up babies and respectable single girls did not become
pregnant before they got married. Over 12,000 gave up babies for adoption every
year in the Sixties compared to 350 in the Nineties. The 1967 Abortion Act, the
introduction of the contraceptive pill, and changing social attitudes towards
single parents have transformed the scene but still left hundreds of thousands of
women feeling loss and pain. Now they may be less wary about a reunion with their
children. Not all reunions will be as successful. Even euphoric reunions can get
tougher later on. But few adopted people, even those with an unsuccessful
reunion, regret searching for their roots. Everyone has a right to know who they
are. <p> <p> <p> <p> <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td width=40><A
HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG
SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A
HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG
SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A
HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG
SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A
HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT
BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG
SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A
