 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Major does U-turn on Queen's  speech</TITLE></HEAD> <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000"  alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea"> <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Major does U-turn on  Queen's speech</b><br><br><br><b><h2>24 October 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Queen's  Speech - Major bows to pressure on abusers and stalkers </h2>
 <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Rebecca  Smithers</b><br><br>      <p> <p>Tony Blair yesterday dismissed the Queen's Speech as the product of a  drifting government acting as if it had "just landed from Mars" and which refused  to take responsibility for the "fractured society" it had created over 17 years  in office. <p> <p>Launching the Commons debate on the speech, the Labour leader  branded it a thin and largely irrelevant programme of legislation, and said the  country needed and wanted an immediate general election instead. <p> <p>But John  Major firmly rejected the criticism and insisted that his legislative programme  was "by any yardstick... a meaty Queen's Speech that we intend to carry  through in the period between now and the election". He pledged that the  Government would deliver a "prudent" Budget next month, adding: "If we can safely  cut taxes, we will. If we cannot, we will not." Denouncing Mr Blair's  "sanctimonious" response, he warned that "any politician should be very cautious  about cloaking himself in righteousness". The debate - which will be followed by  separate debates on different policy areas over the next few days - prompted  numerous angry exchanges and interventions, and included some surprises. <p>  <p>Mr Major stunned MPs in his own speech by agreeing to accept the "unequivocal"  offer of support from Opposition parties to get Government legislation on  stalking and a paedophiles' register through Parliament. The measures were  controversially not included in the Queen's Speech. But departing from his  prepared text, Mr Major said: "I accept that. I accept that deal." Mr Blair  welcomed the move, and said: "It shows the country what we can achieve in  opposition." <p> <p>Mr Major was also faced with an embarrassing rebuttal after  earlier claiming during an intervention in Mr Blair's speech that the Labour peer  and fertility expert Lord Winston strongly supported the Tories' NHS reforms,  which had led to improvements in the service. <p> <p>Mr Blair said he looked  forward to the day when a new government could introduce a bill to "end the Tory  internal market in the NHS and return it to its rightful place as a proper public  service". Mr Major intervened to claim that Lord Winston had said there was "no  doubt" that the reforms had led to improvements in the NHS. <p> <p>Mr Blair  challenged the accuracy of the claims and said he had never heard such a  "ridiculous" intervention. "Lord Winston has vigorously attacked the Tories over  the internal market," he said. Later Lord Winston himself rebutted Mr Major's  assertion. "I am firmly against the internal market in virtually every respect  and I believe it has been counter-productive to having a good and fair National  Health Service." <p> <p>Mr Blair opened his speech by telling MPs that, instead  of debating the Queen's Speech, MPs should be having an election. "The country  wants to make a judgement," he said. "Every element is there bar one. The election  itself. And that is absent for one reason only. The Tories dare not call a  general election." <p> <p>Mr Blair said the speech had "received more publicity  for what has been left out of it than what is in it" in an undisguised attempt to  "embarrass Labour". He warned that the Government's drift meant "that decisions  that used to be taken aren't taken. Drift on beef, drift on crime, drift on  Europe... , everything just swept under the carpet". <p> <p>Taking up the  current morality theme, he asked MPs: "If our society is as torn and fractured as  it is, I ask, who... fractured it? They did! The Government cannot escape  responsibility." He attacked the Tories' failure to tackle beef, crime, Europe,  the NHS, where "drift means decisions that used to be taken aren't taken...  everything just swept under the carpet". The Tories' last hope lay in an outbreak  of "national amnesia" to ensure that people forgot about the 22 tax rises, VAT on  fuel, the poll tax, cash for questions, business failures, the Scott Report. But  Mr Major accused Mr Blair of being "evasive and misleading" about his own  policies, insisting that Conservative measures had brought about low inflation,  falling unemployment and "new hope and new investment" to the inner cities.  Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown later branded the Queen's Speech "a rag bag  of irrelevant measures from a government in its tormented twilight days". <p>  <p>He complained that too much of politics was now in the hands of spin doctors  and soundbites, which meant that people were lied to about tax, kept in the dark  about the true state of the economy and left out of the debate on the future of  Europe. <p> <p>He warned: "If the Chancellor does cut taxes this autumn, he will  be doing so for purely political purposes and the British people will see right  through it." <p> <p>Mr Ashdown said, despite billions from North Sea oil and  privatisation, the NHS was in crisis and class sizes increasing. The most glaring  bungling of all was over the BSE crisis. "This Government seems to believe that  BSE stands for Blame Somebody Else. But farmers are not fooled, they know where  the blame lies - with the Government." <p> <p><p> <p> <p> <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr> <td  align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG  border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=center valign=middle  width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=right valign=middle  width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td> </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
