 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - London revival in full  swing</TITLE></HEAD> <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000"  alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea"> <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>London revival in full  swing</b><br><br><br><b><h2>29 October 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Booming London is the  capital of cool</h2><h3>After the swinging Sixties comes the Nineties renaissance   </h2>
 <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Vivek Chaudhary</b><br><br>      <p> <p>It was swinging in the Sixties, plagued by punks in the Seventies and had  to endure Thatcher's pin-striped yuppies in the Eighties. Now the city is once  again hogging the world stage as the capital of cool. From fashion to  music to bars and restaurants, London is enjoying a cultural renaissance that  some say has never been witnessed before - not even during the Sixties. <p>  <p>"Although there was all this free love around in the Sixties, people were  quite inhibited," said Tuppy Owens, who was part of the scene then. Ms Owens, who  now organises a club night called the Sex Maniacs Ball, added: "The city is much  more vibrant and exciting now. You've got a greater mix of people, from different  races and backgrounds. You've got more choice of where to go and things go on  much later." <p> <p>Author Jonathon Green, who wrote 'Days in the Life', a  history of the Sixties, said: "I think it must be awfully fun to be young now."  <p> <p>London-born models have become a permanent feature of the international  catwalk, while Alexander McQueen and John Galliano, two London-based designers,  are to head top French couture houses Givenchy and Christian Dior. <p> <p>Gucci  yesterday unveiled plans to build its largest European store in Chelsea, west  London, at a cost of &#163;3m, while Calvin Klein is also planning to open a  fashion superstore in the same area next year. London's clubs attract an  estimated 500,000 every Saturday, producing a vibrant mix of music that reflects  the capital's cosmpolitan population. Kathryn Willgress, co-editor of Straight  No Chaser magazine, which specialises in jazz and soul music, said: "People are  visiting from all over the world and there is a tremendous variety of music and  talent coming through." <p> <p>Even business is booming. The London Chamber of  Commerce estimates that the capital's economy is set to grow by 4.3 per cent,  compared to 2.3 per cent nationally. "The success of the fashion and club scene  is all part of London's revival," a spokesman said. <p> <p>Even previously  run-down areas are benefiting. Inner city areas like Hoxton, in east London, and  Stoke Newington, in north London, are said to be home to more artists per square  mile than any other city in Europe. <p> <p>Rick Williams, editor of D'Tour  magazine, which focuses specifically on art and music in north and east London,  said: "Areas like Hoxton are the real heart of London. The British, and London in  particular, have always been known for individuality in music and fashion and I  think that suits the Nineties." At Jimmy Beez, a bar-cum-restaurant in Portobello  Road, west London, Simon Heppner, the 26-year-old manager, was in no doubt that  the city is booming. "London is pukka. There's a really good vibe, and people  are expressing their individuality. It's ethnically diverse, and people mix quite  well. In other places they all bind together and look inward. That makes for a  good Chinatown or Spanish quarter, but it doesn't create something new in the way  London has." The evolution of Jimmy Beez mirrors that of London. Founded  originally as post-club cafe-bar, it now offers a full evening menu. For Mr  Heppner, these developments would have been unthinkable only three years ago.  "Then, the number of people who appreciated good food could not support the  number of good restaurants. Now business is good because people are prepared to  opt for something new." <p> <p> <p> <p> <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr> <td  align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG  border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=center valign=middle  width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=right valign=middle  width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td> </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
