 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Manton school closed because of unruly pupils</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea"> <A  HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Manton school closed because of unruly  pupils</b><br><br><br><b><h2>30 October 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Mother of unruly  pupil may sue head</h2><h3>The latest attempt to end impasse over excluded boy  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Vivek Chaudhary</b><br><br>      <p> <p>A crisis meeting will be held tonight at the junior school in Worksop, Nottinghamshire, which  has closed because staff say they cannot control a 10-year-old boy, in an attempt to break the  impasse surrounding the issue. Yesterday the mother of Matthew Wilson threatened legal action  against the headmaster of Manton junior school. Pamela Cliffe said she did not want to send her son  to another school, although the local education authority has promised to find him a place. <p>  <p>Steven Williams, her solicitor, said: "The obligation rests with the headmaster to ensure that  Matthew is provided with a proper education." He added that action would be also considered against  Nottinghamshire education authority and other parties in the dispute. "We are not seeking damages.  We are just trying to enforce the obligation to teach Matthew, and for the refusal to teach him to  be reviewed by the court." <p> <p>The problem over Matthew had turned into a crisis, said Fred  Riddell, Nottinghamshire's education chairman, because of a long history of "very bad relationships  between the governing body and the headteacher and the staff". He ordered an inspection of the  school to examine the breakdown in relations. It will take place next month. <p> <p>The gates at  Manton school are set to be closed again today as members of the National Association of  Schoolmasters and Union of Women Teachers (NASUWT) strike. The local education authority said  yesterday it was confident of reaching a settlement at tonight's meeting. It could involve Matthew,  who has been accused of assaulting other pupils, being transferred to another school. <p> <p>The  dispute dates back to early summer when Manton's head teacher, Bill Skelley, permanently excluded  Matthew because he was said to be violent and disruptive. The school's governors twice overruled  his decision. Individual tuition arrangements for Matthew, which had averted teachers' threats of  industrial action, collapsed after the governors said last week that they could not continue to pay  for a supply teacher for Matthew, at an annual cost of &#163;14,000, and Mr Skelley refused to  continue teaching Matthew himself. <p> <p>In the absence of alternative arrangements, members of the  NASUWT served notice that they would strike from today. Mr Skelley said he was closing the school  because he could not guarantee the health and safety of his pupils. Parents are angry at being  excluded from tonight's meeting and say their opinions are being ignored. Parent governor Caroline  Morrison said: "Matthew has been portrayed as a monster but he's a 10-year-old child who accepts  that he can be difficult. We should be a little more understanding." Another parent governor, Fran  Lawrence, said: "We want to bring in supply teachers to reopen the school as soon as possible.  Matthew should be allowed back in his usual class. The special tuition may have worked. He should at  least be given the chance." <p> <p>Mr Riddell, who will attend tonight's meeting, criticised the  Education Secretary, Gillian Shephard, for saying that the local education authority should settle  the dispute. He said: "The Secretary of State must be aware of her own government's legislation  which removed the powers to settle such disputes from LEAs in 1988." <p> <p>* Five inspectors moved  into the troubled Ridings school in Halifax, West Yorkshire, yesterday to begin a two-day  investigation ordered by Mrs Shephard, writes David Ward. <p> <p>The emergency inspection follows a  strike ballot by teachers who say that 60 of the comprehensive's 620 pupils should be excluded. <p>  <p><p> <p> <p> <p> <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE  height=30 width=400 border=0><tr> <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A  HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td> <td  align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
