 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Fighting breaks out in Zaire</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Fighting breaks out in Zaire</b><br><br><br><b><h2>13 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Cholera epidemic "could wipe out 250,000"  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Buchizya Mseteka</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Cholera has broken out at a hillside settlement of about 250,000 Rwandan Hutu refugees near Bukavu in eastern Zaire and could kill many within days, a doctor said yesterday.  <p>  <p>Walter Bonifazio, a member of the UN-funded Doctors in Catastrophic Situations, said the refugees were trapped in Mwenga, 120 miles west of rebel-held Bukavu, east Zaire.  <p>  <p>"Cholera broke out at Mwenga on Saturday night, but there is also dysentery and malnutrition. This, put together with the conditions of the 250,000 people, is like putting fuel on fire," Dr Bonifazio said in Kigali. "The human loss will be impossible to calculate, it is a bomb, a very big bomb, and the people will die like flies unless help reaches them soon." He said the 250,000 people at Mwenga were being held hostage by the former Rwandan Hutu militia and troops of Rwanda's ousted Hutu army and the Zairean army.  <p>  <p>Dr Bonifazio was evacuated from Bukavu last month. His information is based on radio reports reaching colleagues still working at Bukavu hospital. Cholera killed at least 30,000 refugees within weeks when more than a million Hutus fled from Rwanda into eastern Zaire in 1994 after the genocide by Hutu extremists of up to a million Tutsis and others.  <p>  <p>Aid workers say thousands of refugees have already died in eastern Zaire, and even if a UN force brought aid today many more would be too sick to be saved.  <p>  <p>The aid agency Medecins Sans Frontieres estimated that 1,000 were dying every day.  <p>  <p>* A fourth Spanish missionary has been presumed murdered in the Bukavu area of Zaire, where they were aiding refugees fleeing fighting in eastern Africa, the Spanish foreign ministry said.  <p>  <p>Although the body had not been found he was believed to be dead, said Adolfo Varas Garcia of the Marist order in Madrid.  <p>  <p>After the announcement, the foreign ministry asked the 39 Spanish missionaries working in the North Kivu and South Kivu areas of Zaire to return to Spain.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>GDN 14 Nov 96 Mission to save million lives: Clinton agrees to send US troops into Zaire as part of multinational force. Britain may send 3,500 soldiers to join relief drive (946)   <p>  <p>By Martin Walker in Washington, Ian Black in London and John Palmer in Brussels  <p>  <p>President Bill Clinton yesterday agreed, under intense international pressure, to send United States troops to Zaire as part of a multinational force under overall Canadian command, with neither its precise objectives nor rules of engagement clearly defined.  <p>  <p>Britain followed suit by saying it was ready to contribute "constructively" to the international effort, "providing a satisfactory plan can be worked out" for dealing with an unprecedented humanitarian relief mission to more than a million refugees caught up in fighting by Tutsi rebels in Zaire. John Major said later: "We will contribute, we will definitely send troops." But he said their number, the scope of the mission and its "exit strategy" were yet to be decided.  <p>  <p>The Foreign Secretary, Malcolm Rifkind, said: "The United Kingdom is prepared to play its part, including a military contribution, to help deal with the humanitarian aid, to get food, medical aid and shelter to the refugees."  <p>  <p>If crucial issues can be resolved at a meeting of potential contributors at the United Nations in New York today, thousands of troops from north America, Europe and African countries could be heading for the Great Lakes region of central Africa by the end of this week.  <p>  <p>The rapid deterioration of conditions in Zaire has led to chaotic military planning. As the standby orders went out last night from the Pentagon, which is to send up to 5,000 troops - 1,000 into Zaire and the rest in logistical and support roles - commanders were still uncertain of their brief. The defence department said the mission would not exceed four months. The Defence Secretary, William Perry, said: "Our mission will be to secure Goma airport [in eastern Zaire], and then open and secure a [three-mile] land corridor to the main refugee area, to bring food and medical relief to this terrible humanitarian tragedy."  <p>  <p>The White House spokesman, Mike McCurry, insisted yesterday: "The mission is not to disarm militants, nor to conduct any forced entry into the area, nor to police refugee camps."  <p>  <p>But commanders wondered whether they would have to impose a local ceasefire and establish and police a humanitarian zone. Some basic aims of the mission are not yet agreed, such as whether the troops will shepherd refugees back into Rwanda, or deeper into Zaire.  <p>  <p>Rwanda's president, Pasteur Bizimungu, warned yesterday that intervention would get "messy" unless rebels in control of eastern Zaire were consulted. US ambivalence about the UN and multinational operations means Mr Clinton's decision carries huge political risks. It could end the post-election honeymoon with the Republican Congress. Haunted by the humanitarian mission to Somalia, which veered out of control in his first months in office, Mr Clinton was talked into the mission by Canada's prime minister, Jean Chretien.  <p>  <p>After a long night of negotiations in the Pentagon, General Maurice Baril, the commander of Canadian ground forces, secured a rare agreement by Washington early yesterday to put its forces under Canadian operational command. They will remain under US tactical command.  <p>  <p>But the US insisted on 'robust' rules of engagement. They will be allowed not only to defend themselves, but to patrol aggressively to ensure they are not attacked.  <p>  <p>The logistical challenge of flying in troops and equipment, and food and medicine for a million refugees, into an area with few roads and dilapidated airfields - where cholera vies with Aids as a health hazard for the troops - "will make Somalia look like a tea party", one Pentagon officer told the Guardian yesterday. "We are looking at literally hundreds of C-5 [cargo plane] airlifts," he added.  <p>  <p>"Every second counts," Emma Bonino, the European Union's humanitarian aid commissioner, told the European Parliament yesterday. "If it [the mission] arrives in three weeks, it will have a lot of work burying corpses, but not much else."  <p>  <p>The mission is to be tripartite. There will be a north American contingent of some 1,500 Canadian troops and two US logistics and communications battalions, protected by US paratroops.  <p>  <p>The European contingent is expected to have British, French and Spanish troops, with the Netherlands and Belgium providing logistical support. Although no British units have yet been placed on standby, the most likely option is a light brigade of about 3,500 troops, drawn primarily from 45 Commando Royal Marines and the 1st Battalion The Parachute Regiment. France said yesterday it was prepared to send 600 paratroopers to Zaire within 24 hours of UN approval of the mission, and 600 more a day later. It is also making available its bases in west and central Africa. The WEU, still embryonic as the eventual European pillar of Nato, will undergo its first big test when officials meet in Belgium on Monday to co-ordinate.  <p>  <p>European countries are expected to foot the bulk of the bill and provide equipment and training for the African contingent, whose participation is seen as essential politically. The main local contingent will be South African, with token units expected from Mali, Ethiopia, Cameroon, Senegal, Eritrea and Congo.  <p>  <p>The UN Security Council was planning a special session last night to give a formal mandate to the effort, not as a Nato mission, but as an unprecedented "multinational force under Canadian command".  <p>  <p>US officials told the Guardian they expected their part of the mission to be "very limited in time, to establish the conditions in which the African countries will be able to take over on the ground and create the space for a longer-term political settlement."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
