 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Glenn Hoddle includes Gazza in the England squad</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Glenn Hoddle includes Gazza in the England squad</b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The greater glory game</h2><h3>What are the implications when the holder of an important national post feels guided by God?   </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Mark Lawson</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Faced with the question of whether a controversial player should continue to be selected for the team, football managers generally take the precaution of consulting a higher authority. Most speak to the Football Association. Glenn Hoddle - almost certainly - spoke to God.  <p>  <p>The deep religious beliefs of the England football coach have added an extra dimension to the debate over whether Hoddle was right to include Paul Gascoigne - who has admitted physically assaulting his wife, Sheryl - in the squad for England's World Cup qualifying match against Georgia next Saturday. What are the implications when the holder of an important national post believes himself guided by a higher being? Does a declared Christian have an obligation to impose high moral standards on those with whom he works? And - given these questions - might the Gascoigne row be a foretaste of a problem soon to be presented in British politics?  <p>  <p>I recently interviewed Hoddle about his religious beliefs and their application to his job for a BBC1 series, 'The Big Question'. A clear sense emerged of the relationship between Hod and God, in the context of which the manager's controversial decision to stand by Gazza may be easier to understand.  <p>  <p>In his final years as a player, Hoddle became known as the only footballer likely to suffer knee injuries as result of sustained prayer rather than ill-timed tackles. Raised in an averagely apathethic Anglican household, he came to serious religious belief only at the age of 28.  <p>  <p>The England team - for whom Hoddle won 50 caps as an exceptionally elegant and inventive midfielder - was playing Israel in Jerusalem. In the months before this fixture, the footballer, by now a millionaire with all the material rewards offered by a modern sporting career, had been feeling restless and empty. In Israel, between training sessions, there was an excursion to Bethlehem, where, as Hoddle tells it, he "felt, all I can say, a real spiritual feeling inside of me and it was exhilarating and I came back from that trip and I really searched myself and searched different books: the Bible, Eastern philosophies, the whole lot really." The circumstances of this conversion - a sudden flash in adulthood - precisely fit the usual profile of born-again Christianity and Hoddle, soon after joining the God squad, appeared in a video for the evangelical outfit Christians in Sport. However, he now rejects the label 'born-again'. He thinks "Jesus is very important, the best example we have of how to lead our lives" but he refuses to accept, as evangelicals do, that only those who turn to Jesus can be saved. There are 'many paths'. He attends church only every three or four months. Prayer and reflection are more important than ritual.  <p>  <p>Hoddle's spirituality is most concerned with the relationship between mind and body. The revelation before the Israel game in 1986 connected with experiences Hoddle had been having as a footballer. While most players treated the numerous injuries of a professional career with ice-packs, physiotherapy and ultrasound, Hoddle, since the age of 18, had been consulting faith-healers, with what he believes to have been success. It began when he limped round to see an early girlfriend, Michelle. He was suffering from a torn hamstring which had been diagnosed to require a seven-week rest. Michelle's mum, Eileen, offered him the laying on of hands. A sceptical Glenn declined but Eileen promised 'absent healing' instead. Next morning, he claims, "I was digging my fingers into the hamstring injury as far as I could and there was nothing there. I couldn't believe it and I phoned up and said: 'What happened?' And she said she'd done absent healing for me. I found it difficult going into the ground because they must have thought I'd been conning them."  <p>  <p>Hoddle admits that, as manager at Swindon, Chelsea and now England, he recommends Eileen and other faith-healers to injured players. The late great philosopher Sir Alfred Ayer was a well-known football fan and it is perhaps a good thing that the celebrated rationalist was spared the advent of an England manager who believed in this kind of thing.  <p>  <p>There is little intellectual reasoning behind his beliefs. Asked why God would intervene - through faith-healing - in order to heal a midfield player's groin strain before Saturday's big match, while neglecting to prevent famine, earthquakes or plane crashes, he can only resort to New Age vagueness: "If we all lived very close to God, if we all had a spiritual life, every single person on this planet, I am pretty well sure that there'd be no such thing as earthquakes, there would be no such thing as people blowing people out of the sky, would there? There wouldn't be any war." His convictions are instinctive, rather than cerebral. They are, however, deep and central to his character. Last week, a former team-mate of Hoddle described him as a "special, lovely person". It is easy to cringe at this - to feel that the language of theatre has been improbably transported to the playing fields - but it is possible to understand what was meant. There is an air of serenity about Hoddle, a sense of quiet strength; a quality, even, of goodness. Unlike some public Christians, he has nothing sanctimonious about him. Of the 13 people I have interviewed during two series of The Big Question, Hoddle and Bishop Desmond Tutu were the two who - at quite different levels of theological reasoning - gave a real sense of spiritual strength and a sincere personal apprehension of a higher power. There are two areas in which the religious faith of a football manager might matter: one trivial, one fundamental. The trifling question of soccer theology concerns the matter of whether God knows or affects the score. Yet this is not entirely a minor matter. The cricketer Imran Khan told me in an earlier interview that he believed Allah had intervened directly to give Pakistan victory in the 1992 cricket World Cup, even to the extent of manipulating rainfall.  <p>  <p>Hoddle believes he was 'guided' by God to take the England job. So the obvious question arises of whether it would be theologically proper to pray during a penalty shoot-out - the sporting torment on which the careers of two of his predecessors as England manager, Bobby Robson and Terry Venables, came to depend. Here, I'm afraid, there is bad news if the FA appointed Hoddle on the basis that only divine assistance could revive England's footballing fortunes.  <p>  <p>"I don't think God cares too much about who's going to win the World Cup," he said. "I think, if there's something behind it, there might be a lesson there for a nation or whatever..."  <p>  <p>"But the lesson might be failure?"  <p>  <p>"Well, of course."  <p>  <p>"But, if you have a faith, as you do, there must be a temptation, when the next Gareth Southgate steps up to the penalty spot, to say: 'Go on, give me this one' ."  <p>  <p>"No. I tell you what I'd do there. I would give the player every good thought, or prayer if you like. But human mistakes come in to it. And that's what makes it so intriguing, not just in football but in life. What I wouldn't do is to put out a negative thought to the goalkeeper. I think that's wrong."  <p>  <p>This kind of speculation is merely amusing: how many wingers can dribble on the end of a pin? The far more serious implications of a Christian presiding over the national side have been seen in recent days. If Hoddle so publicly espouses a creed of decency and good behaviour, should he not also demand such standards of his players?  <p>  <p>Our conversation took place before the wife-beating allegations against Paul Gascoigne, but I asked the question in the context of the England team's alleged violent and drunken behaviour on a tour of the Far East and the confessed addictions - to drugs, alcohol or gambling - of many players, including Paul Merson and Tony Adams.  <p>  <p>"Christianity isn't all about being nicey-nicey," Hoddle replied. "There's a time when you have to let people know what you're thinking, and if it's not particularly good then you have to tell them and they have to become a better player or a better person. I've said it already to the England players that there's a line to be drawn. So we'll see how we go. But that line's pretty flexible. Every individual circumstance would have to be taken into consideration. The reasons why it was done, if there was a problem there... If a manager has a faith, he might be able to help other people face their problems, he might send someone on a new way of life, a new path."  <p>  <p>Women who have suffered domestic violence or campaign against it assume that Hoddle is cynically ignoring the fact that a man is a wife-beater because he might be a sporting world-beater. In fact, it is more likely that the coach has set himself to save Gazza's soul. This may be a naive or hopeless or religiose ambition but it is the polar opposite of cynicism. It is possible, though, that the debate over the possible conflict between Hoddle's beliefs and the company he keeps may have wider implications. Some time within the next six months, it is highly possible that another high-profile Christian, Tony Blair, will take charge of another important national team: the Cabinet.  <p>  <p>There is no evidence that the higher levels of the Labour Party contain any alcoholic wife-beaters but it is nearly certain that, at some point, a senior colleague of Blair would fall from grace, because of some private or public irregularity. And the Prime Minister would find, as the English coach has found in recent days, the boss's professed religious beliefs being quoted against the miscreant. How, the newspapers will ask, can a man of God stand by such a person?  <p>  <p>Blair, who will be judged by opinion polls, might well decide in such circumstances to put earthly power before heavenly glory and drop the wrongdoer. Hoddle, who is judged only be results, has opted to be the Good Samaritan.  <p>  <p>He would see this as one of Christianity's hard choices but the risk is being seen - by those who fall victim to his players' demons and by the press - as a soft touch or a hypocrite.  <p>  <p>Glenn Hoddle, incidentally, also believes strongly in reincarnation. He must wonder what a certain soul did wrong to deserve being sent back to Earth this time round as Paul Gascoigne.  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
