 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - BBC celebrates its 60th birthday </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>BBC celebrates its 60th birthday</b><br><br><br><b><h2>1 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Open the box: 60 years of the BBC  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Andrew Culf</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>1936 World's first high-definition television service launched by BBC from Alexandra Palace, north London, on 2 November.  <p>  <p>1937 Mickey Mouse made his debut on British television. George VI's Coronation gave the nation its first taste of a shared TV experience.   <p>  <p>1938 Reception was confined to London and just 5,000 sets had been sold. <p>  <p>1939 Television service was suspended for defence reasons, bowing out, without explanation, midway through a Mickey Mouse cartoon. It was thought the mast at Alexandra Palace would attract enemy bombers.  <p>  <p>1946 Leslie Mitchell reopened television with the words "As I was saying before we were so rudely interrupted." Introduction of a &#163;2 TV and radio licence. Regular children's programmes began with 'For The Children' and 'Muffin The Mule'.  <p>  <p>1947 Government closed down TV for a month because of a fuel crisis in the severe winter.  <p>  <p>1948 There were more than 17 hours of live coverage of the Olympics from London (there were more than 300 from Atlanta '96).  <p>  <p>1950 First live television from Europe. 'Watch With Mother' began with the arrival of 'Andy Pandy'.  <p>  <p>1951 'What's My Line?' began with Gilbert Harding in the chair - a survey revealed 90 per cent of those with sets watched it.  <p>  <p>1952 'Bill And Ben, The Flowerpot Men', were accused of imparing children's speech development.  <p>  <p>1953 20 million viewers watched seven hours of live coverage of the Coronation.  <p>  <p>1954 Richard Baker, out of vision, read the first BBC TV news bulletin. Until then cinema newsreels or recordings of radio bulletins had been used. <p>  <p>1955 ITV was launched and dismissed by Sir Winston Churchill as "this tuppenny Punch and Judy show".  <p>  <p>1956 'Hancock's Half-Hour' was transferred from radio.  <p>  <p>1957 The Toddler's Truce - the hour when TV went off the air at 6pm so parents could get children to bed - came to an end.  <p>  <p>1958 'Blue Peter' set sail, initially once a week.  <p>  <p>1960 Television Centre, at White City, west London, was opened. Ten million people now had TV licences.  <p>  <p>1962 Television satire was born with 'That Was The Week That Was'.   <p>  <p>1963 BBC ended ban on mentioning politics, royalty, religion and sex in its comedy programmes.  <p>  <p>1964 BBC2 was launched after being blacked out by a power cut on its opening night.  <p>  <p>1965 Kenneth Tynan became the first person to use the word "fuck" on television.  <p>  <p>1966 'The War Game', featuring a dramatised nuclear attack, was banned by the BBC - and not screened for a further 19 years.  <p>  <p>1967 Colour transmissions began on BBC2, coming to BBC1 two years later. <p>  <p>1969 The fly-on-the-wall documentary on the royal family irreversibly changed the relationship between monarchy and media.  <p>  <p>1971 The Open University was born.  <p>  <p>1972 The slow growth of cable television began in Greenwich, covering 9,000 homes.  <p>  <p>1973 The fuel crisis took TV off the air each night at 10.20pm.   <p>  <p>1974 Modern documentary methods were born in 'The Family', which made a working-class Reading family the subject of a 12-part series.   <p>  <p>1977 Televisions capable of receiving Ceefax and Oracle went on sale for &#163;500.  <p>  <p>1979 BBC dominated ratings during the 11-week ITV strike.  <p>  <p>1981 39 million people watched the wedding of Charles and Diana, and sales of video recorders doubled.  <p>  <p>1982 The launch of Channel 4 increased terrestrial competition.   <p>  <p>1983 BBC won the breakfast television race, launching 'Breakfast Time' with Frank Bough and Selina Scott, two weeks before TV-am.  <p>  <p>1985 'EastEnders' provided the BBC with a popular soap to rival ITV's long-running 'Coronation Street'.  <p>  <p>1987 Upheaval with the sacking of Alasdair Milne, BBC director general, after the Real Lives and Maggie's Militant Tendency embarrassments. 1989 Rupert Murdoch's Sky Television and the ill-fated British Satellite Broadcasting transformed the TV landscape.  <p>  <p>1991 A revolution came to listings magazines, with the ending of the Radio Times/TV Times duopoly.  <p>  <p>1992 The BBC launched 'Eldorado', its most disastrous soap.  <p>  <p>1993 John Birt became director-general with a radical shake-up of the BBC's management and a row over his tax affairs.  <p>  <p>1994 BBC signed a strategic alliance with Pearson to develop global commercial ventures.  <p>  <p>1995 'Panorama' discarded its staid image to deliver a sensationally frank interview with the Princess of Wales.  <p>  <p>1996 John Birt announced a revolution in programme-making, putting TV and radio together in bi-media Broadcast and Production directorates.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
