 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - BT launches takeover of US telecommunications company MCI</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>BT launches takeover of US telecommunications company MCI</b><br><br><br><b><h2>2 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>BT launches huge takeover</h2><h3>US company target in £14bn pioneer deal  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ian King</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>British Telecom last night launched the biggest takeover bid in British corporate history when it announced that it was in talks with MCI, the American communications giant, to seal a &#163;14bn deal.  <p>  <p>The takeover, which would be the second biggest in world history, would create a rival for American group AT&T as the world's biggest telecommunications group.  <p>  <p>Sources close to the deal said last night that BT was "supremely confident" the deal would go through.  <p>  <p>News of the proposed takeover, 12 years after BT was privatised by Margaret Thatcher's government, would cement its status as a world power in the telecommunications industry.  <p>  <p>A combined BT, whose stock market value is more than &#163;22bn, and MCI, which is worth &#163;10.6bn, would easily rival AT&T's market value of &#163;34bn.  <p>  <p>BT, which already owns a fifth of MCI, is expected to pay around $40 a share - valuing MCI at around $27.5bn (&#163;16.8bn) - for the remaining 80 per cent of the American group with a mixture of cash and shares.  <p>  <p>Shares in MCI, which had earlier raced ahead in frantic trading, were suspended on the New York stock exchange yesterday afternoon after MCI - the second biggest long distance carrier in America - confirmed it was in talks with BT. Trading in BT shares, which closed down 4p at 351 1/2 p, had closed before rumours of the takeover broke.  <p>  <p>News of the deal comes as BT seeks to establish itself as one of the biggest players in the world telecommunications market, which industry experts say will be dominated by just two or three companies by the turn of the century. Like AT&T, BT already has strategic alliances with European operators, including German utilities group Viag, and earlier this year failed in attempts to merge with British rival Cable & Wireless in an attempt to secure its future in the Far East.  <p>  <p>Last night BT executives, led by chairman Sir Iain Vallance and chief executive Sir Peter Bonfield, were locked in talks at the company's headquarters near St Paul's Cathedral.  <p>  <p>A BT spokesman said: "BT is considering a possible strategic merger with MCI. BT's board will meet over the weekend to consider an anticipated proposal from MCI. "BT anticipates that it will be able to make an announcement prior to the opening of the London markets on Monday."  <p>  <p>Meanwhile, Washington-based MCI's spokesman Frank Walter confirmed that MCI's board of directors was considering a strategic merger with BT. However, as details of the proposed tie-up became clearer last night, there were indications that AT&T - which already has a full licence in the UK - or another US rival might launch a legal challenge to the deal. Under US regulations, monitored by the Federal Communications Commission, foreign carriers may only take a stake of over 25 per cent in a US carrier if its home market is open to competition from US companies. But analysts suggested last night that the British market, which is regarded as the second most open in the world, would comply with FCC requirements. BT and MCI already own Concert, a &#163;3.5bn joint venture signed when BT bought its MCI stake in 1993, which took just over a year to win clearance from American authorities.  <p>  <p>BT also looks clear to complete the deal on the home front. A DTI spokesman said last night it was "a matter for the companies", adding that the structure of any agreement reached would determine its treatment under the competition regimes of Europe, the UK and the US.    <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
