 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - BT launches takeover of US telecommunications company MCI</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>BT launches takeover of US telecommunications company MCI</b><br><br><br><b><h2>4 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Opening salvos in a global communications war</h2><h3>US telecoms leader urges regulators to block MCI takeover deal  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Nicholas Bannister</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>America's most powerful telecommunications group, AT&T, yesterday said it would challenge British Telecom's planned &#163;12bn takeover of MCI, the second largest long-distance carrier in the United States. AT&T believes that the regulatory authorities in the US should block the deal on the grounds that BT would enjoy a competitive freedom in the US not available to American companies in Britain.  <p>  <p>Robert Allen, the US group's chairman, said yesterday: "We believe this proposed merger must get the scrutiny it deserves from the US Department of Justice, the Federal Communications Commission and the appropriate regulatory authorities in the UK and Europe.  <p>  <p>"We would expect our government would condition any such approval on the complete and unqualified opening of the UK telecom market."  <p>  <p>BT and the British Government claim that the UK has probably the most open telecoms market in the world, and that there are no barriers to foreign companies wanting to compete here.  <p>  <p>However, Mr Roberts rejected that view. "New entrants and carriers who want to serve customers still face significant barriers. BT still controls more than 90 per cent of all local telephone connections, and equal access to customers and telephone providers simply does not exist."  <p>  <p>He added that the relative openness of telecoms markets was not just a UK issue. "The ability of a company with this kind of market power to negatively impact competition and reduce customer choice makes the evaluation of this proposed merger a global priority of the highest order." Sir Peter Bonfield, BT's chief executive, said that the regulatory climate in the US had changed recently, providing BT with "a window of opportunity" to acquire full control of MCI.  <p>  <p>He was confident that regulatory approval would be forthcoming, though it might take up to a year of detailed negotiations. He admitted that BT would probably be running up some hefty legal bills as rivals sought to block the deal.  <p>  <p>US regulation prevents foreign companies acquiring more than 25 per cent of an American telecom company if their home market is less open that that in the US. BT, which purchased its 20 per cent in MCI for $4.3bn in June 1993, was recently given FCC approval to raise its MCI stake to 35 per cent, but has not bought any further shares.  <p>  <p>Sir Peter said that the merged BT and MCI - to be named Concert - aimed to cut costs by about &#163;1.5bn over five years, although the impact on jobs would not be significant because there was little overlap between the two companies.  <p>  <p>The new group would continue to support MCI's policy of expanding its long-distance operations and taking advantage of recent changes in US telecoms legislation to build local phone networks, either alone or with partners.  <p>  <p>Gerald Taylor, MCI's president and chief executive, said his group already had local networks in 13 US cities, and would be able to offer local services for 53 per cent of its business customers by the first quarter of next year.  <p>  <p>"To give local coverage to all our customers would involve capital investment of about $2bn, half of which we have already made," he said.  <p>  <p>MCI also wants to attack the residential market, until now the almost exclusive preserve of the Baby Bell regional phone groups. Mr Taylor said MCI was already running residential trials in California and other states.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
