 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - All Welsh pubs to open on Sunday</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>All Welsh pubs to open on Sunday</b><br><br><br><b><h2>4 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>History's tide turns against the Welsh dry sabbath</h2>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Matthew Engel</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The landlords of the Lleyn Peninsula surveyed their silent, shuttered bars and saloons yesterday and then retired for their traditional early Sunday night. As they did so, a piece of the Welsh heritage retreated into history. Almost certainly, one of Wales's longest-standing jokes is henceforth out of date. It is the story of the man who jumps out of an aeroplane and finds his parachute fails to work. As he hurtles towards oblivion, a man on the ground looks up and says "Bloody fool. He should know nothing round here opens on a Sunday."  <p>  <p>From the passage in 1881 of the Sunday Closing (Wales) Act in the heyday of the Victorian Nonconformist revival, every pub in Wales closed on a Sunday until 1961. From that point on - in a rare example of British local democracy - each area was given the choice in referendums held every seven years. Gradually, every district has voted to go wet except one: Dwyfor, the remote, lovely and very Welsh spit of North Wales that juts out into the Irish Sea.  <p>  <p>On Wednesday, Dwyfor votes again, for the last time - because the Welsh Office has decreed that the referendums will cease, and this week's vote will now stand for ever. Leaders of the anti-drinking campaign have conceded that the vote will go against them, and that next Sunday - for the first time in 115 years - every pub in Wales will be allowed to open. The odds are stacked against the dry lobby because of the latest changes to Welsh local government which come along more regularly than rural buses. In April the district of Dwyfor was merged with the already wet areas of Arfon and Meirionnyd to form the new authority of Caernafonshire and Merionethshire.  <p>  <p>This then changed its name to Gwynedd - not to be confused with the former county of Gwynedd, which had completely different borders. In these circumstances, it is not surprising that people need a drink. The whole of new Gwynedd will vote together, and the Rev Aled Davies, Baptist minister and secretary of the pro-dry Dwyfor Referendum Campaign, says this makes defeat inevitable. "I still feel that if Dwyfor had been left on its own, we could have done it. The people of Dwyfor see themselves as different and want to be different. But there aren't even campaign groups in the other areas. We did meet up with some people but they said no. We've lost the battle, and so be it."  <p>  <p>The poll has been characterised by confusion. The wet supporters failed to get their act together in time to get a maildrop to every house. The dries did - but told people to go out and vote on the wrong date. Some extreme wets claim this was deliberate disinformation, which may be the drink talking.  <p>  <p>But not all the wets are confident. "We know the dry lobbyists have been round the old people's homes and the nursing homes and got proxy votes," said Edna Williams, wife of the licensee at the Coach Inn, Clynnog Fawr. "And there's a lot of apathy because people think it's a certainty. The vote could very well go dry. If it happens, there'll be a lot of unemployment and a lot more people killed drinking and driving because of the distances they have to travel.  <p>  <p>"Foreigners get really irate because they just can't believe it. They think this sort of law went out with the Ark."  <p>  <p>No one who lives in the towns and villages of Dwyfor - Porthmadog and Pwllheli, Aberdaron and Abersoch - ever goes short of a drink. The rugby, golf and yacht clubs are unaffected and do a roaring trade. So do the pubs just over the border like the Griffin at Penrhyndeudraeth, which was jammed solid yesterday lunchtime.  <p>  <p>Even Mr Davies says he will welcome the end of the unseemly Sunday rush eastwards. "People should not have to put up with that. This is a very traditional area and the Sunday is still a very special day. A high percentage of the population think that even if they don't go to church. And they worry about the problems caused by alcohol."  <p>  <p>"Yes, Sunday is special," says Mrs Williams. "Most mums work all week and go shopping on Saturday. They want to go out with their family on Sunday and have some quality time."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
