 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Company buys Carnaby Street for &#163;90m</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Company buys Carnaby Street for &#163;90m</b><br><br><br><b><h2>4 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Hip London all arts and no trousers</h2><h3>So Newsweek thinks London is the hippest place on the planet  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Caroline Sullivan</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>London, believe it or not, is swinging again. Just check out last week's issue of listings magazine Time Out. A cover story on micro-starlet Chloe Sevigny, star of the docu-flick 'Kids', was entirely angled around one throwaway remark: "London's my favourite city, and British boys are my favourite, too." If she says so, it must be true. But in the same issue are more substantial tributes to the capital, which is experiencing its greatest surge in three decades.  <p>  <p>In the past year, Londoners such as Alexander McQueen, Damien Hirst and the relocated Oasis have come to define their era just as Mary Quant, David Bailey and the Beatles did the Sixties. This isn't just wild style-mag puffery; foreign publications are also devoting long analyses to the capital. The consensus is that London is once again the hippest place on the planet.  <p>  <p>That's good news if you're young, delectable and within easy reach of Soho, Camden or Notting Hill. The bad news is that many people are turning these delightfully tawdry districts into boutique heaven. In Notting Hill's Ledbury Road, for example, residents of a council estate are forced to live yards from a posh handbag shop and a restaurant, Beach Blanket Babylon, serving kangaroo fillet in red wine. "Patsy and Liam and Kate Moss come here a lot," says Beach Blanket's manager over the sound of haunches of Skippy being chomped by celebutantes. But if you can overcome resistance to the idea that there are prettier people having a better time than you, London is indeed the place to be.  <p>  <p>There's evidence everywhere of a renaissance. It's in the record sales of London-based acts such as the Bluetones and Goldie, in the super-shops opened by Ralph Lauren, Donna Karan and Calvin Klein, in the well-attended readings at Covent Garden's Poetry Cafe. Not since the Sixties has there been such a confluence of fashion and art.  <p>  <p>As in the Sixties, London has become a mecca for people seeking new lives. But what few are prepared for is how unwelcoming it is to outsiders. A whole school of Sixties film and literature was inspired by the hordes who came south and failed to find the London of popular myth. The isolated heroine of the Beatles' 'She's Leaving Home' was heading for the capital and, you sensed, heading for disappointment. 'Georgy Girl', who with high hopes had left a decaying provincial town, found herself overwhelmed by the loneliness of London.  <p>  <p>Still, it was the Sixties and jobs grew on trees. It's a different story now. Unemployment and the dismantling of social services mean the place can be wretchedly depressing, as a fledgling model called Michelle is learning. A month ago she left Los Angeles for Britain, believing her Chinese-Filipino looks would create interest here. She quickly signed with an agency, but things haven't taken off as she had hoped. Work has been slow to materialise and most of her cash was stolen from her rucksack within days of arrival. Broke, she took a live-in job cleaning a homeless hostel in impoverished Peckham, a part of the city most visitors never see. At night fights spill over from the nearby Gloucester Grove estate.  <p>  <p>"It's like East LA, except here you live like a pauper and have to spend much more doing it. Living in this hostel has given me an insight into real poverty. And someone else's room was robbed last night, which is really disheartening. I'm starting to wonder what kind of place this is." I met her in Soho's boutique du jour, Shop, a Wardour Street basement where apparently sane women pay £80 for crunchy nylon slips. Skinny and fashionably rumpled in anorak and men's trousers, Michelle looked like Shop's sort of girl. But she admitted: "I'm just looking. I can't afford anything here."  <p>  <p>So what attracted a UCLA anthropology graduate here? "It's where models come to do pictures when they're starting out. But it's hard getting started." Her sweet voice brightens. "I wasn't expecting it to be perfect. Creativity needs poverty and deterioration to thrive."  <p>  <p>Max Karie, Shop's proprietor, agrees. "Britain was the first country to have had a major recession. Brits have always had a talent for making do on not much money. We learned to prune, and that strengthened our aesthetic. We invented street culture, which is why you find Jean-Paul Gaultier going through the rails at markets. Coupled with the Britpop explosion, where bands are doing iconographic music again, the spotlight is on us again." There's a undeniable buzz on the streets. Newburgh Street, yards from the Sixties' ground zero, Carnaby Street, is cluttered with joints selling expensive knick-knacks. And Carnaby Street... well, more on Carnaby Street later.  <p>  <p>They require money, all these designer doodads. "I don't know where they get their money," says Karie of his young customers, but got it they have. He won't even speculate how. It could be that eight years of rave culture, with its &#163;30 admission tickets and &#163;2 bottles of water, has accustomed people to that once-a-month indulgence. But that doesn't explain the &#163;3,000 leather coats walking out of the big designer shops. Drug-dealing money? There are certainly so many drugs around - ecstasy, cocaine, a heroin glut - that someone is getting rich from them, and with a paucity of legitimate jobs around it's not unknown for rave kids to do a little dealing.  <p>  <p>Tourism, most of it from Japan and America, also accounts for the upturn. These aren't the middle-aged tourists of the past, though. London's new prominence has created the phenomenon of stylish Japanese girls who come in search of London men and clothes, which they find irresistible. Girls such as Tokyo-born Takane, who's lazily pawing through a rack of thirties dresses at Portobello market. Her opinion that "London is much better than Paris now because it's so exciting and cheap" is echoed a couple of miles east in Camden market by Yasuko from Kyoto. She stands out because of her black-rimmed glasses, a tribute to Spud from Trainspotting (which several Japanese girls cite as a reason for visiting London, though the film is set in Edinburgh).  <p>  <p>"I came to Camden because Pulp mentioned it in a song. I'd love to live here, but my father's spent so much sending me to school in Switzerland that I can't ask him for more. But I love English guys, the accents." The English pop stars she idolises are ambivalent about being the centre of such attention. While some bask in it - Liam Gallagher comes to mind - others are bemused. At least the Brit of Yasuko's dreams, Crispin Hunt of the highly-rated Longpigs, is. His look is much in demand by British fashion designers, as evinced by the number of skinny male models all over the place. Yet he protests. "I've never thought English guys were sexy at all. If other people think we are, it must be to do with our facade of manners. Maybe taste is just coming around to us floppy-haired, louche types." Jonathan, a Cockney wheeler-dealer who sells the Big Issue in Carnaby Street, is less modest about his charms. He approaches your investigator with "Can I interest you in a Big Issue, gorgeous?" and is persuaded to sit and talk in a doorway across from a blockful of cheapo leather shops. "I say that to all the girls," he admits crushingly, "and loads of 'em fall for it, expecially the tourists. Some of them are really excited, like, 'Wow, an English guy is talking to me!' It's done wonders for my sex life, being English right now."  <p>  <p>He watches the flow of neon-rucksacked Continentals aimlessly wandering from one tatmonger's to the next. Carnaby Street has long since been defrocked of its Sixties glamour, if it ever existed at all. Despite an image-building initiative by the local traders' association, it's best avoided by all but fans of plastic policemen's helmets. Yet tourists are legion, looking for swinging London.  <p>  <p>"They're so sad," Jonathan says of three French teenagers standing in the middle of the street, taking turns to spray purple dye on their hair. Tres branche (really cool), they're obviously thinking.  <p>  <p>They are sad, but not because they believe purple hair equals street style. It's their faith that hip London is out there somewhere, if only they could find it.  <p>  <p>The place probably hasn't changed much since the Sixties, still promising more than it delivers. For some, the promise is fulfilled; the hedonistic children raised on techno and E are finding London very much to their liking. It's gradually turning into a 24-hour city to meet the demands of people who party all night with no job to go to in the morning. Phill Savidge of pop publicists Savage & Best perceives "a city celebrating itself, and an arrogance that can be very attractive".  <p>  <p>"No future," said Johnny Rotten the last time London celebrated itself with hedonism 20 years ago. There seems to be even less future now other than McJobs and short-term contracts. For the 20-year-olds of swinging London '96, that's reason enough to party till they're sick.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
