<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Oxford dons reject &#163;20m Said gift for business school to keep sports ground</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">
<A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Oxford dons reject &#163;20m Said gift for business school in order to protect sports ground</b><br><br><br><b><h2>12 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Ultimatum on business school  </h2>
<br>By <b>John Carvel</b><br><br>


<p>
<p>Oxford university was last night given a 12-week ultimatum to agree an acceptable site for a &#163;40m business school or face the loss of a &#163;20m benefaction from Wafic Said, the Middle Eastern businessman who helped Britain clinch the al-Yamamah arms deal with Saudi Arabia.
<p>
<p>The university's executive decided to try harder to find an alternative location after its unexpected defeat last week when dons voted by 259 to 241 against plans to build on a supposedly protected city centre sports field. But the 24-member Hebdomadal Council said it was not abandoning its proposal to establish a world class management studies department on playing fields in Mansfield Road, which were acquired 30 years ago on condition that they remained undeveloped.
<p>
<p>It agreed a formal resolution to call for a postal vote of the university's 3,200 dons on whether the project should go ahead on the sports ground site, which Mr Said has said he favours.
<p>
<p>The ballot will be deferred until next term and the council will "redouble its efforts to find an alternative and central site, acceptable to both the university and the benefactor," a spokeswoman said.
<p>
<p>Mr Said said: "I have decided for the moment to maintain the offer of my benefaction because I believe in the importance of the project. If the university is able to produce agreement on an acceptable site for the business school by 1 February, my benefaction will stand." The Hebdomadal Council includes Lord Jenkins, the university's chancellor, and Peter North, the vice-chancellor, who argued last week that the sports ground would be the only central site to meet Mr Said's requirements. The decision to try harder to find an alternative came after warnings from the city planning authorities that they would not be bounced into giving permission for building on the land, sold to the university in the 1960s on condition it would never be developed.
<p>
<p>John Kay, director-designate of the new school, said he would withdraw his acceptance of the post if the school's future was not decided well before April.
<p>
<p>"The objective for many was simply to give the university a bloody nose. They had forgotten that they themselves were the university, and the nose they bloodied was their own," Professor Kay said.
<p>
<p>
<p>
