 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Stephen Dorrell wins extra cash for NHS</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Stephen Dorrell wins extra cash for NHS</b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Dorrell wins £1.3bn to stave off looming health cash crisis</h2><h3>Hospitals get bulk of extra cash as union dismisses "hollow victory"  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Michael White</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The Health Secretary, Stephen Dorrell, will be able to direct an extra &#163;1bn in cash towards the NHS's struggling hospitals next year, as a result of the 1997-98 public spending package which the Cabinet agreed yesterday.  <p>  <p>"Substantial agreement has been reached on all programmes," a Downing Street spokesman said after the two-and-a-half hour session.  <p>  <p>But celebrations at the Department of Health were muted last night as ministers braced themselves for critical dissection of what the public sector union Unison called Mr Dorrell's "pretty hollow victory" in last-minute negotiations with the Treasury ahead of Kenneth Clarke's 26 November Budget.  <p>  <p>Hopes of dramatic tax cuts in the Budget also look doomed to disappointment. Despite talk of &#163;4bn worth of tax cuts, matched by equal spending cuts to avoid alarming the City, supporters of the Chancellor were again massaging expectations downward to say that &#163;2bn - roughly 1p off income tax - is a more realistic hope.  <p>  <p>Analysis of the NHS settlement looks likely to confirm that its position is little or no better than last year's deal which has contributed to this winter's cash crisis - the subject of bitter Commons clashes between the three party leaders yesterday.  <p>  <p>On top of the &#163;33.8bn currently being spent on the NHS, some &#163;800m extra is being allocated to cover inflation and a further &#163;500m 'real' increase - gained over the past week of intense negotiations - to ease the shortages already hitting hospital services. Unlike 1996-97 when primary care got a generous settlement, designed to boost GP services, the bulk of the &#163;1.3bn - around &#163;1bn - will go to hospitals and community health services. Though it will not be available until 1 April the theory is that health managers will now feel able to juggle their way through, unless it proves a harsh winter. Gillian Shephard's friends were also saying she is happy with a quiet success in the public spending round from which she emerged as one of the three biggest winners, along with health and law and order. There were no precise figures from her department, but the Education and Employment Secretary was said to have gained "hundreds of millions" extra after battling hard over the weekend.  <p>  <p>Mrs Shephard played this year's round less visibly than before, when she was suspected of leaking her own warnings to the Treasury last year about the unacceptable increase in class sizes which would occur if she did not get her way.  <p>  <p>The full Cabinet is now unlikely to be recalled for a further special meeting on public spending, so straightforward was the progress made yesterday.  <p>  <p>It did not stop Tony Blair accusing John Major of providing merely "a sticking plaster" for the NHS in its mounting cash crisis, at question time in the Commons yesterday.  <p>  <p>Mr Major rattled off familiar figures about extra resources for the NHS provided by the Tories, while Paddy Ashdown insisted the money is needed now, not next year. His health spokesman, Simon Hughes, later said: "In the last Budget the Government committed less to NHS growth than at any time since the oil price shock in the late 1970s. It is no wonder that they are now having to scrape around for extra cash. Unfortunately the money announced today may be too late for many areas."  <p>  <p>Bob Abberley, health organiser for Unison, said: "This is just a cynical public relations gimmick. It does nothing to secure more money for this financial year - and it will be this winter that the crisis hits, not after 1 April."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
