 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Clinton wins US presidential elections</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Clinton wins US presidential elections</b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 November 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Clinton surges to victory</h2><h3>South saves Dole from humiliation  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Martin Walker</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Victory came shortly after 2am British time, and Republican opponent Bob Dole's spokesman conceded defeat shortly afterwards, even before polls closed in the West.  <p>  <p>Mr Clinton, the first Democratic President to win re-election since Franklin D Roosevelt in 1944, was sweeping towards a comfortable majority of close to 400 seats in the 538-strong electoral college.  But he was in danger of falling just short of his desired moral mandate of 50 per cent or more of the popular vote.  <p>  <p>As voting continued in the West, Mr Dole was running at 42 per cent of the national popular vote to Mr Clinton's 49. The Republican appeared likely to carry at least 10 states, a far better performance than the wipeouts inflicted on the Democrats in the last landslide elections of 1972 and 1984. Mr Clinton took pride in the marked improvement on his 43 per cent of the vote in 1992. Mr Dole also did far better than the 37 per cent of the vote for George Bush.  <p>  <p>The big loser of the night was the Reform Party candidate Ross Perot, who saw his 1992 vote of 19 per cent cut by nearly two-thirds.  <p>  <p>His character and his fund-raising ethics mercilessly battered in the campaign, Mr Clinton appeared to face yet again a vengeful Senate controlled by a narrow Republican majority.  <p>  <p>The House was too close to call, but Democratic officials told the Guardian that their projections showed them winning a razor-thin margin after the east coast polls closed.  <p>  <p>The uncertain fate of Congress cast a slight shadow on the celebrations in Little Rock, Arkansas, where Mr Clinton was already making preparations for his second term, with strong hints that the expected retirement of secretary of state Warren Christopher was imminent.  <p>  <p>The Democrats held Georgia, one of four Senate marginal seats in the South, but were struggling to hold another in Mr Clinton's native Arkansas. But Democrats were well-placed to win open Republican Senate seats in Maine and Oregon, and they gained a Senate seat in New Hampshire.  <p>  <p>As the first polls closed, Mr Clinton was winning overwhelmingly in New England. He was declared the winner in Pennsylvania, Michigan and Illinois, and easily won the bellwether state of Ohio. He also won Florida, the first Democrat to do so in 20 years, thanks to heavy support among the elderly, fearing for their Medicare.  <p>  <p>Strong margins for Mr Clinton in California, where he was 14 points ahead, and New York, where he led by 20 points, offered his best hope of just reaching 50 per cent of the popular vote as the night wore on. Mr Dole was holding most of the Republican strongholds of the South and West, winning Alabama and Indiana and carrying Texas by 10 points, thanks to an unusually heavy male turnout. But Mr Clinton was three points up in Virginia, and Colorado was too tight to predict.  <p>  <p>A spirited Republican recovery in the South, and the strenuous Get Out The Vote efforts on their behalf by the Christian Coalition, appeared to have forestalled a Clinton landslide and saved his exhausted Republican opponent from humiliation.  <p>  <p>Both party machines strained every nerve to get out the evening vote, which traditionally favours Democrats as their voters leave work and mothers with younger children can finally get to the polling booths.  <p>  <p>Mr Perot appeared to be winning about seven per cent of the vote, far less than his 1992 showing. Few undecided voters appeared to have made a last-minute decision to cast an essentially protest vote for the Texan billionaire. This was despite Mr Perot's 'saturation bombing' of the election-eve airwaves, buying 30 minutes of television time on the four biggest networks to warn that the Clinton scandals promised "a constitutional crisis of Watergate proportions".  <p>  <p>Mr Clinton cast his vote in Little Rock, joining the thousands of Arkansans who confounded the predictions of low turnout to queue round the block at polling stations.  <p>  <p>Lacking any home in Little Rock, the First Family then retreated to the Excelsior Hotel's presidential suite to watch the election returns. In a mark of Democratic confidence, parties in the city started long before any results were in, the biggest on the steps of the Old State House where Mr Clinton claimed his victory four years ago.  <p>  <p>Mr Dole hauled his weary 73-year-old body across the finish line in his home town of Russell, Kansas, where he voted, after a last stop at the grave of President Harry Truman, who defied the polls to snatch an upset victory in 1948.  <p>  <p>Calling himself "the marathon man" after his last non-stop 96 hours of campaigning, Mr Dole could hardly have done more.  <p>  <p>The expected Republican retention of the Senate, albeit with a reduced majority, threatens big upheavals in each party. Many Republicans blame the strident House Speaker, Newt Gingrich, for the Democratic campaigns which labelled them 'extremist'.  <p>  <p>This was the first presidential election since 1928 with America at peace worldwide and enjoying genuine prosperity at home.  <p>  <p>The rare combination was the key to Mr Clinton's re-election strategy, despite the concern of many voters with his character, ethics and the latest fund-raising scandals.  <p>  <p>These problems presage a difficult second term, which could be made more difficult by the growing signs that the five-year economic recovery is drawing to an end.  <p>  <p>One of the first to offer his congratulations was the Labour leader, Tony Blair.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>How America voted</b>  <p>  <p>Bill Clinton 49 per cent  <br>Bob Dole 42 per cent  <br>Ross Perot 7 per cent  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
