<HEAD>

<TITLE>Guardian Weekly</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC00OO" VLINK="#660000" ALINK="#66OO00" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="600"><tr><td><center><TABLE BORDER=0  WIDTH="590">
<TR><td></td><TD align=left>
	
	</TD> 
	<TD>
	<IMG SRC="http://www.guardian.co.uk/gweekly/pix/gweekly.gif"  HEIGHT=60 ALT="" ALIGN=right><P></TD>
</TR>

<TR> <TD>
	
	</TD>

	<TD colspan=2>
	<HR noshade size=1 width="590"><P>
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></center> 

<center> <TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="590">
<TR>

	<TD>

	<!--TEXT--> The Guardian Weekly, read and enjoyed each week by hundreds of thousands of people throughout the world, offers a weekly digest of the best of the Guardian as well as a selection of news, comment and features from the Washington Post and Le Monde.
<P>
This unique mix from three of the world's great newspapers gives depth and perspective to the often confused events of the week. Thanks to a global spread of foreign correspondents, the Guardian Weekly provides news coverage that is second to none. Graphic eyewitness accounts of the Balkans war by Maggie O'Kane and Ed Vulliamy, a weekly Washington diary by Martin Walker, and the clear-sighted analysis of Martin Woollacott are just three of the reasons the Guardian Weekly is appreciated by academics, business people, diplomats and opinion-formers throughout the world.
<P>
Outside Britain the Guardian Weekly is printed in Australia and Canada to ensure speedy delivery to subscribers and to the news-stands of the world's major cities. In addition, four Latin American partner papers - in Mexico City, Buenos Aires, Santiago and Caracas - carry a special edition of the Guardian Weekly every weekend. And those who live in South Africa will recognise the Weekly's stamp on the Johannesburg-based <A HREF="http://www.mg.co.za/mg/">Mail & Guardian</A>.
<P>
With its judicious mix of news, views, culture and sport, the Guardian Weekly offers a vital link to the world and to the community of ideas.
<P>


This week: Forget the lavender and olives. The new Provence is a crowded, xenophobic zone that keeps voting the National Front into local power. If the economy fails to pick up, Le Pen could be president of France by 2002, warns <a href="lepen.html">Alex Duval Smith</a>

<P>
If you wish to find out how to get one of the world's best international weeklies,<A HREF="mailto:gwwwsubs@guardian.co.uk"> click here </A>and ask for details. </TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></center><BR><BR> 

