<FONT SIZE="3"><A HREF="archive/week6.html"><img src="pix/arrow.gif"
border=0 height=15 width=15 ></A> Week 6<br>4 November-<br>10 November</font><font size=2><br><br><img
width=100 height=1 src="pix/dot.gif"><p> </font>


<FONT SIZE="3"><A HREF="archive/week5.html"><img src="pix/arrow.gif"
border=0 height=15 width=15 ></A> Week 5<br>28 October-<br>3 November</font><font size=2><br><br><img
width=100 height=1 src="pix/dot.gif"><p> </font>


<FONT SIZE="3"><A HREF="archive/week4.html"><img src="pix/arrow.gif"
border=0 height=15 width=15 ></A> Week 4<br>21 October-<br>27 October</font><font size=2><br><br><img
width=100 height=1 src="pix/dot.gif"><p> </font>


<FONT SIZE="3"><A HREF="archive/week3.html"><img src="pix/arrow.gif"
border=0 height=15 width=15 ></A> Week 3<br>14 October-<br>20 October</font><font size=2><br><br><img
width=100 height=1 src="pix/dot.gif"><p> </font>


<FONT SIZE="3"><A HREF="archive/week2.html"><img src="pix/arrow.gif"
border=0 height=15 width=15 ></A> Week 2<br>7 October-<br>13 October</font><font size=2><br><br><img
width=100 height=1 src="pix/dot.gif"><p> </font>


<FONT SIZE="3"><A HREF="archive/week1.html"><img src="pix/arrow.gif"
border=0 height=15 width=15 ></A> Week 1<br>1 October-<br>6 October</font><font size=2><br><br><img
width=100 height=1 src="pix/dot.gif"><p> </font>

<FONT SIZE="3"><A HREF="http://www.guardian.co.uk"><img src="pix/arrow.gif"
border=0 height=15 width=15 ></A> The Guardian</font><font size=2><BR><BR><img
width=100 height=1 src="pix/dot.gif"><p> </font>











<td valign=top align=left><img width=1 height=1000 src="pix/dot.gif" align=left>

<img width=20 height=1000 src="pix/invdot.gif" align=left> <font size=7><b>Willetts to get &#163;8,000 pay-off
</b></font><br><font size="-1">David Hencke</font><p> <font size=3>






The disgraced minister David Willetts, who resigned his job as paymaster general after being savaged by a powerful committee of MPs for his role in the cash-for-questions affair, is to receive an &#163;8,000 tax free pay-off.<p>

His former employer, the Cabinet Office, confirmed yesterday the former minister will receive a quarter of his ministerial salary - &#163;31,125 - in three weeks. He will still draw his MP&#146;s pay of &#163;43,000.<p>

Labour&#146;s deputy leader, John Prescott, who yesterday called on Mr Willetts to resign his parliamentary seat in Havant, Hampshire, said he was shocked that ministers who quit would be paid.<p>

"I have no doubt as he is an honourable man he will be donating this to charity," he said.
The disclosure of Mr Willetts&#146;s payment came as the minister, who had been attacked by the Commons Standards and Privileges Committee for dissembling - or effectively lying - to a parliamentary inquiry over his role in the affair, insisted he had no intention of quitting politics. Cabinet Office rules say that a minister is entitled to a quarter of his salary if he resigns.<p>

Mr Willetts&#146;s involvement was revealed after the libel case brought by the former minister Neil Hamilton and lobbyist Ian Greer against the Guardian collapsed in October.
Mr Willetts, who was a junior whip at the time, had written a memorandum to fellow whips on the day in October 1994 that the Guardian exposed Mr Hamilton and Tim Smith for accepting cash from Mohamed Al Fayed, the owner of Harrods, for asking parliamentary questions in a lobbying campaign which was orchestrated by Mr Greer.<p>

In the memo Mr Willetts tried to smother a parliamentary inquiry being set up to investigate the matter by Sir Geoffrey Johnson-Smith, then chairman of the now defunct Members&#146; Interests Committee.<p>

Mr Willetts&#146;s explanation to MPs investigating the affair over the last two months was unanimously dismissed by the committee as largely inaccurate.<p>

Dismissing Mr Prescott&#146;s call to resign his seat, Mr Willetts said yesterday: "I hope to represent Havant for many years to come. I am very pleased and very touched by their loyalty and their confidence.<p>

"There&#146;s more to life than politics, and an episode like this reminds you of the importance of the rest of life. But it hasn&#146;t affected my appetite for political argument.<p>

"I am looking forward to a family Christmas and then in the new year I will be an active backbencher. I will think and take stock."<p>

Next week the Commons committee investigating the affair will meet to discuss its next move.<p>

The meeting, which will be held in private, will decide whether to call Andrew Mitchell, a second minister who is implicated in the affair and who sat on Sir Geoffrey&#146;s committee as a government whip.<p>

Dale Campbell-Savours, a Labour member of the Standards and Privileges Committee, attacked Mr Mitchell for his involvement in the affair, suggesting that he was part of an organised attempt to suppress the inquiry into whether Mr Hamilton had broken the rules in accepting cash and not registering a stay at the Ritz Hotel, Paris, which is also owned by Mr Al Fayed.<p>

Since the committee has decided to take future evidence under oath, Mr Mitchell could be the first minister to have to do this since Reginald Maudling, the former chancellor, appeared before the Privileges Committee in the Poulson inquiry in 1976.<p>
 </font>


</td></tr>

</table>




