<HTML> 
<HEAD> <TITLE>Stakeholder Debate: The Introduction
</TITLE> <!-- Date: Monday, January 22,
1996  9:41 am --> 
</HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" TEXT="#000000"> 
<BLOCKQUOTE> <A HREF="http://www.guardian.co.uk/">
<IMG height=34 SRC="pix/theg1.gif" align=left
border=0 alt="The Guardian"></A> <BR clear=all><BR></blockquote><blockquote> <IMG
align=left SRC="pix/head.gif" height=40> <BR
clear=all><BR></blockquote><blockquote> <IMG SRC="pix/lines2.gif" width=540
height=10> <br> <font size=2>Best viewed in Netscape 1.0+. Please resize your
screen to the width of the line above. </font> <br clear=all> <br>

<center><font size=2>Last Update: February 19th 1996</font size></center>
<font size=4> Tony Blair's now famous "stakeholder" <A HREF="speech/sing1.html">
speech</A> in Singapore has, according to <A
HREF="articles/hezza.html#water">Michael Heseltine</A>,  opened <A
HREF="articles/water.html">clear blue water</A> between Labour and the
Conservatives. <P>


The idea of stakeholding, that the individual can have a stake - or make an
investment - in all aspects of society, whether it is financial or not, isn't
new. Its history can be traced back to the <A
HREF="articles/hist.html">1930s</A>. However, it may be the Big Idea that wins
the next election for Labour. But could stakeholding go the way of the <A
HREF="articles/stake1.html">Citizen's Charter</A> or "<A
HREF="articles/basics.html">Back to Basics</A>"?<P> One thing is certain: the
debate sets up a political dogfight between left and right; between those who
believe that "stakeholder capitalism" leads to a better society, and those who
believe in individual empowerment through "<A
HREF="articles/thous.html">shareholder capitalism</A>".<P> The following pages introduce stakeholding. How
people - including the <A HREF="articles/chasl.html">Prince of Wales</A> - define
it, how Tony Blair<IMG SRC="pix/map1.gif"
height=150 align=right vspace=10> understands it, how various interest groups  responded to his
speech, and how it could affect every area of society. There is also the
opportunity to join the stakeholding debate: just <A
HREF="feedback/letter.html">e-mail</A> your views. The most
interesting <A HREF="feedback/letters.html">letters</A> will become part of the
site.<P>



The Guardian Stakeholder site will grow with the debate. It will be constantly
updated as politicians, the media, trade unions, business and the academic world
begin to define the implications of stakeholding for Britain, its economy and its
people. </font>

<BR> <BR>

<HR noshade size=1> <BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 width=65% CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>

<TR> <TD align=left valign=top><IMG SRC="pix/arrow.gif" width=60></TD> <TD>

<B><A HREF="speech/sing1.html">The Speech</A></B><BR> <B><A
HREF="issues/concept.html">The Issues</A></B><BR> <B><A
HREF="debate/debate.html">The Definitions</A></B><BR> </TD> <td> <B><A
HREF="speech/news.html">News</A> </B><BR> <B><A HREF="quiz/quiz.html">Quiz</A>
</B><BR> <B><A HREF="feedback/index.html">Feedback</A></B><BR> </TD>

<TD> <B><A HREF="help/help.html"> Help</A> </B><BR> <B><A
HREF="http://www.guardian.co.uk/cgi-bin/stake"> Search</A> </B><BR> <B><A
HREF="http://www.guardian.co.uk"> The Guardian</A></B><BR> </TD>

</TR>

</TABLE> <P> <font size=1>&copy; Guardian Media Group plc 1996. All rights
reserved. Designed by NML</font></center>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

