<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Tusday, February 11, 1997 -->

</HEAD>

 <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="333333" LINK="660000">
<P><BR>
<!--TOP-->



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/edition.gif" ALT="First Edition" BORDER="0"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><br>
<!-- COPY-->




<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10 WIDTH=550>

<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT COLSPAN=2><I><!--Date--><FONT COLOR="#336699">11 February 1997</FONT></I></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT COLSPAN=2><H1>When war is over</H1><p>

<B>Emily Moore reports on the fate of children caught up in war<p></TD></B>
</TR>

 


	<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=270>
	War means loss for children. In the last 10 years, more than two million
children have died in wars, many others have lost their families, homes and
schools and 4.5 million children have suffered terrible injuries. Now the war
between Chechenia and Russia is over, lives must be rebuilt.<p></TD>
   
    
	<TD WIDTH=270 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="pix/granpa.gif" WIDTH="157" HEIGHT="250" BORDER="0"><P>
<B><FONT COLOR="#000000" SIZE="-1">Twelve-year-old Niyonsaba, a Rwandan boy, had not seen his family for two
years. His grandfather laid eyes on him first: "I am so happy, I didn't think I
would ever see him again. His parents are still alive, he has younger brothers
and sisters, the whole family had given him up for dead." Niyonsaba said: "When
I get home I will talk to my family for a week with my story. I have so much to
tell them."</FONT></B></TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>



 

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"> <B><I>Where is Chechenia, and what happened there?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>Chechenia is in the Caucasus, the mountain range between Europe
and Asia. Chechenia had been part of Russia since the 19th century. In 1991,
the Chechens declared their independence from Russia. Russia's president, Boris
Yeltsin, was against this and sent troops into Chechenia in 1991. But the
conflict was not resolved. In December 1994, he sent his troops in again and a
bloody war followed. Russia has now largely pulled out of Chechenia. In January
1997 Chechen elections were held and Aslan Maskhadov was elected president.
Peace now looks more likely.<p></TD>

</TR>



<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>How are children affected by war?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>One of the most painful aspects of war for a child is losing his
or her family. When there is a war, people flee from danger and try to escape
to safer areas. But in the panic it is easy to be parted from your loved ones.
In the last 10 years more than one million children have been separated from
their families.<p>

Sometimes people in danger flee to other countries: they are called refugees.
There are over 20 million refugees in the world and over half of them are
children. People may also flee to other areas of their country -- this is known
as internal displacement. There are 30 million internally displaced people.<p>

Children often lose their homes and schools in wars, either because they have
to leave them or because they are destroyed.<p>
</TD>
</TR>


<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>Is it possible for children to find their families after a war?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>Yes it is, and reuniting families is one of the most important
steps back to normality after a war - it is a real starting point. If you have
ever lost your parents in a public place, you know how scary that feels. Now
imagine losing your family for weeks or even years and not knowing if they are
alive. Many charities spend a lot of time helping children find their parents
and relatives - this work is called "tracing". Charities work together to
register lone children and find them temporary homes with foster parents or in
special centres. They then try to trace their families.<p>

Often parents come to charities to try to find their children. Photographs of
"lost" children are displayed on posters in food distribution centres, meeting
halls or on TV or newspapers.<p>

Because families provide the best environment for helping children to recover
from war, substitute families are looked for if real parents or relatives
cannot be traced or are dead. The charity Save the Children runs tracing
programmes in Mozambique, Angola, Liberia, Uganda, Rwanda and the former
Yugoslavia. It registered 7,000 unaccompanied children who came across the
border from Zaire back to Rwanda in 1996 and managed to find the families of 95
per cent of them.<p>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>What about schools?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>Going to school brings back a sense of normality. Routine and
stability are important if children are to start being children again, and
having fun. Any type of school is helpful - even if "school" means sitting on
the ground under a tree with a teacher, with no books - maybe just a slate and
some chalk.<p>

In the former Yugoslavia lessons were often held in cellars of people's houses
by candlelight. The United Nations Children Fund (UNICEF) has developed a
"school in a box" pack, an emergency kit for teachers. Over 11,500 teachers
have used this pack in Rwanda.<P>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>What will happen in Chechenia?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>The Red Cross was the main charity working in Chechenia. They had
been reopening schools, feeding people and providing medical care. But
something terrible happened before Christmas. On 17 December 1996 six Red Cross
workers were killed in the hospital where they worked. It is now too dangerous
for charity workers to be in Chechenia and international aid agencies have
pulled out of the country. They want to go back when their safety can be
guaranteed.<p>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
<P>
<BR>
 
 <!--HOME-->

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="pix/index-back.gif" ALT="Home" BORDER="0"></A></TD>


</TABLE>






</BODY>
