<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Tusday, February 4, 1997 -->

</HEAD>

 <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="333333" LINK="660000">
<P><BR>
<!--TOP-->



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/edition.gif" ALT="First Edition" BORDER="0"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><br>
<!-- COPY-->




<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10 WIDTH=550>

<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT COLSPAN=2><I><!--Date--><FONT COLOR="#336699">4 February 1997</FONT></I></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT COLSPAN=2><H1>Rule out Britannia?</H1><p>

<B>Should taxpayers' money be spent on a new royal yacht? Emily Moore looks at
the arguments<p></TD></B>
</TR>

 


	<TR>
	<TD>The Government has announced that it plans to build a new royal yacht and pay
for it with public - ie tax-payers' - money. It will cost around &#163;60m to
build. In 1994 it was discovered that the present royal yacht, Britannia,
needed &#163;20m worth of repairs. This is so much money that the Government
has been trying to decide whether to replace the royal yacht using private
funding or with public money, or not to have one at all. The Tories hoped the
announcement, coming just before the general election, would win them votes.
Labour have not committed themselves to building the yacht if they win the
election.<p></TD>

	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="pix/britania.jpeg" WIDTH="300" HEIGHT="197" BORDER="0" ALT="Britania"></TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>



 

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"> <B><I>What is a royal yacht?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>At 125m long and weighing 4,715 tonnes, Britannia, the present royal yacht, is
not a yacht in the usual sense of the word - more a small passenger liner.<p>
<p>
The first royal yacht was built in 1661. Britannia was planned for King George
V1 (1892-1952) in the hope that sailing around in warm seas might be good for
his health. But he died before the ship was built. The project was taken over
by our Queen, Elizabeth II, and her husband Prince Philip. Britannia was
launched in 1953.<p>
<p>
Britannia has a crew of 275, including 27 members of a royal marines band who
only join the crew for overseas official visits. The crew are equipped with
white Plimsoles to cut down on noise.<p></TD>

</TR>



<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>What does the royal yacht do?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>Britannia takes the royal family on trips and acts as a showcase for Britain's
design and engineering skills. It has been claimed that the Britannia has
brought more than &#163;2bn worth of export business to Britain over the last
10 years. But people point out that the Emperor of Japan does not have a royal
yacht and Japan is a country which exports far more than we do.<p>
<p>
The royal yacht left Portsmouth for its last trip on 20 January this year. It
will end the trip in Hong Kong in June, when the colony, which was part of the
British Empire, will be handed back to the Chinese.<p>
</TD>
</TR>


<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>Does Britain need a new royal yacht?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>Michael Portillo, the Defence Secretary, said we need a new yacht because it
symbolises the nation's pride. But others see a new yacht as a pointless
extravagance which Britain really cannot afford. &#163;60m could build two new
hospitals, six new secondary schools, or immunise six million children in the
developing world. Some say, if we are to have a royal yacht then why not build
one that is smaller and cheaper. For example, the Spanish royal yacht, Fortuna,
is 40m long and cost just &#163;3m to build.<p>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>Should taxpayers pay for a new royal yacht?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>A Guardian poll showed that 72 per cent of people disapproved of the
Government's decision to spend &#163;60m of public money on a new royal
yacht.
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>Who would build the new royal yacht?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>A Guardian poll showed that 72 per cent of people disapproved of the
Government's decision to spend &#163;60m of public money on a new royal
yacht.
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
<P>
<BR>
 
 <!--HOME-->

