<HTML>
<HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="333333" LINK="660000">
<P><BR>
<!--TOP-->



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/edition.gif" ALT="First Edition" BORDER="0"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><br>
<!-- COPY-->

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10 WIDTH=550>

<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT COLSPAN=2><I><!--Date--><FONT COLOR="#336699">28 January 1997</FONT></I></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=2><H1>Road to peace</H1><p>

<B>Since 1969, over 3,000 people have lost their lives in the Northern Ireland
Troubles. Emily Moore looks at some of the issues<p></TD></B>
</TR>

 


	<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=2>Last weekend, it was the 25th anniversary of Bloody Sunday. On Sunday 30
January 1972, 13 unarmed people were shot and killed by British paratroopers;
13 others were wounded. It happened in Derry, Northern Ireland, at a Catholic
march against internment (the imprisonment of people without a trial). The Army
feared the IRA would be among the marchers. But the organisers of the march,
worried about violence, had obtained a promise from the IRA that they wouldn't
cause trouble. The British paratroopers crossed into Free Derry. The
Paratroopers say they were fired at, that they shot in self-defence. But people
on the Catholic side say that nobody fired at the soldiers. No guns were found
on the victims. Nor was there any evidence that the paratroopers had been shot
at. Nobody has ever been tried for the killings.</TD>

 </TR>
</TABLE>



 

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"> <B><I>The Downing Street Declaration, December 1993</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>This declared that the British government's main interest was to
see peace in Northern Ireland. But talks between all the political parties in
Northern Ireland, as well as the Irish and British governments, could not take
place as long as some parties used violence to make their political point.
There are parties on both sides which have links with terrorist groups. Sinn
Fein is linked to the IRA, the Ulster Democratic Party is linked to the Ulster
Defence Association (UDA) and the Progressive Unionist Party is linked to the
Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF).<p></TD>

</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>The ceasefire, 31 August 1994</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>
In August 1994, the IRA agreed to a ceasefire, and six weeks
later so did the UDA and the UVF.<p></TD>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>Ceasefire ends, 9 February 1996</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD>
The IRA ceasefire lasted until February 1996, when the IRA bombed
the Isle of Dogs in London. Since then there have been other IRA attacks. Now
the Unionist ceasefire is thought to be disintegrating. There have been attacks
on Catholics and leading Republicans which are likely to have been by the UDA,
but the terrorists have not admitted responsibility.<p>
</TD>
</TR>


<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>What happens now?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>It is unlikely that anything will happen within the next six
months as the British general election is only months away. The Conservative
party relies on the nine Ulster Unionists in the House of Commons for votes
(Ulster Unionists tend to support Conservative policies) and so can't afford to
upset them. Neither the British and Irish governments nor the Unionists will
talk to Sinn Fein until the IRA agrees to another ceasefire. Many agree with
John Hume, leader of the SDLP, that without Sinn Fein at the peace talks there
won't be any progress towards peace. So it seems unless the IRA agrees to
another ceasefire, nothing can be achieved.<p>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>Useful links</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD><A HREF="http://148.100.56.24/bis/nireland/nireland.htm" TARGET="_NEW">Britain in the USA: Northern Ireland</A><br>
	<A HREF="http://www.nics.gov.uk" TARGET="_NEW">Northern Ireland Public Service Web</A><p>
	</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

 
 
<TABLE WIDTH=550>
<TR>

	<TD COLSPAN=3>
	<B><FONT SIZE="+2">Who's who in Northern Ireland politics</FONT></B><P>
	</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD>
	<B><FONT SIZE="+1">Unionists</FONT></B><BR>
The Protestant community of Northern Ireland is mainly Unionist - they
want Northern Ireland to remain within the United Kingdom. David Trimble is
leader of the Ulster Unionist party. The Rev Ian Paisley is the leader of the
Democratic Unionist party.<P><BR>
	</TD>
	
	<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER>
	<IMG SRC="pix/david.jpeg" ALT="David Trimble" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="106" BORDER="0"><br><FONT SIZE="-1">David Trimble</FONT><P><BR>
	</TD>
	
	
	<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER>
	<IMG SRC="pix/ian.jpeg" ALT="Ian Paisley" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="106" BORDER="0"><br><FONT SIZE="-1">Ian Paisley</FONT><P><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>


<TR>

	<TD>
	<B><FONT SIZE="+1">Nationalists</FONT></B><BR>
Most Catholics in Northern Ireland are Nationalists (sometimes called
Republicans). Some want Northern Ireland to be part of the Republic of Ireland
and be governed from Dublin, others want Dublin to have as big a role as
London. John Hume is the leader of the Social Democratic and Labour Party
(SDLP), the largest nationalist party. Gerry Adams is the leader of Sinn Fein,
which is the political voice of the IRA and which supports the IRA's right to
fight a military campaign for independence from Britain.<P><BR>
	</TD>
	
	<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER>
	<IMG SRC="pix/jon.jpeg" ALT="John Hume" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="106" BORDER="0"><br><FONT SIZE="-1">John Hume</FONT><P><BR>
	</TD>
	
	
	<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER>
	<IMG SRC="pix/gerry.jpeg" ALT="Gerry Adams" WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="106" BORDER="0"><BR><FONT SIZE="-1">Gerry Adams</FONT><P><BR>
	</TD>
</TR>

<TR>

	<TD COLSPAN=3>
	<B><FONT SIZE="+1">What is the IRA?</FONT></B><BR>
	The IRA (Irish Republican Army) was formed in 1919 during the struggle
for Irish independence. For most of its history the IRA has used violence for
political ends. Because of this it is known as a terrorist organisation.<p>
	</TD>
</TABLE>


<!--HOME-->

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR>
