</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Tusday, February 4, 1997 -->

</HEAD>

 <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="333333" LINK="660000">
<P><BR>
<!--TOP-->



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/edition.gif" ALT="First Edition" BORDER="0"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><br>
<!-- COPY-->

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10 WIDTH=550>

<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT COLSPAN=2><I><!--Date--><FONT COLOR="#336699">14 January 1997</FONT></I></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=2><H1>Hidden danger</H1><p>

<B>A visit by the Princess of Wales to Angola has highlighted the case for a
worldwide ban on landmines. Emily Moore reports<p></TD></B>
</TR>

 


	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP> One person is killed or maimed by landmines every 20 minutes. There are 110
million landmines littering the world, causing 26,000 deaths and injuries each
year.<p></TD>

	
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=229>
	<IMG SRC="pix/diana.jpeg"  BORDER="0" ALT="Princess of Wales" WIDTH=229 HEIGHT=175>
	<p>
<B>Diana in Angola last week, where she supported the Red Cross campaign to
outlaw landmines</B><br>

 </TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>



 

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"> <B><I>What is a landmine?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>Landmines are bombs. They are sometimes called "anti-personnel
mines" (APMs). There are three main types: blast mines, fragmentation mines and
directional mines. Blast mines are scattered randomly from the air, and explode
when they are stepped on. Fragmentation mines are laid on the ground and are
often set off by trip-wire; when they explode, they can kill people up to 50
metres away. Directional mines are like fragmentation mines but are designed to
send the fragments in a particular direction after exploding.<p>
There are new mines called "smart mines". Some of them turn themselves off
after a certain time and others explode.<p></TD>

</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>Why are landmines more dangerous than other bombs?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>
Landmines explode regardless of what activates them - it could be
a soldier's boot or the foot of a small child. At the end of a war, people stop
fighting but the landmines remain. Years later landmines can still maim and
kill. Eighty per cent of landmine victims are not soldiers but civilians; 20
per cent are children.<p>
Landmines are cheap and easy to make and lay - they can be bought for as little
as &#163;2. They are often scattered haphazardly by soldiers. In mine-infested
countries, even the simplest activity, such as gathering firewood or going for
a walk, can be threatening.<p>
</TD>
</TR>


<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>Which countries are most affected by landmines?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>War-torn countries such as Afghanistan, Cambodia, Angola,
Mozambique and the former Yugoslavia are among the worst hit. In Bosnia and
Croatia, between four and six million landmines have been laid and nobody knows
where half of them are.<p>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>What is it like living with landmines?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>Most mines are in rural areas, where the local people farm the
land. They have three choices: either to leave the area, grow fewer crops, or
literally risk life and limb each day as they go into the fields. Most people
choose a combination of the last two.<p>
In Afghanistan and Cambodia, 35 per cent more land could be cultivated if it
were not for the threat of mines. The blast from an exploding mine often kills
people outright or leaves them to bleed to death in the fields. If they survive
they often have to have a damaged arm or leg amputated and may die later from
infection. In Cambodia one in every 236 people has lost at least one limb
through landmine injuries.<p>
Landmines also have less direct effects. The medical costs of treating victims
are high. Victims are normally unable to work and produce as much as an
able-bodied member of society and often need regular medical check-ups.
Landmines also stop refugees from returning safely to their mother country,
prevent aid workers from coming in to help, and so stop countries recovering
from war and conflict.<p> 
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>What is being done to reduce the danger?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>Bomb experts, often funded by charities, are sent to the affected
countries to help local people find and disarm landmines. But this work is
expensive. On average it costs &#163;650, including the costs of training, to
disarm and remove one mine. What is really needed is for landmines to be
banned.<p>
Fifty-three countries, including the UK, say they support a global ban on the
production, export and use of landmines. But only 20 countries have completely
banned landmines, including Germany, Ireland, Jamaica and Mexico. The British
government has reserved the right to use landmines in "exceptional"
circumstances. It says it will ban landmines when everyone else does. If every
country had this attitude, landmines would never be banned.<p>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

 
 
 <!--HOME-->

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="pix/index-back.gif" ALT="Home" BORDER="0"></A></TD>


</TABLE>


</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
