</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Tusday, February 4, 1997 -->

</HEAD>

 <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="333333" LINK="660000">
<P><BR>
<!--TOP-->



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/edition.gif" ALT="First Edition" BORDER="0"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><br>
<!-- COPY-->

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10 WIDTH=550>

<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT COLSPAN=2><I><!--Date--><FONT COLOR="#336699">14 January 1997</FONT></I></TD>
</TR>
	
<TR>
	<TD COLSPAN=2><H1>Killer bacteria</H1><p>

<B>Emily Moore reveals the complexity of the E. coli bacteria, which can cause
severe food poisoning<p></TD></B>
</TR>

 


	<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP> Since 22 November last year, 16 people have died in Wishaw, Scotland, from E.
coli 0157 food poisoning, making this one of the most serious outbreaks of E.
coli food poisoning ever. Over 400 people have been affected. Last year 9,500
people were affected by an outbreak of E. coli 0157 food poisoning in Japan,
where 11 people died.<p></TD>

	
	<TD WIDTH=209 ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
	<IMG SRC="pix/bacteria1.jpeg" ALT="killer bacteria" WIDTH="209" HEIGHT="250" BORDER="0">
	<p>
<B>An E. coli bacterium uses its flagella to steer itself in the gut</I></B><br>
Science Photo Library
 </TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>



 

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"> <B><I>What is E. coli?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>E. coli's full name is Escherichia coli. It is a bacterium which
has always lived in the gut of most warm-blooded animals, including humans.
Most types of E. coli are harmless but some, such as E. coli 0157, can cause
severe food poisoning.<p>
E. coli seems a simple organism - we have three billion genes, but it has only
5,000. It is made of single cells, 10 times smaller than ours, with wispy hairs
called flagella. But it carries out complicated actions. The bacteria takes in
nutrients, grows and reproduces.  The E. coli rotate their flagella so they can
travel around the intestine.<p>
In 1982, the first E. coli 0157 food poisoning outbreak happened in the US.
Other types of E. coli had caused problems before but none as severe as 0157.
Most E. coli live in harmony with their host. Our intestines provide shelter
and nutrients and the E. coli helps us make vitamins to keep us healthy.
Research on the E. coli from 1950 onwards led to the discovery of genes.<p></TD>

</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>Why is E. coli 0157 so nasty?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>
E. coli 0157 can be very dangerous. This is because it makes two poisons (often
called toxins) which are similar to those made by the dysentery bacteria.
Scientists don't yet know how E. coli 0157 produced these toxins but think they
may have got the relevant genes to make them from other bacteria.<p>
</TD>

</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>How can we be poisoned by E. coli 0157?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>E. coli 0157 has been found in water, milk, yoghurt, cheese and apple juice.
But it is most common in undercooked meat, particularly meat products from
cows. E. coli 0157 lives mainly in cattle's intestines; cows are not poisoned
by E. coli 0157 themselves but they shed it in their dung (faeces). Poor
hygiene in slaughterhouses can contaminate meat. Other meat may be infected at
the butcher's shop, and is then eaten. The E. coli will double its numbers
every 20 minutes in warm conditions.<p>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>What does E. coli 0157 actually do to us to make us so ill?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>Once inside us, the bacteria stick to the walls of the colon, and
then start to multiply. They give off toxins which attack the lining of the
gut, affecting its ability to absorb water. Blood vessels can be damaged. In
bad cases, the toxins, carried by the blood, will go to the kidneys. They will
harm the kidneys' ability to both purify the blood and make sure we have the
right amount of water and salt in our body. In severe cases, this can lead to
kidney failure and death.<p> 
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>What are the symptoms of E.  coli 0157 food poisoning?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>Diarrhoea, often with blood in the faeces, severe stomach cramps,
vomiting - and in some cases even death. A severe attack can lead to long-term
problems with kidneys and blood pressure.<p>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>What is the treatment?</I></FONT></B></TD>

<TD>There is no special drug cure. Most sufferers recover naturally,
but the old, young or weak can be killed by E. coli 0157.<p>
</TD>
</TR>


<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>How can we stop it spreading?</I></FONT></B></TD>

<TD>The following rules should be followed at all times:
<UL TYPE=SQUARE>
 	<LI>No suspected infected food should be eaten. 
	<LI>Strict hygiene is important in farms, slaughterhouses, factories, butchers' shops, restaurants, in the kitchen and after using the toilet. 
 	<LI>Meat must be cooked properly until no pink flesh remains. The bacteria wil be killed by two minutes' cooking at 70&#176;. 
 	<LI>Washing hands after using the lavatory is vital. Under your fingernails is a great breeding ground for E. coli.
	<LI>E. coli 0157 can be passed on directly from live animals, especially calves - so take special care to wash your hands thoroughly after stroking animals at a zoo or farm.
</UL>
<p>
</TD>
</TR>



</TABLE>

 
  <!--HOME-->

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="pix/index-back.gif" ALT="Home" BORDER="0"></A></TD>


</TABLE>
 


</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
