</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>First Edition</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Tusday, February 4, 1997 -->

</HEAD>

 <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="333333" LINK="660000">
<P><BR>
<!--TOP-->



<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/edition.gif" ALT="First Edition" BORDER="0"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><br>
<!-- COPY-->




<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10 WIDTH=550>

<TR>
	<TD ALIGN=RIGHT COLSPAN=2><I><!--Date--><FONT COLOR="#336699">7 January 1997</FONT></I></TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT COLSPAN=2><H1>Beanz meanz genez</H1><p>

<B>We may be eating genetically engineered food without knowing it, reports Emily Moore<p></TD></B>
</TR>

 


	<TR>
	<TD> If you go to the supermarket today and buy bread, cakes or margarine, you will probably be buying food that contains soya products made from soya beans. In fact, 60 per cent of processed food contains soya. So far, two per cent of the American soya bean crop (which is where we get most of our soya from) has been genetically engineered by scientists.<p>

 
In the UK, food labels do not have to tell us when food has been genetically engineered. Many people and organisations all over the world are worried by this and believe we have a right to know  if we are eating genetically engineered foods, or gene foods, as they are often called.<p></TD>

	<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP><IMG SRC="pix/soyaseeds.jpeg" ALT="Seeds from soya bean plant" WIDTH="200" HEIGHT="110"><p>
<B>Seeds from the soya bean plant, also known as <I>Glycine max</I></B><br>
Science Photo Library
 </TD>
 </TR>
</TABLE>



 

<TABLE WIDTH=550 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10>
<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"> <B><I>What is genetic engineering?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>All living creatures are made up of cells. The DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid) in the cells contains genes, which are the coded instructions which make things develop in a particular way.  New techniques mean scientists can now pick out a specific gene responsible for a particular characteristic and copy it into another life form. This is known as genetic engineering.<p></TD>

</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>How have the soya beans been changed?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>
Scientists who work for the chemical company Monsanto have discovered a bacterium that can survive a heavy dose of their chemical herbicide  Roundup. The word &#147;herbicide&#148; means plant-killer. <p>
Farmers rely on herbicides to control weeds before planting and after harvesting. They can&#146;t use them while the crops are growing because that would kill the crops as well as the weeds. Monsanto scientists took a gene from the Roundup-resistant bacteria and added it to the soya plant. Now all genetically changed soya plants will not be killed by Roundup, so farmers who grow the beans will be able to use the herbicide while the crops are growing and in theory will be able to grow stronger and bigger crops.<p>
</TD>

</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>Have other foods been changed by scientists?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>Yes. Supermarkets in Britain already sell tomato paste from genetically altered tomatoes, called FlavrSavr, which are designed to ripen slowly, cutting out waste. Soon to come onto the market are maize (corn), rapeseed oil and potatoes. Many have been re-engineered to improve growth by making them more resistant to pests and disease or to certain herbicides.<p>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>

	<TD VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE="+1"><B><I>Doesn&#146;t genetic engineering mean we can produce more food to feed the hungry?</I></B></FONT></TD>
	<TD>Some people say yes. For example, much of the soil in India and Pakistan is too salty to grow good crops. Halophytes are plants that do survive well in salty environments. If scientists could take the right gene from a halophyte and put it into a basic food crop such as wheat, maybe these crops could survive in salty soils. But many organisations, such as Greenpeace, campaign against gene foods as the new answer. They point out that the reason why there are so many hungry people is poverty - not because of a lack of food being grown in the world. So far, genetic engineering has been used to help big businesses rather than small-scale farmers or you or I, the consumers.<p> 
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD VALIGN=TOP><B><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>Are gene foods harmful?</I></FONT></B></TD>
	<TD>Nobody knows. There could be all sorts of problems but we won&#146;t know until the damage has been done. At the moment there is no international agreement about what safety controls should apply. Some gene foods could cause allergic reactions in certain people.<p>  
There are also fears that gene foods could spread resistance to antibiotics in animal and human populations.  One of the most worrying possibilities is that a genetically changed species, such as the soya bean bred to be immune to Roundup, will breed with its wild relatives to produce &#147;superweeds&#148; - plants which are immune to herbicides. Or the new crop could become a weed itself. This could cause long-term changes to the plant world, as fragile and rare plants could be driven out of their habitat by invasive weeds. One thing we do know is that small changes in the environment can have dramatic and huge results<p>
</TD>
</TR>


</TABLE>

 
 <!--HOME-->

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="550">
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP><A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="pix/index-back.gif" ALT="Home" BORDER="0"></A></TD>


</TABLE>






