<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 BORDER=0 WIDTH=550>
<TR>
<TD><h1>The mark of true genius</h1><p>
<B>There's only one thing more challenging than writing an exam, and that's
composing the question<br>
By Richard John Roberts, University of East London</B>
<P>
<P>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<IMG SRC="../pix/headlect2.jpeg" WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="48" BORDER="0" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=0>

	
When it comes to exams, the deal between students and lecturers is a simple
one. We the students must revise the subject and complete the subsequent
examination. Our lecturers must compose the all-important exam questions and
then grade our papers.<p>

Students should not suppose that theirs is the harder part of the bargain.
Revision requires discipline - the exam is a straightforward matter of
interpretation and application. For the hard-pressed lecturer, however, the
challenge is stark. Not in the marking of the papers, which simply requires a
high boredom threshold and the ability to decipher illegible scrawl, but in the
composition of the exam questions themselves.<p>



<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=O CELLPADING=10>

<TR><TD><IMG SRC="../pix/lecturer.jpeg" WIDTH="250" HEIGHT="161" BORDER="0"></TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><B>Illustration by Claire Goble,<BR> Camberwell College of Arts</B><p></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>




<p>
Writing the exam question is to a lecturer what the party conference speech is
to a political leader. It is an opportunity to demonstrate what they are made
of; a showcase for their talents and reassurance of their continuing ability to
lead and inspire. The prose must be baroque yet retentive. The use of wit
serves a dual purpose: it imbues the students with a sense of warmth, and
reassures the lecturer of his/her ability to carve out an alternative career in
comedy should the short-term contract be terminated.<p>

However, humour alone is insufficient. The question must also possess a certain
literary quality before its author can be truly considered a genuine
all-rounder. The text must exude a fascinating, intricate spirit, it must
demonstrate an ineffable vocabulary and an indubitable creativity - indeed, it
must be the exam question that Ted Hughes would have written!<p>

This year we were treated to a classical feast in our law exam. We were asked
to "advise" and "discuss the liability of" Apollo, Zeus, Diomedes, Pedasos and
Laertes. Although fascinating in their Homeric milieu, they take on renewed
significance when used in questions about equal pay legislation.<p>

The exam question has become a work of art. A concomitant of the art form is
artistic pressure. Students would do well to be aware of this come the summer
exams. We are truly all in it together.</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE><P> <BR>
<!--END OF COPY-->



