<TR>
<TD><h1>Going gaga</h1><p>
<B>Postman Pat on the construction of homogeneity? Well, that's what you get
when you combine study and fatherhood<br>
By Mark Harvey, Open University</B>
<P>
<P>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>


<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=O CELLPADING=10>

<TR><TD><IMG SRC="../pix/baby2.jpeg" WIDTH="239" HEIGHT="170" BORDER="0"></TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><B>Illustration by Tim Balaam,<BR> Camberwell College of Arts</B><p></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


Camille, my eight-month-old daughter, is sitting bolt upright, earnestly
engrossed in the touching and tasting of the various objects within her orbit.
Two-year-old Holly is seemingly over her Christmas-induced confusion between
wrapping paper and ripping books - she scrutinises a page. What matter that it
is upside-down? I'm not going to correct her now. I've an oasis of calm in
which to study my course reader.<p>

Next instant I am leaping across the room to wrestle a piece of poo from her
lips which I'd imagined for a mistaken second was a Malteser. It must have
rolled across the room just 10 minutes earlier when Holly had proudly, but alas
clumsily, picked up her laden potty in a gesture of triumph.<p>

Such is my lot as combined 'house-husband' and Open University student. I find
that I literally have to "think on my feet", and have learnt the skill of
studying in short sprints.<p>

And, to add to the surreality of my situation, I find myself applying my
current intellectual concerns to what Nigel Planer has termed the "marshmallow
land" of baby culture. Postman Pat harks back to some profoundly reactionary
fantasy about organic community and hierarchical social relations - in the
'grown-up' world, Pat, with his cost-inefficient tendency to stand and chat,
would have been 'rationalised' long ago.<p>
<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=O CELLPADING=10>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../pix/baby.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="167" BORDER="0"></TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><B>Illustration by Alex Forsyth,<BR> Camberwell College of Arts</B><p></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

Several years ago, when studying at a 'terrestrial university', I could not
have imagined the strange days that lay ahead. Then I could scatter books
around my room and leave them there without a thought. A stray pen did not
constitute a lethal weapon to be jabbed up a younger sister's nostril. I could
stay up meeting deadlines with impunity. The difference now, of course, comes
in the form of two human alarm clocks who, when they wake up, are astonishingly
awake - whatever the time.<p>


And what a difference parenthood has made to me. Whereas in my life before
babies, my use of time was leisurely, sometimes lazy, now my approach as a
student is resourceful and I gain satisfaction from carving out a distinct
'space' that I claim as my own.<p>


Camille's bottom lip is beginning to tremble, Holly is poised to cack-handedly
attack my course reader with a crayon, Mrs Goggins and Postman Pat discuss the
construction of homogeneity within dominant ideological discourses, and...
Maltesers don't normally stick to your shoe, do they?
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE><P> <BR>
<!--END OF COPY-->



