<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 BORDER=0 WIDTH=550>
<TR>
<TD><h1>Emotional scars</h1><p>
<B>Seven months on, memories of the Manchester city centre bombing remain
painfully strong<br>
By Andrew Lowe, Bury College</B>
<P>
<P>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=O CELLPADING=10>

<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../pix/man.jpeg" WIDTH="127" HEIGHT="189" BORDER="0"></TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD><B>Illustration by C&#233;dric Gatillon,<BR>  Camberwell College of Arts</B><p></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
Last year I was working for Top Man in central Manchester. On the morning of 15
June, I got into work later than usual, due to a hangover. I fed Richard, my
manager, the usual "roads were busy" excuse. He didn't even raise his customary
disbelieving eyebrow as his attention was distracted by the unusual amount of
activity in the city centre. Time was dragging when suddenly we were
evacuated.<p>
<p>
I'm working in Bolton now. It's not too bad here, but it's not the same as the
city. There was a bomb scare last week at Marks and Spencer. It was petrifying,
even though I should have known what to expect. Once again, the stores in the
surrounding area were evacuated, but not ours - I couldn't understand why
not.<p>
<p>
I couldn't concentrate on work. The air felt thick and heavy in my throat and
my stomach was tight. A girl I work with said it would be a hoax. I wanted to
agree with her, but all I could reply was: "You'll be sorry." I thought about
it snowing ashes again.<p>






Sirens called people outside. They were told to get far away. I hunted for a
safe shelter somewhere in the shop, but I couldn't find one. I imagined the
flying glass that would be thrown at me.<p>

I stood in the kids' corner, sickened by the attracted onlookers, and waited
for the echoing boom to send a shuddering, shattering shower of glass through
the town. It never happened.<p>

I went into the centre of Manchester today. Seven months on and the area is
still in tatters. An eerie atmosphere cloaks the Arndale Centre; much of it
remains deserted. Most of the office windows have boards over them. The scale
of the devastation is still powerfully shocking. <p>

Each time I go into town the echoes seem to shake me a little less, but the
memories will remain strong.<p</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE><P> <BR>
<!--END OF COPY-->



