<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian School League Tables</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link=#000000 vlink=#000000 alink=#000000>
<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link=#000000 vlink=#000000 alink=#000000>
<A HREF="http://www.guardian.co.uk"><IMG SRC="http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/tables/pix/education.gif" ALT="The Guardian - Education" ALIGN=MIDDLE BORDER="0"></A><BR>
<br>
<font size="5"><b>The data you can't ignore</b></font><br>


<font size="3"><b>The Government's league tables won't tell parents everything they need 
to know about a school. But they do provide a solid basis for choice, 
writes John Carvel</b></font><P>
<font size=3>
Love them or hate them, the Government's league tables of secondary school exam performance have become a high point of the education year. Teachers may dislike the attempt to categorise their effectiveness by ranking raw exam results without taking account of the social, economic and educational background of the children with whom they work. Parents may know that there is more to education than a school's ability to get a certain percentage of its pupils above the particular benchmarks chosen by ministers to measure success.
<p>

But, rightly or wrongly, the tables fix the world's interpretation of a school's performance. They provide at least some basis of information to help parents choose a child's secondary school or decide on a move to college for A levels or vocational qualifications. They cannot be ignored. Any single set of statistics is arbitrary and the most popular indicator - the percentage of pupils getting at least five GCSEs at grade C or above - does not say everything there is to know about the quality of education provided.
<p>

There are dangers that over-concentration on this measure may encourage teachers to devote too much attention to raising the performance of middle-rankers above that key threshold at the expense of low-achievers for whom a clutch of lower grades may be essential for later development. That is why the Guardian provides as full a set of figures as possible. In a special supplement in the paper on November 20 and on this website, we have provided three measures of schools' performance at GCSE, so readers can assess performance throughout the range of achievement. We also include two columns of information on A level performance and four on vocational qualifications. This is backed up by data on school size and numbers of pupils with special needs.
<p>

The figures do not yet give information about how well schools are achieving, given the academic quality of their intake. A middle-ranking school in a deprived area may be doing a much better job than a high-ranker with socially privileged pupils. But the raw data still counts as one of the factors parents need to assess alongside a school's ethos, non-academic achievement and the quality of its staff.
<BR><BR>
<A HREF="mailto:rebecca@nml.guardian.co.uk">Comments to editor</A>

