<TABLE cellpadding=0 width=600 border=0>
<TR>
	<TD align=center colspan=3><a href=http://www.guardian.co.uk/ Target=_top><IMG SRC="pix/rae.gif" ALIGN=center BORDER="0" alt="The Guardian"></a><p></TD>
	
</TR>

<TR>
	<TD align=left colspan=3><b><center><h2>Councils reveal future of research funding</h2></center></b>

<p><b>The results of the Research Assessment Exercise are the most important announcement of the decade for universities and research institutes in the UK, writes Donald MacLeod. The Guardian has compiled two league tables that rank the research prowess of all 192 rated institutions</b>

<p>The research assessment determines funding for universities, institutes and colleges for the rest of the century and beyond. For many departments the verdict spells the end of research activity altogether - their staff will have to concentrate on teaching from now on.

<p>Ratings for 2,896 departments in 192 universities, institutes and colleges across the UK were announced on Thursday 19 December by four funding councils - the Higher Education Funding Council for England, the Scottish Higher Education Funding Council, the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales and the Department of Education Northern Ireland.

<p>The work of 55,893 academics was assessed by 60 subject panels in an exercise costing £2m. Work over the past four years (six years in humanities) was judged on a seven-point scale from 1 (virtually no research of national excellence) to 5* (research of international excellence in a majority of areas of activity).

<p>No single league table tells the whole story, so The Guardian has compiled two tables listing institution ratings and university ratings. Each table has two sections: one for researchers and one for staff members. Based on the average score for each researcher entered for consideration by the 60 subject panels, the results favour the institutions that have been more ruthlessly selective. Based on the average score per member of staff, the results favour those with strength in depth but show new universities with a handful of good research departments in an unflattering light.

<p>



</TD>
</TR>
 
