<html><!--created by: New Media Factory--><!--email:         paulh@mediafactory.co.uk--><!--date:          19Sep95--><!--file:            magazine.html--><head><title>Magazine Contents</title><link rev="made" href="mailto:paulh@mediafactory.co.uk"></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><p align=center><img src="images/contents.gif"></p><table width=100%><tr><td><a href="magazine.html"><img src="images/cun_mag.gif" border=0></a></td><td><p><font size=+2>Connect is a magazine about the Internet. It is part of a week-long series of pieces in which the Internet's potential has been explored by previous non-users - "net virgins" - who have visited the Guardian offices for a demonstration.  </font></p><p>They have done so because the Internet is currently the fastest growing media form. Around 30 million people utilise some part of its network of computers - and conservative estimates see this figure reaching 750 million by the year 2000. So what is it, this Internet? Essentially, it is made up of hundreds of small networks of computers which are connected by the international phone system. Each of these networks has at its core a computer containing information available for us to access. These small networks may be owned and staffed by universities, businesses, whoever. To discover their riches, we, as individual users, need first to connect with a local "service provider" using a modem to transfer information back and forwards from our own computers using the domestic phone system. This is our entry point onto the Internet.</p><p>Some people on the Internet use only electronic mail to communicate, others exchange ideas in global Usenet "newsgroups" dedicated to particular subjects - everything from  revolutionary theology, the works of Jane Austen, and the lyrics of the Grateful Dead (a favourite at Number 10, it is said). </p><p>Others still explore the many pages on the World Wide Web where electronic newspapers exist alongside pages devoted to Claudia Schiffer or Noam Chomsky. There are communiqu&eacute;s from the Zapatistas of Mexico and Burmese rebel organisations. There are speeches by Kenneth Clarke and film clips from upcoming Hollywood blockbusters. There are recipes and song lyrics, primates and Playmates, psychological tests and Tarot readings. Some is easy to find, some not so. Much is informative, much is rubbish. But the Internet is growing in every direction at more than 10 per cent per month. It is also becoming easier to use and navigate thanks to significant improvements in the friendliness of the technology required. When the Superhighway comes it will be as easy as watching TV. All is revealed in the language of the non-user.</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
