HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 16:54:29 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.3
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 3863
Last-modified: Wed, 30 Oct 1996 18:49:31 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>GWeekly</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC00OO" VLINK="#660000" ALINK="#66OO00" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<center><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="600"><TR><TD>
<center><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="590"><TR><TD>
</TD>
	
<TD colspan=2>
	<IMG SRC="http://www.guardian.co.uk/gweekly/pix/gweekly.gif" 
	HEIGHT=60 ALT="" ALIGN=right>
	
<P></TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
</TD>

<TD colspan=2>
<HR noshade size=1 width="590"><P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></center> 

<center> <TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="590">
<TR><TD> 


	<!--TEXT--><FONT SIZE="4"><B>The Guardian Weekly: A Brief History</B></FONT><P>

The Guardian Weekly was launched after the end of the first world war. Its first issue came out of July 4, 1919 with a purpose that remains true to this day: "We aim at presenting what is best and most interesting in the (Manchester) Guardian, what is most distinctive and independent of time, in a compact weekly form. We aim at securing that the readers of the weekly edition shall miss nothing of substance in its record and nothing of value in its interpretation of them."<P>
The Weekly performed a valuable service in Germany in the chaotic aftermath of the first world war, where it was seen as a bastion of free ideas by the intellectual Left of the ill-starred Weimar Republic. Likewise, after the defeat of 1945, the thirst among Germans for news untainted by fascist ideology was immense. The Guardian Weekly could not meet the demand from its Manchester presses, so it flew out the matrices from which the paper was printed to the Hamburg offices of Die Zeit. The circulation of this special German edition reached an astonishing 100,000.<P>
Now, 76 years after it was launched, the Guardian Weekly has become a truly international newspaper printed in five continents - North and South America, Europe, Australia and Africa, where it appears as an integral part of the <A HREF="http://www.mg.co.za/mg/">Mail & Guardian</A>, a liberal weekly paper published and printed in Johannesburg.
Within its covers the Guardian Weekly also carries up to eight pages of news and views from the Washington Post, the paper that exposed the Watergate scandal, and translations from Le Monde, the leading French daily.<P>
From a circulation of little more than 10,000 when it started, the Guardian Weekly now enjoys a print run all over the world of more than 100,000. That figure does not include the special 20-page Latin American edition that appears in four different countries.<P>
The Guardian Weekly has never set out to be merely a newspaper for expatriate Britons. It sets itself the highest standards of journalism and, from its base in London, strives to put all the week's events into an international perspective while championing human rights issues and the values of a free, democratic society.<p>
<P>
<I>If you wish to subscribe to the Guardian Weekly, <A HREF="mailto:gwwwsubs@guardian.co.uk">click here</A> and ask for details.</I> 

</tr></TABLE></center><BR clear=all><P>

