<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Farewell to armies of the old empires</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC00OO" VLINK="#660000" ALINK="#66OO00" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<center><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="600"><TR><TD>
<center><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="590"><TR><TD>
</TD>
	
<TD colspan=2>
	<IMG SRC="http://www.guardian.co.uk/gweekly/pix/gweekly.gif" 
	HEIGHT=60 ALT="" ALIGN=right>
	
<P></TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
</TD>

<TD colspan=2>
<HR noshade size=1 width="590"><P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></center> 

<center> <TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="590">
<TR><TD> 

<FONT SIZE="+3">Farewell to armies of the old empires</FONT><br>
<b> By Martin Woollacott </b><P>

	<!--TEXT-->
It was a situation in which a powerful army "showed itself unable to conquer an adversary who was practically unequipped and whose troops had in general received only rudimentary training. Impossible as this may appear, it is nevertheless a harsh reality that we must confront." So wrote a French colonel after the withdrawal from Indochina in the fifties.<p>
Chechenia is not Vietnam, yet the scene described - "blows aimed at empty space and a do-nothing existence in isolated outposts, until the illegal fighters one day concentrated their forces to win in a single onslaught" - could certainly have been used to describe the former country this month. It is a bad, sad fight in which the destiny of a small people is at stake.

	 <TABLE   align=right BORDER=0 CELLPADDING="10" CELLSPACING="10">
	<TR> <TD><P>
<IMG SRC="pix/checnia.jpeg" alt="gun" ALIGN=right></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD>	<B> 
A Chechen fighter points his rifle <BR>to the head of a Russian prisoner <BR>of war outside the <BR>Chechen captial of Grozny</B></TD>
</TR> </TABLE>

<P>
But the significance of the Chechen war lies, equally, in the opportunity it represents for Russia and the Russian army to join in the transition from unrealistic pretensions to a humbler appreciation of the uses of force that nearly all other big modern armies, China perhaps apart, have already made.
The armies of the West, in particular, were remade in Indochina, Algeria and in smaller conflicts in the Middle East, southeast Asia, Ireland and Cyprus, where they learnt hard lessons about what can and cannot be done in war and about the frequent irrelevance of superior firepower. The armed forces of India took a similar course in the limits of the possible in Sri Lanka, and continue to do so in Kashmir and the northeast. The Israeli army, too, recoiled from the consequences of its Lebanon adventure, and from the tasks of occupation in Gaza and the West Bank. In Latin America, armies have retreated, bruised and rueful, from the political responsibilities they had widely seized a generation ago.<p>
The general story is the same almost everywhere. Whether or not armed forces could effectively carry out the primary role of national defence, narrowly defined, has not usually been tested. But their claims to be able to hold territories whose inhabitants are reluctant citizens or subjects are frayed. So are their claims to be able to mount successful interventions beyond their own frontiers, even where, as in peacekeeping, there is an almost universal wish that they were able to do so. Some interventions work, many do not. And, in those countries where the army had imagined itself the guardian of the nation, with responsibility to ensure that the country stayed on the "right" path, the experience of political meddling has done much to erode that tradition.<p>
This retreat from military overconfidence, ambition and mysticism may, in the West, have gone too far, so that politicians and generals shirk tasks that are possible and that should be undertaken, Bosnia being the prime example. But in Russia, a generation behind the West in these matters, the wisdom of limits has not been fully learnt. The armed forces had, in Soviet days, an assured place in the coalition of ruling interests, a generous share of national resources and privileged connections with the worlds of industry and advanced science. They sat proudly, in eastern Europe, in Russia itself, on territory that the Red Army had won in war, and they compelled the West to make enormous and expensive military efforts.<p>
Now all this is in question, not only because of the present disarray in Chechenia, but because the revealed inadequacies of the armed forces cast doubt on the whole tradition, past as well as future. One doleful military correspondent for a Russian paper wrote after the early reverses in Grozny: "Our forces not only would not have made it to the English Channel; they would have been defeated before they even reached the Rhine."<p>
General Alexander Lebed, President Yeltsin's new security minister and the man charged with finding a Chechenia solution, is an enigma. Is he the leader who can take the Russian armed forces on that journey to wisdom, extracting them, in the first instance, from tasks of suppression and occupation in the Caucasus? Or is he a man whose impulses to reform are directed only to fashioning a more formidable instrument of power, so that a revived Russian army can continue to try to exercise the imperial, interventionist and spuriously national tasks that most other armies have wisely laid aside?<p>

Since the Chechen war began 20 months ago, two strands of criticism have intertwined: that of Russian military incompetence and that of Russian political foolishness. Yet these are very distinct arguments. It is an open question whether the war in Chechenia could be won with better commanders, better troops and a better strategy. There are others  who say that, even if Chechenia can be held, it is not worth doing so. Lebed said during the election campaign that Chechens should be allowed to choose in a referendum between staying in or leaving the Russian federation. But he coupled this with threats of cutting off all aid and co-operation, which suggests he hopes the Chechens might be frightened into choosing the federation or could be undermined if they did not do so.<p>
Lebed presumably now follows the man he chose as defence minister, General Igor Rodionov, in wanting a greatly reduced, more efficient army of 12 divisions. This is, not coincidentally, about the same size as the US army. That is no small ambition, and could also prove beyond Russia's capacities. But there is a modernisation of the mind that is more important than any upgrading of weapons, training or tactics. When de Gaulle took his Algerian decision he told a restive and partly mutinous officer corps: "The army serves no clan, no faction and no interest. The army serves France, and that is all." In retrospect the French army's withdrawal from Algeria, which ended its imperial role and closed an era, was an essential precondition for the emergence of the successful and dynamic France of the last 30 years. Chechenia is symbolic of the imperial temptation that must be put aside if Russia is to experience a similar renewal. It remains to be seen what kind of military moderniser General Lebed is.<P>


<P>


<I>If you wish to subscribe to the Guardian Weekly, <A HREF="mailto:gwwwsubs@guardian.co.uk">click here</A> and ask for details.</I> 

</tr></TABLE></center><BR clear=all><P>

