<HEAD>

<TITLE>Long horizons</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC00OO" VLINK="#660000" ALINK="#66OO00" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<center><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="580"><TR><TD>
<center><TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="570"><TR><TD>
</TD>
	
<TD colspan=2>
	<IMG SRC="http://www.guardian.co.uk/gweekly/pix/gweekly.gif" 
	HEIGHT=60 ALT="" ALIGN=right>
	
<P></TD></TR>

<TR><TD>
</TD>

<TD colspan=2>
<HR noshade size=1 width="590"><P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></center> 
<br><br>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="560">
<TR><TD> 

<FONT SIZE="+3">Long horizons</FONT><br>
<b>Nicholas Wroe</B><P>

        <!--TEXT-->






<P>Bruce Chatwins short and brilliant travel life has taken on almost mythic qualities. Nicholas Wroe on a new biography that picks through the facts and the fiction</TD></TR></TABLE></center>  



         <TABLE width=205 align=right BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=10 cellspacing=1>
        <TR><TD valign=top>
<IMG SRC="pix/chatwin.gif" alt="Bruce Chatwin " ALIGN=right> </TD>        
    <TR><td valign=bottom align=left><B>
Bruce Chatwin . . . gone to Patagonia<br> 
<B>Photo: Snowdon</B></TD>
</TR> </TABLE>

<p>A MONTH after he died in January 1989, a service of commemoration was held for Bruce Chatwin at the Greek Cathedral of St Sophia in west London. Black-robed, long-bearded priests swung censers under the high domes as representatives of smart society and literary London looked on in more or less bewilderment. "It was a very Chatwin-like event," recalls Susannah Clapp, his editor and now biographer. "To most of the congregation it was rather mysterious. Apart from the repetition of the word, 'Bruce', no one knew what was going on." The service was also of interest in another respect. As the congregation filed out they were confronted by a pack of news journalists. A fatwa had been pronounced in Tehran that morning and Salman Rushdie, a close friend of Chatwin, was ushered away into hiding.<p><p><p><p><p>To see this event as a fantastic coda to a life that had already taken on almost mythical status sounds too much like a neat line for a biographer or an obituarist. But in Chatwin's case it is true. "People sometimes talk about the commemoration service as if Bruce had manipulated it," laughs Clapp. But looking back over his 48 years, nothing could be more appropriate than for his passing to be marked by the peculiar consequences of ancient religion uneasily coming up against modern metropolitan literary chic.<p><p><p><p><p>Despite a relatively short time in the public eye - he was not published until he was 37 - his life as much as his work had become the stuff of legend. It was Chatwin as an 18-year-old working in Sotheby's who identified a Picasso gouache of a harlequin as a fake. It was Chatwin who woke up one morning to find himself blind and so taking his doctor's advice "to seek long horizons", set out for the deserts of Sudan. He announced his resignation from the Sunday Times in a telegram to his editor saying simply, "Gone to Patagonia". <p><p>And even during his final illnesses, while close friends knew he had Aids, he spoke publicly of a rare Chinese bone fungus contracted from a black egg eaten in Lijiang. Clapp's biography With Chatwin, is well placed to pick through the fact and the fiction of his life, as well as to appraise his work. They first met in 1976 when he arrived at the offices of his publisher with a leather haversack slung over his shoulder. He would go on, habitually, to carry a Mont Blanc pen and mole-skin notebooks, but that day he had only a French paperback, a pocket edition of the letters of Sydney Smith and a manuscript of In Patagonia.<p><p><p><p><p>This remarkable book changed travel writing for ever and made Chatwin's reputation as an author. His idiosyncratic study of that strange South American region almost entirely dispensed with the geography of the place, turning instead to a personal exploration of the byways and tangents of its history, legend and people. This "cubist" approach, as Chatwin appositely called it, allowed him to flag up many of the preoccupations - prehistoric animals, the Welsh, archaeology and indigenous peoples and their land - that he would develop in later works.<p><p><p><p><p>Clapp then worked on his debut novel, The Viceroy Of Ouidah, and remained friends with him as he published On The Black Hill, his novel about identical octogenarian twins living on a bleak Welsh farm, and The Songlines, his meditation on Australian Aboriginal beliefs which made the best-seller list. They also worked at the end of his life on the Booker shortlisted novel, Utz.<p><p>His work is difficult to classify. "It dangles between fact and fiction," says Clapp, which partly explains why On The Black Hill, a second novel, won the Whitbread best first novel award and why The Songlines was published as non-fiction in Britain and fiction in America.<p><p><p><p><p>When Chatwin died, Clapp was made a literary executor along with his widow Elizabeth and fellow travel writer Redmond O'Hanlon.<p><p><p><p><p>"I wanted With Chatwin to be a personal memoir that wouldn't disappear under a mass of documentary data," she explains. And while strong on the literary side - providing a fascinating insight into the editing process that pared down In Patagonia and opened up The Viceroy - her book is at its best on the man. She has gone some way to answering Rushdie's complaint that while he admired his work, the Chatwin in the books was not "the whole person he was when you met him". <p><p><p><p><p>Born in Sheffield in 1940 into a solidly middle class family, Bruce Chatwin was the eldest of three brothers. His family moved to the Birmingham suburbs - or "a clearing in the forest of Arden" as he called it - and he attended prep school before going to Marlborough College. There were early signs of the aesthete as his parents remember him in his sixth-form study, furnished with Italian oil paintings and a chaise-longue, being very much an "Edith Sitwell reader among a lot of Neville Shute fans".<p><p><p><p><p>He failed to get in to Oxford and was taken on by Sotheby's as a porter. This was a grander job than it sounds, and when not identifying fakes he was in Cap Ferat persuading Somerset Maugham to sell his collection of Matisses and Renoirs. He soon rose through the ranks and by the time he was in his mid-20s he had married a colleague, Elizabeth Chanler, and been offered a directorship. And then things got really interesting. As an employee of one of the world's great auction houses, he found himself appalled by objects and possessions. As a bisexual man, he found himself newly married.<p><p><p><p><p>Despite having "no problems" from his widow in writing or researching her book, Clapp is reluctant to talk about Chatwin's sexuality. She expresses apprehension that it may overshadow his literary achievements, but in the biography she quotes Howard Hodgkin's accusation that Chatwin would "flirt with man, woman or dog". She also reveals that one of the two men he had loved in his life was the designer Jasper Conran with whom he had once considered setting up home.<p><p><p><p><p>"This aspect has been made more of a problem for him than for other people," says Clapp. "Most writers don't go around saying, 'these are the details of my sex life, please put them on the front page of the paper'. He also wasn't really interested in sexual politics. There were reasons for that - not hurting people's feelings - but it's been portrayed as a moral duty that he should have come out, while in reality he was never in. People knew about it but he didn't write about it. In that sense he was quite old-fashioned."<p><p><p><p><p>Much has been made of the contents of his notebooks in this respect, now housed in the Bodleian Library. They are under embargo until 2010 and have been seen as part of some conspiracy involving his influential friends to protect his reputation. "They did excite a certain amount of fevered discussion after his death," claims Clapp. "But, in fact, he hardly wrote a confessional line in his life. It would have been very surprising if he had poured out his secret thoughts into a notebook, sobbing into a pillow every night. It just wasn't his way of going on." <p><p><p><p><p>And as for his status as the ultimate insider still under the protection of the literary and social mafia? "He started off as very much not part of the establishment," says Clapp, "that was the point of him. But he certainly had a weakness for toffs. He was glamorised by them, and glamour was a term of huge praise in his vocabulary. But that said, he didn't spend the whole time draped around these people. He was a writer who went away and wrote. Admittedly sometimes in the homes of these people, but often not." <p><p><p><p><p>Getting the work right and getting the life right. Clapp sees the influence of his much-vaunted "eye" - his uncanny ability to identify good from bad art - everywhere. "In his close attention to his appearance, to his flat, to his sentences." Equally, it was applied to the self-editing process that created the Chatwin myths during his lifetime and sustained them after his death. "But the really interesting thing," explains Clapp, "is that many of the stories are much truer than posthumous rumours would suggest." <p><p><p><p><p>Chatwin did own the king of Hawaii's bed-sheet, he did dine with Jackie Onassis and, to George Melly's astonishment, he had never heard of the Muppets. As an art expert, he suffered from afflictions of the eye, as a walker he had varicose veins. "What happened to his stories," explains Clapp, "was that they changed as they were retold. It was like a sauce being reduced and becoming more concentrate. Maybe he did himself a disservice by seeming to be more glamorous than he was, while all the time he was more glamorous than he thought."<p><p>

<p>
<br><br>

<P>
