<HR> 

<H3>"Ask the Astronaut" Videoconference Set for Tuesday, Jan. 21</H3>

<P> Space science enthusiasts are encouraged to go online with their
questions during videoconferences set for Tuesday, January 21. 

<P> On January 21 from 10:00-11:00 a.m. (CST), a videoconference on the
"Challenger Center Space Mission" will include Janel Badrina and James
Wooten of the Houston Museum of Natural Science. This conference is part
of the "Science Quest" series and will be carried on both satellite TV and
CU-SeeMe. 

<P> "Ask the Astronaut" is a videoconference that will be carried live via
CU-SeeMe transmission only on Tuesday, January 21, from 10:30-11:00 a.m.
(CST). It will feature NASA astronaut Don McMonagle, who will be online to
answer questions about living and working in space, and to demonstrate
equipment used by astronauts. The Web site is located at <A
HREF="http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/mcmonagl.html">http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/mcmonagl.html</A>

<P> For more information on the videoconferences, go to <A
HREF="http://space.rice.edu/hmns/dlt/video.html">http://space.rice.edu/hmns/dlt/video.html</A>

<P> The videoconferences are part of The <A
HREF="http://space.rice.edu/hmns/">Public Connection</A>, a project funded
by NASA's Digital Library Technology Program at Rice University. 
<BR>
<I>Posted January 20, 1997</I>

<A NAME="HL2"><H3>FIRST SHUTTLE MISSION OF 1997 UNDER WAY</H3>

<P>STS-81 launched as scheduled on January 12, 1997, at 3:27 a.m. CST
(09:27 GMT) at the beginning of a 7-minute window.  The shuttle Atlantis
carries more than 3,600 pounds of food, fuel, clothing, and other supplies
for transfer to the orbiting Russian Mir space station. Docking is
scheduled to occur at 9:53 p.m. CST Tuesday (03:53 GMT Wednesday).  Follow
the progress of this mission to Mir by checking out the newly redesigned
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://shuttle.nasa.gov/">Shuttle Web</A>.  The
Shuttle Web brings you all the details of the mission as they unfold. 
It's the only way to fly! 
<BR> 
<I>Posted January 14, 1997</I>

<A NAME="HL3"><H3>MASSIVE BLACK HOLES DWELL IN MOST GALAXIES, ACCORDING TO 
HUBBLE CENSUS</H3></A>
 
<P>Announcing the discovery of 3 black holes in 3 normal galaxies, an
international team of astronomers suggests that nearly all galaxies may
harbor supermassive black holes which once powered quasars (extremely
luminous nuclei of galaxies), but now are quiescent. 
 
<P>This conclusion is based on a census of 27 nearby galaxies carried out
by NASA's Hubble Space Telescope (HST) and ground-based telescopes in
Hawaii, which are being used to conduct a spectroscopic and photometric
survey of galaxies to find black holes which have consumed the mass of
millions of Sun-like stars. 
 
<P>For images and more information, go to the Space Telescope Science
Institute's (STScI) <A
HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://www.stsci.edu/pubinfo/PR/97/01.html">press
release</A>. 
<BR> 
<I>Posted January 14, 1997</I>

