<head>
   <title>Planes</title>
   <meta name="Author" content="">
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/observe/exhibit/planes/graphics/backgrnd.gif">
 

<center>


<IMG SRC="/observe/exhibit/planes/graphics/final-header2.gif"
ALT="[header-logo]"> <p>

<IMG SRC="/observe/exhibit/planes/graphics/mhead1.gif" 
ALT="[header-logo]">
</center>
<BR>

<p>Planes and flying are fun.</p>

<p>During take-off, we get pushed back into our seats like on a roller 
coaster. From the air, buildings, trees, and cars are so small they look 
like toys; highways and railroad tracks are mere lines across the land. 
After we land at our destination, new adventures await us.</p>

<p>If you have ever flown, you may remember these feelings. But have you 
ever wondered, how planes stay up in the air? For the answer, click 
on:</p>

<p><b><font SIZE=+1><A HREF="planes_1a.html">How Do Planes 
Fly?</a></font></b> </p>
<br>
<p>Want to get answers to other questions about planes and flying? Want
to find out how planes and flying are used in education? Go to these 
NASA-sponsored
Web sites designed especially for kids and their teachers: </p>

<p><b><font SIZE=+1><A HREF="planes_2a.html">Planes, Flying, and K-12
Education</a></font></b></p>

<p><b><font SIZE=+1> <A HREF="planes_3.html">NASAs <i>Internet in the
Classroom</i></a></font> </b>
<br></p>


<CENTER>

<A HREF="/observe/exhibit/exhibit.html">
<IMG BORDER="0" SRC="/observe/exhibit/planes/graphics/exit.gif"
ALT="[EXIT]"></a> 

<A HREF="planes_1a.html">
<IMG BORDER="0" SRC="/observe/exhibit/planes/graphics/next.gif" 
ALT="[FORWARD]"></a>
