<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Observatorium - Million Man March Exhibit</TITLE>

<META name="description" content=
	"This Observatorium Exhibit examines how remote sensing was used
to improve estimates of attendence at the Million Man March held
in Washington DC in October of 1995.">

<META name="keywords" contents
	"Million Man March, remote sensing, counting, crowd estimate,
attendence, photomap, orthophoto, aerial photography, NASA IITA">

</HEAD>

<BODY background="graphics/one.gif">

<P>
<CENTER><IMG src="graphics/march.gif" border=0 ALT="[Million Man March
logo]" height=140 width=453 align=bottom>
<BR>
<IMG src="graphics/number.gif" border=0 ALT="[numbers]" height=28 width=459
align=bottom>
<BR>

<P>
</CENTER><CENTER>
<P>
A controversy developed after the <I>Million Man March</I> in
Washington, DC, in October 1995. The National Park Service announced
that 400,000 people participated in the event, but organizers
called that figure a &quot;gross underestimate.&quot; Could remote
sensing resolve the dispute? </CENTER><CENTER>
<P>
Dr. Farouk El-Baz, director of the Boston University (BU) Remote
Sensing Lab, answered with a resounding &quot;Yes!&quot; He knew
he could &quot;count&quot;on remote sensing. </CENTER><CENTER>
<P>
Counting objects on aerial photographs has long been an application
of remotely-sensed imagery. For example, foresters routinely count
trees, geologists count sand dunes, agronomists count hay bales
and cows, planners count houses and cars, and biologists count
birds. Very often a grid is placed over the images and objects
are either directly counted or estimated for each grid square.
</CENTER><CENTER>
<P>
<IMG src="graphics/birds.gif" border=0 ALT="[migrating birds]" height=207
width=324 align=bottom>
<BR>
<IMG src="graphics/text.gif" border=0 ALT="[migrating birds captions]" height=99 width=311 align=bottom>
<BR>
<BR>
<A href="/observe/exhibit/exhibit.html"><IMG src="graphics/exit.gif"
alt="[Exit]" border=0 height=72 width=91 align=bottom></A>
<A href="march_2.html"><IMG src="graphics/next.gif" alt="[Next]" border=0
height=72 width=91 align=bottom></A>
</CENTER>

<HR>


