<HEAD>

<TITLE>UBAR</TITLE>

<META name="description" content=
        "This Shockwave enhanced Observatorium Exhibit describes how
hard work, dedicated research, and remote sensing technology was used
to search for an ancient lost fortress.">

<META name="keywords" content=
        "shockwave, marcomedia, director, remote sensing, archaeology,
Ubar, Oman, Arabian Peninsula, Empty Quarter, Ash Shisr, Landsat TM, radar
image, SPOT, NASA IITA">

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#e4d377" ALINK="#bf6c00" VLINK="#dd0456" 
LINK="#b37103">

<P>

<CENTER>

<IMG SRC=" graphics/pg1_1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM" ALT="[The Observatorium]"><BR>
<EMBED SRC="graphics/thndr.dcr" WIDTH=320 HEIGHT=167 PALETTE=background>
</EMBED>
<NOEMBED> <IMG SRC=" graphics/pg1_2.gif" ALT="[Ubar logo]" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> 
<BR>
<BR>
</NOEMBED>


<P>The legend goes like this: Ubar, a rich and fabulous trading
center of ancient Arabia rose out of the desert and then mysteriously vanished
back into the sands. References to Ubar in the Koran, the Arabian Nights,
and countless Bedouin tales told around desert campfires have captivated
the imaginations of explorers and archaeologists. But all searches were
fruitless and the city remained lost.

<P>Now, centuries after Ubar's disappearance, a combination of hard work,
dedicated research, and remote sensing technology has perhaps unraveled
this ancient mystery. 
<BR>

<HR SIZE="5" WIDTH="70%">

<BR>
<IMG SRC=" graphics/pg1_3.gif" ALT="[Navigation Through This Exhibit]" 
ALIGN="MIDDLE">


<P>To get the most out of this exhibit we recommend that you read these
Web pages in order. The easiest way to do this is to use the navigation
buttons. Click on the &quot;NEXT&quot; button to advance through the
exhibit. The &quot;BACK&quot; button will take you to the previous page.
To return to the Exhibit Hall choose the &quot;EXIT&quot; button. 


<P>


<IMG SRC="graphics/pg1_4.gif" ALT="[Back]" ALIGN="MIDDLE">
