<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Observatorium - Data at Work News Briefs</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> 

<CENTER>

<IMG SRC="/observe/graphics/briefs_header.gif" 
ALT="Data At Work News Briefs - The Observatorium">
<BR>
<A HREF="/observe/graphics/buttonb.map">
<IMG BORDER="0"  SRC="/observe/graphics/buttonb.gif" 
ALT="Navigation Links" ISMAP></A>
</CENTER>

<BR>
<IMG SRC="graphics/finger.gif" ALT="Mini-Camera on a Fingertip" ALIGN="LEFT">
<H2>Camera On a Chip</H2>

<P>NASA has developed a new imaging system that is virtually a camera on a
chip.  The figure shows the actual size of the device.  Called the
CMOS Active Pixel Sensor (APS), the new system uses complementary
metal-oxide semiconductor (CMOS) technology.  Most calculator and
computer chips use CMOS technology.  It is well understood
and supported by worldwide research and development.</P>

<P>Current space imaging systems, video camcorders, and electronic imaging
instruments use charge-coupled devices, or CCDs.  CCDs require much more
power than the five volts needed to operate the APS.  The APS has an
electronic shutter, as well as timing and control circuits built into its
chip so that the camera can connect directly to a recorder.  It can also
connect to a computer for display.  This reduces the number of additional
components the camera needs and makes it much more compact than a 
CCD-based camera. </P>

<P>The APS uses standard CMOS industrial processes.  It can be manufactured
for a fraction of the cost of a comparable CCD imager.  In addition to
its use on future space missions, the APS will find potential uses in home
security systems, personal electronic cameras, manufacturing inspection,
and dental x-ray imaging.  Several companies are interested in licensing
the APS for commercial use.</P>

<P>To learn more about the CMOS APS, check out the APS homepage at:</P>

<UL>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://mishkin.jpl.nasa.gov/APS_Page">
http://mishkin.jpl.nasa.gov/APS_Page</A>  
</UL>

<P>To learn more about the Jet Propulsion Laboratory's Center for Space
Microelectronics Technology, where the APS was developed, check out their
homepage at:</P>

<UL>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://mishkin.jpl.nasa.gov/">
http://mishkin.jpl.nasa.gov/</A> 
</UL>

<P>You can find the NASA press release describing the CMOS APS at:

<UL>
<A 
HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?ftp://ftp.hq.nasa.gov/pub/pao/pressrel/1995/95-98.txt">
ftp://ftp.hq.nasa.gov/pub/pao/pressrel/1995/95-98.txt</A>
</UL> 


