<H2>Data Compression</H2>
</CENTER>

<P>New NASA earth and space observing missions are being designed that
will generate as much as 300 megabytes of data per second.  Moving and
storing this much data is a real challenge for data system designers. 
Closer to home, you may have experienced the frustration of downloading a
large image through a modem, where a 1 megabyte file can take 15 minutes
or more to be received.</P>

<P>Communication and information theory researchers are working on
ways to use data compression to minimize the number of bits (and hence
the time) required to transmit files.</P>

<P>Check out the resources below for information on some of the latest 
research in this fast-moving and exciting area.</B>

 <HR>
<DL>
<DT><B>Compression and Progressive Transmission of Digital Images</B>
<DD>
<!--#include
virtual="/observe/techpark/resources/short_abstracts/prog_x_short.html"-->
[<A HREF="infodocs/prog_x_sh.html">Tell Me More</A>] 
[<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://www.sal.wisc.edu/~jwp/can.html">Go There 
Now</A>] <BR>
</DL>

<DL>
<DT><B>Retrieval of Digital Images by Means of Content Search</B>
<DD>
<!--#include
virtual="/observe/techpark/resources/short_abstracts/ibm_short.html"-->
[<A HREF="infodocs/ibm_sh.html">Tell Me More</A>]
<BR>
</DL>

<!--#include virtual="/observe/includes/button_bar.html"-->

