<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Observatorium - Internet Education Resources</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"> 

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/observe/graphics/ed_header.gif" ALT="EDUCATION CENTER">
<BR>

<A HREF="/observe/graphics/buttonb.map">
<IMG BORDER="0" SRC="/observe/graphics/buttonb.gif"
ALT="Navigation Links" ISMAP></A>
<BR>
</CENTER>

<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="graphics/internet_ed.gif" ALT="Internet Education Resources">
</CENTER>

<P>The sites below provide good starting points for learning more about 
information infrastructure, on-line interactive projects, grants, and the 
many ways that the Internet can be used to disseminate information.
</P>

<UL>

<LI>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://k12.cnidr.org/"><B>CNIDR</B></A>
<BR>
There are several WWW servers hosted at the Center for Networked Information
Discovery and Retrieval (CNIDR). Resources of interest include:
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://k12.cnidr.org:90/">EdWeb</A> and the
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://k12.cnidr.org/gsh/gshwelcome.html">Global SchoolHouse
Project</A>. CNIDR is a  three-year award in the form of a Cooperative
Agreement between the National Science Foundation and the Microelectronics
Center of North Carolina (MCNC), Research Triangle Park, North Carolina.
<BR>
<BR>

<LI>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://www.globe.gov/"><B>The GLOBE Program</B></A>
<BR>
Global Learning and Observations to Benefit the Environment (GLOBE) is an
excellent example of a collaborative worldwide Internet project. It is a
worldwide network of students, teachers, and scientists working together
to study and understand the global environment. 
<BR> 
<BR>

<LI>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://www.nasa.gov/"><B>NASA On-Line</B></A>
<BR>
NASA World Wide Web (WWW) Information Services. From here you can visit the
NASA field centers, see NASA on-line resources and NASA education programs.
<BR>
<BR>
     
<LI><A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/"><B>NASA's Quest Program</B></A>
<BR>

NASA's K-12 Internet Initiative is an excellent resource for schools,
teachers and students. It provides information about technology plans and 
information infrastructure required to get schools connected to the Internet,
<A  HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://www.rice.edu/armadillo/acceptable.html">Acceptable
Use Policies</A>, on-line interactive projects, <A 
HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://quest.arc.nasa.gov/online.html"> schools with Internet
connectivity</A>, grants, and much more. 

<BR>
<BR>

<LI>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://spacelink.msfc.nasa.gov/"><B>NASA Spacelink</B></A>
<BR>
Spacelink provides a wide range of educational and instructional materials.  
It offers a teacher resource center, electronic library, the latest NASA 
happenings, and links to more resources. <BR>
<BR>

<LI>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://www.nceet.snre.umich.edu/"><B>NCEET</B></A>
<BR>
The National Consortium for Environmental Education and Training (NCEET)
provides resources for environmental education on the Internet.
<BR>
<BR>

<LI>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://sln.fi.edu/tfi/sln/sln.html">
<B>The Science Learning Network</B></A>
<BR>
The Science Learning Network (SLN) Alliance, funded by the National Science
Foundation and Unisys Corporation, consists of six science centers in the
United States aimed at providing Internet science resources. One of the
exhibits from the <A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://sln.fi.edu/tfi/">Franklin
Institute Science Museum</A> in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, is a
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://sln.fi.edu/tfi/hotlists/kid-sci.html">science page</A> 
done by kids. Check it out.  
<BR>
<BR>

<LI>
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://www.ed.gov/"><B>U.S. Department of Education</B></A>
<BR>
The U.S. Department of Education provides valuable information to educators
at all levels on legislative issues, funding, educational resources,  and
much more.
<BR>
<BR> 

<LI><A HREF="/cgi-bin/log.pl?http://web66.coled.umn.edu/"><B>Web66</B></A>
<BR>
Web66 provides educators with information on how to set up
Internet servers, how to link to other K-12 servers and how to find
education resources on the Net. This project is an extension of the Hillside
Elementary cooperative project with the University of Minnesota College of
Education and the Center for Applied Research and Educational Improvement.
<BR>
<BR>

</UL>

<!--#include virtual="/observe/includes/button_bar.html"-->

<HR>

<!--#include virtual="/observe/includes/footer.html"-->

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
